<html>
<head>
   <title>AIDS Came to My House</title>
   <meta name="Author" content="Jonathan W. Pait">
   <meta name="GENERATOR" content="Mozilla/2.0GoldB1 (Win32)">
</head>
<body text="#000000" bgcolor="#00FFFF" link="#0000EE" vlink="#551A8B" alink="#FF0000">

<div align=center><CENTER><p><font SIZE=+3>When Aids Came to My House</font>
<br><i>by Jared Martin Thacker</i></p></CENTER></div>

<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Aids and HIV are terms that almost everyone
in this country has come to associate with sinful lifestyles. &nbsp;But in the
case of my family, no sin was committed. &nbsp;God decided, in His Master Plan,
to use a deadly virus for His glory and to teach many people, as well as
members of my family, how facing death could bring new life and a new way
to love.</p>

<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In 1984, my parents and my sister contracted
the disease known as HIV from a blood transfusion given to my mother when
my sister was born. &nbsp;This is my story.</p>

<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I'm what you might call your normal 16-year-old
Christian teenager. &nbsp;I lived what I thought to be a mormal life. &nbsp;But, all
that was to change dramatically in January of 1993. &nbsp;I remember talking
to my older sister. &nbsp;We both realized that for the past couple of years
some very strange things had occurred in our family. &nbsp;My parents fought
more that &quot;usual.&quot; &nbsp;My dad had almost died of cancer in 1990,
and my mother had hinted at a hidden health problem that was affecting
her and my father. &nbsp;I was very angry that my parents would not tell me the
truth. &nbsp;So that night, in January of 1993, I was determined to find out
what was going on.</p>

<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;My mother told my father it was time that
I knew the truth. &nbsp;So that night we went for a drive, and my father told
me what was going on. &nbsp;AIDS had &quot;come home&quot; to me. &nbsp;I was devastated,
to say the least. &nbsp;I didn't know what to do. &nbsp;It was the &quot;family secret,&quot;
so I could tell no one. &nbsp;So I went on in silence.</p>

<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In April of that year, after my sister
had tonsillitis for several months, my parents decided to get her tested. &nbsp;
They knew that because she had breast fed from my mother after mom had
gotten the tainted blood transfusion there was a good chance that she was
HIV positive as well. &nbsp;The test showed that Sarah was indeed HIV positive.</p>

<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I didn't know what to feel. &nbsp;First there
was anger. &nbsp;My dad is not only publisher of Today's Christian Teen, he also
has a black belt in Karate, and he had taught me a few things. &nbsp;We had some
wood in the basement, and I remember sitting on the floor with my knuckles
bleeding and broken wood all around me and not feeling the pain, only rage. &nbsp;
I wasn't mad at God. &nbsp;I wasn't angry at my parents. &nbsp;I was just angry that
this had happened to me and my parents and my precious little sister.</p>

<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Next came depression. &nbsp;I was depressed
all of the time, but I had to go on. &nbsp;One day, I decided I could not. &nbsp;So
I got one of my dad's guns, put it to my head, and pulled the trigger. &nbsp;
But, the gun didn't go off. &nbsp;I heard the words of my mother echoing in my
head, &quot;God's got something special for you to do.&quot; So I put the
gun down and went on. &nbsp;Later on I tried jumping from a moving car and other
ways to end my life, but God wasn't finished with me yet.</p>

<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Next came some level of acceptance. &nbsp;I
have learned to live with the &quot;new normal.&quot; &nbsp;It wasn't easy. &nbsp;But,
after several battles with depression, I have learned how to thank God
for this disease. &nbsp;I still cry sometimes, but I still thank God for the
opportunities this disease has given me. &nbsp;I have met a lot of dear friends
thanks to AIDS, but this disease has also taken some very close friends
of mine. &nbsp;The legacy of faith those friends have left behind will affect
me forever.</p>

<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;I believe that God can do miracles. &nbsp;God
can heal anyone if He chooses, but that same God also gives the strength
to walk in our infirmities. &nbsp;God has done a miracle in my life. &nbsp;No, He hasn't
healed my parents, but He has given me the strength to walk on. &nbsp;He has
also taught me how to love -- to love regardless of someone's affliction
-- to look beyond their problems and see their need for a Savior. &nbsp;He has
shown me that in this life our sole mission as Christians is to love our
God, take care of our families, and to help others. </p>

<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Now you must ask yourself, &quot;What
will I do when AIDS 'comes home' to me?&quot; &nbsp;Maybe it won't be you or
your family, but maybe it will be someone you know. &nbsp;In the next ten years
I believe everyone of us will be affected by this disease, so you must
decide how you will react. &nbsp;Will you show those who are hurting and dying
the love and compassion that God has shown to us through Christ Jesus? &nbsp;
Or will you turn them away?</p>

<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;What will you do when you are faced with
the temptation of premarital sex or illicit drug use? &nbsp;(These are the two
key ways this disease is transmitted.) &nbsp;Will you stand for what is right,
or will you bow to the temptation? &nbsp;Will you live for you, or will you live
for Him? &nbsp;The choice is yours; but remember whatever choice you make, to
choose wrongly may indeed end your life.</p>

<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The best way to deal with AIDS is to not
have to deal with it al all. &nbsp;Do right. &nbsp;When AIDS comes home, it is not
a pretty sight. &nbsp;Especially when it affects those you love.&nbsp;
<br>
<hr   width="100%"></p>

<div align=center><p><img src="note.gif" alt="For more information call (610) 372-1111" hspace=5 vspace=5 border=0  height=210 width =160 align=right ><CENTER><b>Jared
Thacker Home with the Lord.</b></p></CENTER></div>

<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;After a 30 hour bout with pneumoccal meningitis,
a bacterial form of meningitis, the autor of this article, Jared Thacker,
age 16, died in a Reading Pennsylvania hospital on Friday Novermber 24. &nbsp;
While Jared was not infected with HIV, he had his spleen removed as a child
after an accident. &nbsp;This reduced his natural immunity.&nbsp;
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&quot;Jared's death adds to the tragedy of
what our family has already been through but we know the Lord is going
to use his life and death for His glory.&quot; said his father, <I>Today's
Christian Teen</I> Publisher, Jerry Thacker. &quot;Jared was greatly loved. &nbsp;
He will be greatly missed.&quot;
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;More than 200 people attended the grave
side service for Jared, and over 700 people were present for a memorial
service held November 28th. &nbsp;Several teens have already made professions
of faith in the aftermath of Jared's death.
<br></p>

<hr>
<CENTER><b>| <a HREF="http://www.bju.edu/">BJU</a>  | <a HREF="index.html"><i>Opening Page</i></a> | <a HREF="tct.html"><i>Today's Christian Teen</i></a>
| <a HREF="tcp.html"><I>Today's Christian Preacher</I></a> | <a HREF="order.html">ORDER</a>
| </b>

<p><b><i>&copy; Scepter Publications
<br>All Rights Reserved.</i></b></p>
</body>
</html>
