<DOCHDR>
http://www.bju.edu:80/resources/teen/story2.html 198.69.96.10 19970118034436 text/html 7183
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Communications/1.12
Date: Saturday, 18-Jan-97 02:43:22 GMT
Last-modified: Monday, 19-Aug-96 20:35:59 GMT
Content-length: 6992
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
   <title>AIDS Came to My House</title>
   <meta name="Author" content="Jonathan W. Pait">
   <meta name="GENERATOR" content="Mozilla/2.0GoldB1 (Win32)">
</head>
<body text="#000000" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#0000EE" vlink="#551A8B" alink="#FF0000">

<center><i><b><font SIZE=+3>Getting Along with Difficult People 
<br></font></b>by Pastor Jerry Dean</i></center>

<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<p>Fred Jackson is not an imposing figure. &nbsp;Early fifties. &nbsp;Graying
around the ears. &nbsp;Balding on the top. &nbsp;Slight of build. &nbsp;
Extremely quiet. &nbsp;Unassuming.&nbsp;&nbsp;Good family.&nbsp;&nbsp;But,
an absolute terror in a deacon's meeting! &nbsp;A real Jekyll and Hyde.

<br>
<br>Then there's Bruce Overman, one of the pillars of the congregation,
who has a differing opinion on everything. &nbsp;If he had been advising
the Lord at the close of the sixth day, Creation would have taken another
week! 
<br>
<br>Also, we could not forget Helen Foran who, for some reason, just does
not like you. &nbsp;She was in the church when you came, but left and joined
another fellowship about a year later. &nbsp;Weekly, you are confronted
by members and non-members alike who ask you pointedly about things you
did and said that you never did or said! &nbsp;When the source is uncovered,
it is always Helen Foran. 
<br>
<br>It is a strange assortment of people a pastor is called upon to get
along with, isn't it? &nbsp;No matter where you serve, what size your congregation,
rural or inner-city, the shepherd is always called upon to guide a weird
bunch of sheep. 
<br>
<br>Far too often, it is not major doctrinal, moral, or spiritual difficulties
that send the pastor packing. &nbsp;Rather, it is the frustration, irritation
and pressure of handling and coping with the uniqueness of those to whom
they minister. &nbsp;How can the preacher avoid those feelings that often
bring about an early departure to another greener field? 
<br>
<br>A number of years ago, I came across a pretty well-known book entitled
<i>Irregular People</i>. &nbsp;The basic premise of the book is that everyone
has at least one someone in his life he would classify as irregular. &nbsp;That
person who just doesn't follow standard operating procedure. &nbsp;That
person who simply drives you nuts with what they do and say and how they
think. &nbsp;The person you cannot, for the life of you, understand &quot;where
they are coming from.&quot; &nbsp;I am certain you are thinking of two
or three irregulars right now. 
<br>
<br>However, the expanded premise of the book was, &quot;everyone is someone
else's irregular person.&quot; &nbsp;I balked at that idea to begin with.&nbsp;
That certainly could not mean me! &nbsp;I am quite normal in my responses
and attitudes. &nbsp;I have no strange quirks or idiosyncrasies that would
qualify me for the irregular rack. &nbsp;But, as I&nbsp;contemplated and
observed myself, I began to understand the truth of the statement 
<br>
<br>You preacher friend, are an &quot;odd bird&quot; yourself! &nbsp;Don't
believe me? &nbsp;Ask you wife. &nbsp;If she is honest, she will reveal
to you strange habits and thought processes that are totally beyond her
ability to comprehend. &nbsp;She has learned to cope beautifully, and you
never knew it! 
<br>
<br>May I&nbsp;share a small personal experience? &nbsp;The wall plug on
our small television had been pulled out. &nbsp;Naked wires were exposed.
&nbsp;I knew how to fix that. &nbsp;Merely purchase a new plug from any
hardware store. &nbsp;Attach it properly to the wire and the problem is
solved. &nbsp;The cost is a couple of bucks at best. &nbsp;Time to do the
job? &nbsp;Approximately five minutes. However, instead of repairing the
plug, I&nbsp;stuck the two naked wires into the socket. &nbsp;The TV worked
fine. &nbsp;That was okay for me, but when my wife returned home one day
in my absence, my ten-year-old was attempting to watch TV just like her
dad had taught her. &nbsp;As she inserted the wires, fire shot from the
outlet just as Mom entered the room. &nbsp;To say they were frightened
is an understatement! 
<br>
<br>When my wife asked me (in her kindest, most understanding tone) why
I&nbsp;had not repaired the plug properly, and did I not understand the
danger to the children and our home, I had no good explanation, although
I&nbsp;did try! 
<br>
<br>My point is, I&nbsp;did something pretty dumb and foolish, and I could
not explain why.&nbsp; I just did it.&nbsp; Unfortunately, there are many,
many things my wife, secretary, and parishioners &quot;put up with&quot;
in my life over the many years.&nbsp; Realizing my own weaknesses helps
me to be more accepting of their irregular ways of thinking and acting.

<br>
<br>Further, to get along with difficult people requires that I&nbsp;reevaluate
my calling. &nbsp;Did the Lord call me to the ministry? &nbsp;Did He call
me to this place? &nbsp;Has that changed?&nbsp; Nearly every man of God
in the Scripture dealt with extremely difficult sitrations and people.
&nbsp;Yet, they maintained their focus on God and remained faithful to
His calling.&nbsp; Remember, irregulars are waiting at the next church,
too! 
<br>
<br>Finally, to get along with difficult people often requires that we
be confrontational. &nbsp;Not in a belligerent, aggressive way, but merely
holding people accountable for their words and deeds. &nbsp;If you have
heard that Brother So &amp; So has said something about you that is not
true, go and ask him if he said it. &nbsp;If he says no, invite him to
go with you to see the third person whose report Brother So &amp; So says
is untrue.&nbsp; If he refuses to go with you, perhaps you have uncoverd
his problem. &nbsp;Or, as the two of you confront the other, his false
statements can be unearthed. 
<br>
<br>If this procedure is followed regularly, your people will soon get
the idea that folks around the church are held accountable for what they
say or do, so they had better be careful of the words they utter and the
deeds they do. 
<br>
<br>God uses people--weak, sinful, difficult people--to do in our lives
what cannot be done any other way.&nbsp; As we yield to the Spirit of God
and submit ourselves in obedience to His Word, we will observe groweth
in our lives as believers. &nbsp;And as the preacher grows and matures
in the faith, he becomes a more consistent, understanding, patient, loving
shepherd of the flock to which God has called him. 
<br>
<hr     width="100%"></p>

<center><b>| <a HREF="http://www.bju.edu/">BJU</a> | <i><a HREF="index.html">Opening
Page</a></i> | <i><a HREF="tct.html">Today's Christian Teen</a></i> | <i><a HREF="tcp.html">Today's
Christian Preacher</a></i> | <a HREF="order.html">ORDER</a> | </b></center>

