<HEAD>
<TITLE>
TestBanks: Something You Can 'Bank' On
</TITLE>
<LINK REV="OWNER" HREF="mailto:bjup@bju.edu">
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<A NAME = "TOP"></A>
<H1 ALIGN = CENTER>
TestBanks: Something You Can 'Bank' On
</H1>

<P ALIGN = CENTER>
[ <A HREF = "contents.html">Home School Helper Contents</A>
| <A HREF = "../resource.html">On-Line Resources</A>
| <A HREF = "../../home.html">BJUP Home Page</A> ]
</P>

<HR>

<P>Test time arouses more fear and frustration for both child and
parents than any other classroom event.  Even a well-prepared
student often misreads  questions or faces items that were not in
his notes or in the book.  You as a teacher must spend long hours
to produce and grade each test for each child.  You must make
sure that every questions is clear, that each one covers
something to which your child has been introduced, and that the
test as a whole reflects what you have emphasized in the course.

<P>BJU Press TestBanks can alleviate some of that frustration for
both parties.  For you, the teacher, half of the time in
developing a good test is spent in generating original and
accurate test questions-items that correctly assess the ability
being tested but are also imaginative in wording (not "Bob and
Jane" in every setting).

<P>For your child, tests can be frustrating not because he does not
know the material but because he cannot understand the question
or the instructions.  Your child will find TestBank questions
both clear and direct, and he can study for every question from
the textbook.  Prepared by several experienced teachers, the
questions include a wide variety of matching, true/false,
multiple-choice, short-answer, and essay items.  The <I>English 7</I>
TestBank contains many grammar-specific activities, such as
labeling parts of speech, underlining sentence parts,
diagramming, and punctuating.

<P>What TestBanks are not designed to do, however, is replace the
teacher.  Only you know which questions are appropriate for your
child and which questions accurately assess what you have been
teaching.  Sometimes you need to adapt the questions to fit your
instructional objectives you have established.  Furthermore, you
may want to ask questions about supplementary material you have
brought into the course.  You may also find questions over the
same content in both the multiple choice and the matching
sections.  You can decide which type of question in more suitable
to your presentation of a particular item.

<P>Hence, these TestBanks can in no way be used a printed
publisher-made tests.  In fact, the answers are printed with the
items so that the sections cannot be photocopied.  Standardized
tests, one kind of printed test, are necessary for occasional
national comparison, but not every test the child takes should be
so designed.  The less input you have into the makeup of a test,
the less control you have over your child's education.

<P>This parent-centered philosophy of test construction (and of home
education in general) is emphasized throughout BJU Press
materials.  <I>Classroom Testing</I> thoroughly treats the testing
theory that was applied in the TestBank manual.  This booklet
contains detailed information on each of the different types of
test questions.  It also gives helpful instruction on how to
phrase questions effectively.

<P>Every student deserves the opportunity to do his best.  With the
aid of BJU Press TestBanks and a few simple principles, you can
create tests in less time and with more accuracy in measuring
both how effectively you have taught and how much your child has
learned.

<HR>


