</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT24-B08-54</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA043-000789-B024-282</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.bju.edu:80/press/resource/hsh/0501.html 198.69.96.10 19970118032550 text/html 4028
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Communications/1.12
Date: Saturday, 18-Jan-97 02:24:35 GMT
Last-modified: Friday, 29-Nov-96 19:29:48 GMT
Content-length: 3837
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
The Preschool Push
</TITLE>
<LINK REV="OWNER" HREF="mailto:bjup@bju.edu">
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<A NAME = "TOP"></A>
<H1 ALIGN = CENTER>
The Preschool Push
</H1>

<P ALIGN = CENTER>
[ <A HREF = "contents.html">Home School Helper Contents</A>
| <A HREF = "../resource.html">On-Line Resources</A>
| <A HREF = "../../home.html">BJUP Home Page</A> ]
</P>

<HR>

<P>Parents are the child's first and most influential teachers.  The
interaction of the young child with his parents begins to mold
the child's personality, his self-image, and his emotional
stability.  This interaction also forms the foundation for both
his attitude toward and potential for learning.

<P>Pressure in early childhood education has been a point of
conflict and debate for the past thirty years.  Examples of
children that have learned to read at the age of three and four
are often cited.  Yes, this has happened, but it is not the norm.
For that matter, some babies walk sooner than others, and some
talk earlier.  It is interesting that we have come to accept
early toilet training as an unnecessary frustration; yet pressure
for early academic achievement is now emphasized in the
stimulation activities being suggested for the unborn child.

<P>We do want to stimulate the young child intellectually,
increasing his skills of observation, his awareness, his basic
reasoning skills in comparing, classifying, associating,
ordering, and perceiving relationships--in other words to begin
early to teach the child to think.

<P>But we must remember that maturation varies greatly, especially
on the early childhood level.  We must let each child mature at
his own rate.  To stress reading instruction prematurely could
cause an underestimation of a child's true potential.  Even
putting a child into social situations or decision-making roles
for which he is not prepared could overload him with too much
responsibility too soon and could carry devastating consequences
for the child even into adulthood.

<P>Why can we not let a child be a child?  What's wrong with letting
a child play?  Too soon he will grow up and find that he does not
have much time for play.  By the way, plan can help relieve
stress in a child.

<P>The best way to prepare your child for reading is to read to him.
"Reading" pictures--having him identify characters or objects,
actions or details, infer conversations or motives, and
anticipate the outcome--provides not only fun and companionship
but also one of the best strategies for building a good reader.
The importance of reading illustrated storybooks to increase
vocabulary, to ask comprehension questions, and to read just for
enjoyment cannot be overstressed.  You are conveying to your
child "print awareness" which is a prerequisite to (not a
substitute for) phonics instruction.

<P>Another important aspect of print awareness is labeling or
captioning (i.e., family members' names for table settings,
family members' names on the appropriate calendar date for their
birthdays), printing the child's dictation about his artwork on
the piece of art, having the child dictate stories or letters to
relatives for you to write down, then reading these back to and
with your child.  These activities emphasize the relationship of
thought and oral and written language.  They motivate the child
to want to read.  The undue stress and pressure are absent, and
the child develops the appropriate attitude.  This is reading in
its earliest stage.

<HR>


<P><I>Home School Helper</I> is published by <A HREF =
"http://www.bju.edu/press/home.html">Bob Jones University Press,</A> Greenville,
South Carolina 29614

