<BODY>
<A NAME = "TOP"></A>
<H1 ALIGN = CENTER>
What in the World!
</H1>

<P ALIGN = CENTER>A news service prepared by <A HREF =
"http://www.bju.edu/">Bob Jones University</A> for the local church

<P ALIGN = CENTER>Volume 19, Number 08

<H4 ALIGN = CENTER>
[ <A HREF="#GOV">Government</A>
| <A HREF="#REL">Religion</A>
| <A HREF="#SOC">Society</A>
]
</H4>

<HR>


<A NAME = "GOV"></A><H2>Government</H2>

<P>&#182; Hawaii's state Senate has passed a bill 
to create "domestic partnerships" for homosexual couples. Meanwhile, 
the House has approved a proposal to let voters decide next fall whether 
to amend the state constitution to ban same-sex marriages.<BR>
&#160;&#160;&#160;The votes are responses to a 1993 state supreme court ruling that 
denying marriage license to same-sex couples, without a compelling 
interest, is unconstitutional. Hawaii's attorney general will argue 
the case for a "compelling interest" before the state Supreme Court 
in July. However, a gubernatorial commission has recommended that 
homosexuals be allowed to marry. Marriages in one state usually must 
be recognized by all other states (<I>NIRR,</I> 3/18/96).

<P>&#182; On March 6 a federal appeals court struck 
down Washington state's ban on physician-assisted suicide. The court, 
which drew heavily on past abortion decisions, dismissed most counter 
arguments briefly and "with undisguised contempt," according to 
<I>National Right to Life News</I> (3/25/96).

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;The court hinted that suicide should be available to more than 
just the terminally ill: "Our conclusion is strongly influenced by, 
but not limited to, the plight of mentally competent, terminally ill 
adults. We are influenced as well by the plight of others, such as 
those whose existence is reduced to a vegetative state or a permanent 
and irreversible state of consciousness." Referring to "the handicapped," 
the court states, "seriously impaired individuals will . . . be the 
beneficiaries of the liberty interest asserted here. . . . If they 
are not afforded the option to control their own fate, they like many 
others will be compelled, against their will, to endure unusual and 
protracted suffering." In light of this decision, the "suicide doctor" 
Jack Kevorkian said he plans to open suicide clinics in California.

<A NAME = "REL"></A><H2>Religion</H2>

<P>&#182; Dallas Seminary released a statement in 
December on the Promise Keepers ministry. It said, "Although Dallas 
has no official ties to Promise Keepers, some of our faculty and alumni 
have participated in their public meetings. One of our distinguished 
professors, Dr. Howard Hendricks, also serves on the PK board."<BR>
&#160;&#160;&#160;The statement said that groups with theological differences can 
work together on social issues: "For example, Roman Catholics and 
Evangelical Protestants can unite in opposition to such evils as abortion 
on demand and pornography. Furthermore, noncharismatics and charismatics 
can unite in support of the basic biblical values of sexual morality, 
personal integrity, and family fidelity" (<I>Calvary Contender,</I> 
3/15/96).

<P>&#182; Most of the 9.4 million Mormons in the 
world now live outside the United States, the church reports. The 
most growth has occurred in Latin America, where there are more than 
3 million Mormons. The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints 
has 50,000 missionaries (<I>NIRR,</I> 3/4/96).

<P>&#182; Many American prisoners are converting 
to Islam. Between 10% and 20% of the 1.5 million inmates in federal, 
state, and municipal prisons and jails today identify themselves as 
Muslims, according to the National Association of Muslim Chaplains. 
In New York City jails, the figure is closer to 30%.<BR>
&#160;&#160;&#160;As a result, the nation's prisons have become a key element in the 
rapid growth of Islam in America, particularly among African Americans, 
who account for almost half of the nation's three to five million 
Muslims. Some 30,000 black men convert to Islam in prison each year 
(<I>Christian News,</I> 1/29/96).

<P>&#182; A group of secular humanist scholars and 
Baptist intellectuals and seminarians have issued a "Cooperative 
Baptist--Secular Humanist Declaration" that supports academic 
freedom and church-state separation. Noting that "many Baptist schools 
and seminaries have undergone a major assault on the academic freedom 
of their faculties," the document calls for academic settings to 
be "free of intimidation and repression."<BR>
&#160;&#160;&#160;Among those who endorsed the document were Stan Hastey, executive 
director of the Alliance of Baptists, and Robert Alley, professor 
emeritus of humanities at the University of Richmond, a Southern Baptist--affiliated 
school (<I>Christian Century,</I> 3/13/96).

<A NAME = "SOC"></A><H2>Society</H2>

<P>&#182; Pollster George Barna says America faces 
moral anarchy in the next five to ten years, if revival does not come. 
Most people who marry this year will have previously cohabited with 
someone. One-third of Americans believe it is acceptable for consenting 
adults to have an affair. Some 71% of Americans believe there is no 
such thing as absolute truth, a view shared by 64% of "born-again" 
Christians and 40% of evangelicals. Although 95% of Americans believe 
in God, 45% believe Jesus committed sins.<BR>
&#160;&#160;&#160;Despite the growth of some churches and talk of revival, there has 
been no overall increase in the number of people becoming Christians, 
Barna said. His research indicates that 70 to 80 percent of church 
growth in America is "transfer" growth from one church to another 
(<I>Baptist Courier,</I> 3/4/96).

<P>&#182; People who engage in murder, rape, and 
other forms of violence rarely suffer from low self-esteem, according 
to a review of nearly two hundred studies. The study, published in 
<I>Psychological Review,</I> found that people whose self-esteem is 
unstable or inflated seem to be the most dangerous. "One major cause 
of violent response is threatened egotism, that is, a favorable self-appraisal 
that encounters an external, unfavorable evaluation." Professor Roy 
F. Baumeister of Case Western Reserve University concludes that a 
little more modesty and humility would do more for society than boosting 
self-image (<I>Christian News,</I> 3/4/96).

<P>&#182; Forty-five million abortions, about one 
for every three live births, are performed around the world every 
year, the United Nations has reported. About 38% of the world's population 
lives in countries where abortion is available on demand (<I>NIRR,</I> 
3/4/96).

<P>&#182; The evangelical Eerdmans Publishing Company 
has printed a book that supports evolution. <I>The Fire in the Equations--Science, 
Religion, and the Search for God,</I> written by Kitty Ferguson, says 
on page 2, "Darwinism demolished the literal interpretation of the 
biblical Creation story." It asserts, "The theory of evolution is 
a well-established theory, not speculative and on the fringe of science. 
. . . The consensus of science today is that the theory of evolution 
is a powerful theory indeed, extremely well supported by evidence."<BR>
&#160;&#160;&#160;In the end of the book, the author argues, "The only thing of which 
I can be certain is my own existence. . . . Who else could possibly 
decide what is truth? I am, not by claim, but by default, my own ultimate 
authority on everything else" (<I>O Timothy,</I> vol. 13, #2).

<P>&#182; The 15th National Workshop on Christian-Jewish 
Relations, to be held October 27-30, is expected to draw 1,500 to 
2,000 participants. "This is the largest gathering of Jews and Christians 
in the world for conciliation, understanding and collaboration," 
said Rabbi Robert Lennick of Greenwich, one of the conveners. The 
theme of the conference is "Seeking God: The Challenge of Being Religious 
in America." Among the cosponsors are the Home Mission Board of the 
Southern Baptist Convention, the National Council of Churches, the 
National Conference of Catholic Bishops, and the American Jewish Committee. 
This year some Muslims are expected to attend as well (<I>Christian 
News,</I> 2/26/96).
<HR>


<P><I>What in the World!</I> is published by <A HREF =
"http://www.bju.edu/">Bob Jones University,</A> Greenville, South
Carolina 29614 to help believers know what the devil is up to.
Free church subscriptions: 864-242-5100, ext. 3074

