<HEAD>
<TITLE>
What in the World!
</TITLE>
<LINK REV="OWNER" HREF="mailto:bjup@bju.edu">
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<A NAME = "TOP"></A>
<H1 ALIGN = CENTER>
What in the World!
</H1>

<P ALIGN = CENTER>A news service prepared by <A HREF =
"http://www.bju.edu/">Bob Jones University</A> for the local church

<P ALIGN = CENTER>Volume 19, Number 11

<H4 ALIGN = CENTER>
[ <A HREF="#GOV">Government</A>
| <A HREF="#REL">Religion</A>
| <A HREF="#SOC">Society</A>
]
</H4>

<HR>


<A NAME = "GOV"></A><H2>Government</H2>

<P>&#182; The U.S. Supreme Court has refused to 
review lower court rulings that struck down parts of South Dakota's 
abortion law. South Dakota had the only state law that did not provide 
for a "judicial bypass" that lets minors get permission from a judge 
rather than a parent (<I>Christian News</I>, 5/6/96).

<P>&#182; The National Institutes of Health (NIH) 
say the terms <I>husband</I> and <I>wife</I> need to go by the wayside 
in the work place, according to a <I>Washington Times</I> report. 
The NIH Office of Equal Opportunity says the two words are too exclusive 
and leave out co-workers involved in homosexual relationships. The 
Institute suggests using phrases like "partner" or "significant 
other" in conversation and correspondence (<I>AFA Journal</I>, 6/96).

<P>&#182; On May 20 the U.S. Supreme Court struck 
down an amendment to Colorado's constitution that barred special privileges 
for homosexuals. The court's majority opinion "has no basis in American 
constitutional law, and barely pretends to," said a stinging dissent, 
written by Justice Scalia. The amendment had been approved in 1994 
by 54% of state voters. It did <I>not</I> deny homosexuals the protections 
that all citizens enjoy. It merely precluded the granting of special 
protection to homosexuals because they are homosexuals  (<I>Human 
Events</I> 5/31/96). 

<A NAME = "REL"></A><H2>Religion</H2>

<P>&#182; Promise Keepers is planning a series of 
regional rallies for pastors as follow-ups to its Atlanta clergy conference. 
About six such rallies are planned for the fall of 1997, although 
dates and locations are not finalized. After PK's initial sponsorship 
of the regional rallies, future meetings will be organized by pastors. 
The goal is for pastors of various denominations to befriend each 
other, hold concerts of prayer together, and cooperate in ministry 
efforts (<I>NIRR</I>, 5/13/96).

<P>&#182; Salem's celebrated witches are more in 
vogue than ever. Publicity for the 300th anniversary of the 1692 witch 
trials has sparked a steady increase in tourism from its initial 15% 
jump back in 1992. The number of witches has grown to exceed 10% of 
the local population of nearly 40,000. One of the more famous sites 
is Crow Haven Corner, a witch shop founded and still owned by Laurie 
Cabot, the "Official Witch of Salem" (World, 5/11/96).

<P>&#182; A group of secular humanist scholars and 
Baptist intellectuals and seminarians have issued a "Cooperative 
Baptist--Secular Humanist Declaration" that supports academic 
freedom and church-state separation. Noting that "many Baptist schools 
and seminaries have undergone a major assault on the academic freedom 
of their faculties," the document calls for academic settings to 
be "free of intimidation and repression."<BR>
&#160;&#160;&#160;The declaration was endorsed by such individuals as Stan 
Hastey, executive director of the Alliance of Baptists, and Robert 
Alley, professor emeritus at the University of Richmond, a Southern 
Baptist--affiliated school (<I>Christian Century,</I> 3/13/96).

<P>&#182; In what has been hailed as a model for 
religious cooperation in large cities, five large religious organizations 
in the Minneapolis--St. Paul area have launched "Congregations 
in Community." The three-year initiative will help Jewish, Muslim, 
and mainline Christian congregations recruit and train nearly 7,000 
volunteers to serve families and children. The initiative is being 
funded by the McKnight Foundation, which was endowed by an early leader 
of the 3M Company (<I>Christian Century</I>, 5/15/96).

<P>&#182; Most of the 9.4 million Mormons in the 
world now live outside the United States, the church reports. The 
most growth has occurred in Latin America, where there are more than 
3 million Mormons. The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints 
has 50,000 missionaries (<I>NIRR,</I> 3/4/96).

<P>&#182; Ignatius Press has published <I>Ecumenical 
Jihad: Ecumenism and the Culture War</I> by Roman Catholic professor 
Peter Kreeft. The advertisement says, "Peter Kreeft argues that we 
need to change our current alignments. We need to realize that we 
are at war and that the sides have changed radically: many of our 
former enemies (e.g. Muslims) are now our friends, and some of our 
former friends (e.g. humanists) are now our enemies. Documenting the 
spiritual and moral decay of modern society, Kreeft issues a wake-up 
call to all God-fearing Christians, Jews, and Muslims to unite together 
in a 'religious war' against the common enemy of godless secular humanism, 
materialism and immorality."<BR>
&#160;&#160;&#160;"Aware of the deep theological differences between these monolithic 
faiths, Kreeft calls for a moratorium on our polemics against each 
other so that we can form an alliance to save western civilization." 
The advertisement included endorsements by J.I. Packer, Chuck Colson, 
and Richard Neuhaus (<I>Christianity Today</I>, 5/20/96).

<A NAME = "SOC"></A><H2>Society</H2>

<P>&#182; Recognizing the sales potential of the 
rapidly growing Christian music category, major secular music companies 
have purchased the largest gospel music labels, including Sparrow, 
Star Song, and Reunion. Contemporary Christian musicians are excited 
about the opportunity for their music to be sold in mainstream stores 
such as Wal-Mart and Target. As a result, Christian artists have gained 
a higher profile in mainstream society. In 1990, gospel music accounted 
for 2.5% of all music sales. By 1994, that increased to 3.3%, amounting 
to $390 million--about the same as classical and jazz, according 
to news reports (<I>NIRR,</I> 4/15/96).

<P>&#182; Psychic Friends Network is taking in about 
$1.5 million a week. Since going on the air in 1992, it has raked 
in roughly $200 million. Last year the service received its 10-millionth 
call. In May the company launched <I>Psychic Friends Live Radio</I>, 
a two-hour program that airs nationwide five nights a week, and Psychic 
Friends on the Internet, which will allow users to get live readings 
in Psychic Friends chat rooms. The network appeals mostly to women, 
typically in their 30s and 40s, and the first question likely is to 
be about relationships (<I>Insight</I>, 6/10/96).

<P>&#182; Buddhist, Scientologist, and Mormon writings 
are now appearing in hotel rooms alongside Gideon Bibles. A total 
of 2,500 hotels carry <I>The Teachings of Buddha</I>, distributed 
by the Tokyo-based Society for the Promotion of Buddhism. Followers 
of the Church of Scientology said they have placed more than 90,000 
copies of <I>The Way to Happiness</I> in 350 hotels. Christian Scientists 
are trying to increase the availability of Mary Baker Eddy's <I>Science 
and Health with Key to the Scriptures</I>, which is being placed ad 
hoc in hotel rooms. The Book of Mormon has long been a fixture in 
hotel rooms owned and operated by the Marriott Corporation (<I>Christianity 
Today</I>, 5/20/96).



<HR>


<P><I>What in the World!</I> is published by <A HREF =
"http://www.bju.edu/">Bob Jones University,</A> Greenville, South
Carolina 29614 to help believers know what the devil is up to.
Free church subscriptions: 864-242-5100, ext. 3074

