<HEAD>
<TITLE>
What in the World!
</TITLE>
<LINK REV="OWNER" HREF="mailto:bjup@bju.edu">
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<A NAME = "TOP"></A>
<H1 ALIGN = CENTER>
What in the World!
</H1>

<P ALIGN = CENTER>A news service prepared by <A HREF =
"http://www.bju.edu/">Bob Jones University</A> for the local church

<P ALIGN = CENTER>Volume 20, Number 09

<H4 ALIGN = CENTER>
[ <A HREF="#GOV">Government</A>
| <A HREF="#REL">Religion</A>
| <A HREF="#SOC">Society</A>
]
</H4>

<HR>


<A NAME = "GOV"></A><H2>Government</H2>

<P>&#182; A U.S. district judge has ruled that Mississippi 
cannot limit the "right" of abortion clinics to perform abortions 
by placing them under the same regulations governing other medical 
facilities. The twelve restrictions include such basic things as the 
number of rest rooms in the building. This is the first court to recognize 
a "right" of abortion clinics to perform abortions. The state's 
effort to regulate clinics was sparked by the infamous abortionist 
Tommy Tucker, who lost his licenses in both Mississippi and Alabama 
following the death of clients (<I>World,</I> 10/12/96).

<P>&#182; Two boys, ages 8 and 11, must be returned 
to the custody of their homosexual father, a North Carolina appeals 
court ruled October 15. The court said, "There is no evidence that 
[homosexual] conduct has or likely will have a deleterious effect 
on the children." The mother will appeal to the state supreme court 
(<I>World,</I> 10/26/96).

<P>&#182; President Clinton established the White 
House's first-ever "liaison to the gay and lesbian community" in 
June 1995. Ironically, the radical homosexual group ACT-UP is planning 
to file a complaint with the Federal Elections Commission (FEC) because 
the president has routinely used the taxpayer-funded liaison to campaign 
rather than to represent homosexual interests. Indeed, the liaison, 
Richard Socarides, left his position a few weeks ago to work on the 
Clinton/Gore reelection campaign.

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;Socarides defends the president as the most gay-friendly president 
in history: "He's better than all other presidents combined on gay 
and lesbian issues." Socarides ticks off the presidents accomplishments: 
"He's the first president to support non-discrimination in the work 
place. He's the first president to support the removal of sexual-orientation 
barriers in security-clearance procedures. And he's had more homosexual 
and lesbian appointees than any other president" (<I>World,</I> 10/12/96).

<P>&#182; The European Court of Human Rights has 
accepted a 12-year-old boy's claim that his parents violated the 1950 
European Human Rights Convention. The boy's stepfather had caned him 
for trying to stab another child with a kitchen knife. The lawsuit 
specifically challenged a British law that allows corporal punishment. 
If successful, the suit could force Britain to change its law (<I>World,</I> 
9/21/96).

<A NAME = "REL"></A><H2>Religion</H2>

<P>&#182; Evolution as a work of God is acceptable 
dogma, the pope has said. In his most comprehensive statement yet 
on evolution, Pope John Paul II told scientists that Darwin's theories 
are sound as long as they take into account that creation was the 
work of God. In 1950 Pope Pius XII proclaimed that evolution was a 
"serious hypothesis," but the current pope says that new knowledge 
has confirmed that Darwin's theory of evolution is "more than a hypothesis" 
(<I>Greenville</I> [S.C.] <I>News,</I> 10/25/96).

<P>&#182; The World Council of Churches (WCC) has 
released a report on AIDS that urges churches across the world to 
"put aside your differences about theology and sexuality" and "become 
actively involved in the global struggle against AIDS." A Russian 
Orthodox leader in the WCC condemned the report's apparent failure 
to discuss "the question of personal ethics and personal sinfulness" 
(<I>Baptists Today,</I> 10/24/96).

<P>&#182; Southern Baptist leaders in Georgia have 
censured Mercer University president Kirby Godsey over his new book 
<I>When We Talk About God . . . Let's Be Honest.</I> The book rejects 
the infallibility of Scripture, minimizes the importance of the Virgin 
Birth, and apparently rejects original sin. Godsey says that God's 
revelation continues today.

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;Godsey says of creeds, "I believe that creeds should never 
be used as tests of orthodoxy." He explains, "Today's confession 
may be tomorrow's uncertainty. Tomorrow's confession may be today's 
heresy."

<P>&#182; Church attendance is at its lowest level 
in two decades, with just 37% of adults attending on a given weekend, 
says pollster George Barna. Data also indicate that only 28% of men 
attend Sunday services versus 46% of women (<I>New Man,</I> 11-12/96).

<P>&#182; The Autumn issue of Dallas Seminary's 
<I>Kindred Spirit</I> lists faculty speaking engagements at a wide 
variety of places: a Youth for Christ meeting, a conference of the 
Independent Fundamental Churches of America, a Promise Keepers conference, 
a Moody men's conference, the charismatic Christ for the Nations, 
and a Campus Crusade Fall retreat (<I>Calvary Contender,</I> 11/1/96).

<P>&#182; Promise Keepers meetings failed to fill 
their venues to capacity in 1996, and the New Orleans rally lost a 
substantial amount of money. "Products and resources did not sell 
as well as in seasons past; revenues did not keep pace with budget 
projections. It has caused some anxious moments at national headquarters," 
wrote Promise Keepers cofounder Bill McCartney in <I>New Man</I> (11-12/96). 
"For Promise Keepers to fulfill its God-given mission, we must also 
depend on the unreserved, Spirit-led offerings of individuals. . . 
. I am asking that each man begin to pray daily, humbly beseeching 
God for the resources needed to sustain His work."

<A NAME = "SOC"></A><H2>Society</H2>

<P>&#182; An Assemblies of God pastor in Iran was 
found dead last September, hanged on a tree, under still unexplained 
circumstances. Pastor Mohammed Bagher Yusefi had close ties to two 
other Iranian Assemblies of God pastors who were murdered in 1994 
(<I>Christian News,</I> 10/14/96).

<P>&#182; Students from fifteen colleges and universities 
have formed the Campus Freethought Alliance. The intercollegiate group 
of atheists, humanists, and skeptics will coordinate activities, protect 
the rights of non-believing students, and try to spark the formation 
of freethought organizations on every campus nationwide. The students 
are concerned about a "resurgence of religious fundamentalism" and 
a growing disdain for science and the principles of the Enlightenment 
(<I>Christian News,</I> 9/30/96).

<P>&#182; Pat Boone, a Christian entertainer known 
for his "vanilla pop" songs in the '50s and '60s, will release a 
heavy metal album early next year. "How can God be in Pat Boone doing 
an album of heavy metal?" he asked <I>Charisma</I> (11/96). "Well, 
He's confirmed to me that He is, and that this is a means to an end." 
<I>Pat Boone in a Metal Mood</I> will compile twelve songs from Alice 
Cooper, Guns N' Roses, Ozzy Osbourne, Judas Priest, and others. Boone 
acknowledges "There will be plenty of Christians who will think I'm 
wrong," but he says he is being guided by Scriptures that talk about 
"becoming all things to all men in order to win 'the outlaws.' "

<P>&#182; The parents of popular Christian singer 
Jeffrey Fenholt have filed a $12 million lawsuit against their son, 
because they claim he has falsely accused them of abusing him during 
his childhood. Fenholt, 45, said in his autobiography that his parents 
held pillows over his head and beat him, kicked and slapped him, and 
threw him down stairs. Fenholt's brother and two sisters say Jeffrey 
made up the stories to further his career. The singer's claim that 
he spent time in a juvenile detention center is being disputed by 
court officials (<I>Charisma,</I> 10/96).

<P>&#182; A Roman Catholic priest has been married 
for fifteen years, a bishop in St. Petersburg, Florida, announced 
October 1. The priest will be allowed to resume his vocation if he 
decides to end his marriage. On the same day, the bishop revealed 
that another priest had diverted $225,000 of church funds to pay off 
a former male love (<I>Christian Century,</I> 10/23/96).

<P>&#182; PBS has begun airing an animated series 
<I>Adventures from The Book of Virtues</I> based on William Bennett's 
best-selling collection of stories on virtues. In the six pilot programs, 
two children turn to a cast of animal friends for comfort and spiritual 
guidance. Even though the series incorporates two Bible stories, it 
draws no distinction between the God of the Bible and the deities 
of other cultures. In one episode, Plato the buffalo teaches the girl 
Annie to "believe in yourself" (<I>World,</I> 9/28/96).

<P>&#182; Australia's Northern Territory has allowed 
the world's first legally assisted suicide. Bob Dent, 66, who was 
suffering from cancer, was allowed to take deadly drugs under a euthanasia 
law passed earlier this year (<I>Baptists Today,</I> 10/24/96).



