<A NAME = "TOP"></A>
<H1 ALIGN = CENTER>
What in the World!
</H1>

<P ALIGN = CENTER>A news service prepared by <A HREF =
"http://www.bju.edu/">Bob Jones University</A> for the local church

<P ALIGN = CENTER>Volume 19, Number 05

<H4 ALIGN = CENTER>
[ <A HREF="#GOV">Government</A>
| <A HREF="#REL">Religion</A>
| <A HREF="#SOC">Society</A>
]
</H4>

<HR>


<A NAME = "GOV"></A><H2>Government</H2>

<P>&#182; The federal government is America's largest 
distributor of pornography. Through the military exchange system, 
it sells sex magazines tax-free and at discount prices. Even the Pentagon 
Book Store sales nine "soft-porn" magazines and two explicit homosexual 
magazines. After the rape of a 12-year-old Japanese girl in Okinawa 
by three U.S. servicemen, the <I>AFA Journal</I> (3/96) has called 
on the President to sign an executive order prohibiting the sale of 
sexually explicit materials on military bases.

<P>&#182; The U.S. Supreme Court has refused to 
hear an appeal by a student who got a "zero" on a paper because 
she wrote about Jesus Christ. In 1991 an English teacher had assigned 
Brittney Settle a research paper on any "researchable" topic. The 
teacher, Dana Ramsey, said that Jesus was not an appropriate topic 
in a public high school. She argued that the students were supposed 
to write an unbiased paper on an unfamiliar topic. Other students 
in the class were permitted to write about witchcraft, magic, and 
reincarnation (<I>Alliance Life,</I> 1/3/96).

<P>&#182; A federal judge has ordered school officials 
to return a book on homosexuals to public school libraries. The judge 
said that members of the school board in Olathe, Kansas, violated 
the First Amendment when they removed the book <I>Annie on My Mind</I> 
from high school library shelves. Board members had argued that their 
view was representative of the city (<I>AFA Journal,</I> 3/96).

<P>&#182; Christians have faced increasing persecution 
ever since the Chinese government appointed Ye Xiaowen, a hardline 
Communist and atheist, to head the Religious Affairs Bureau. After 
a January meeting with top Communist officials, the Religious Affairs 
Bureau issued an order that all unsanctioned places of worship must 
register with the government. Registered churches must agree not to 
associate with foreigners, to curtail youth work, and to restrict 
the use and distribution of Bibles and Christian literature.

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;In November and December police raided more than 30 homes in 
Shanghai where independent church groups had been gathering, confiscating 
books and other materials. The owner of an underground print shop  was 
fined $10,000 and shut down. Police have warned many pastors they 
could face fines up to $50,000 if they do not register. "China now 
has the largest number of Christian prisoners in the world," says 
Freedom House's Puebla Program (<I>World,</I> 2/17/96).

<A NAME = "REL"></A><H2>Religion</H2>

<P>&#182; More than 7,000 youth workers from over 
100 denominations and ministries gathered February 11-12 at the Atlanta 
'96 Youth Leaders Conference. Leaders came from charismatic, evangelical, 
Roman Catholic, and mainline churches. The consensus was that revival 
will sweep across America within the next few years, led by Generation 
X youth. Leaders said they have agreed to work together to reach a 
common outreach goal: Every Kid, Every Campus, Every Community (<I>NIRR,</I> 
2/19/96).

<P>&#182; Pope John Paul II is calling on Catholics 
to thwart the threat of "religious sects." In September he warned 
visiting bishops from Brazil that "certain sects are destroying the 
faith of the people, at times in a violent manner." Recently he told 
a Vatican commission, "Missionary expansion has not been able to 
keep pace with the increase in population and is being challenged, 
especially in Latin America, by the destructive work of the sects." 
Protestant leaders deny these harsh accusations (<I>NNI,</I> 1/19/96).

<P>&#182; The Christian Coalition has joined the 
mainline National Council of Churches in an effort to stop the spread 
of legal gambling in the U.S. The National Coalition Against Legalized 
Gambling, based in Washington, will be headed by Tom Grey, a United 
Methodist minister. The coalition's top priority is the establishment 
of a national commission to investigate legalized gambling's economic 
impact, its alleged ties to organized crime, and the political influence 
the gambling industry wields through campaign contributions (<I>Christian 
Century,</I> 2/7/96).

<P>&#182; Committing suicide or assisting a suicide 
may be morally acceptable under some circumstances, the Episcopal 
diocese of Newark, New Jersey, has declared. Suicide may be okay when 
"pain is persistent and/or progressive; when all other reasonable 
means of amelioration of pain and suffering have been exhausted; and 
when the decision to hasten death is a truly informed and voluntary 
choice free from external coercion." The action contradicts a 
1991 resolution by the General Convention (<I>Christian 
News,</I> 2/12/96).

<A NAME = "SOC"></A><H2>Society</H2>

<P>&#182; "Therapeutic touch," a mystical form 
of alternative healing, is growing in popularity. TT practitioners 
sweep their hands a few inches above a sick person's body to smooth 
out kinks in the energy field. Practitioners reportedly number in 
the tens of thousands in the U.S. and many foreign countries.<BR>
&#160;&#160;&#160;Therapeutic touch is taught in nursing schools, practiced in hospitals, 
and described in <I>Techniques in Clinical Nursing,</I> a widely distributed 
textbook, reports said. The Defense Department has given a $355,225 
research grant to the School of Nursing at the University of Alabama 
at Birmingham to study the effects of TT on patients with battle-related 
burns.<BR>
&#160;&#160;&#160;Critics say the same effect can be attained when a nurse sits on 
a bedside, talks to a patient, and holds his hand (<I>NIRR,</I> 2/5/96).

<P>&#182; The number of organizations extending 
health benefits to homosexual partners of employees is growing. They 
include universities (Duke, Harvard, MIT, and Princeton), non-profit 
groups (the American Red Cross and United Way), computer companies 
(Apple, Lotus, and Microsoft), entertainment companies (Walt Disney, 
MGM, Paramount, and Universal Studios), media (Time, Barnes & Noble, 
New York Times, and Viacom), and municipal governments (Baltimore, 
Hartford, New Orleans, New York, Seattle, Oakland, San Diego, and 
San Francisco) (<I>AFA Journal,</I> 3/96).

<P>&#182; Major U.S. media organizations are biased 
in favor of legalized abortion, according to an extensive new study. 
Reporters consistently used favorable language to describe supporters 
of unrestricted abortion, while applying negative terms to opponents 
of abortion. Stories have been predicting that a pro-life position 
will harm the GOP, even though not a single pro-life incumbent lost 
in the 1994 elections. The media also ignored Democratic politicians 
who are pro-life (<I>Christian News,</I> 2/12/96; <I>World,</I> 1/27/96).

<P>&#182; A new politically correct hymnal has been 
published by the United Church of Christ. "Patriot dreams" and other 
words that hint of militancy have disappeared from "America the Beautiful." 
Instead of "America, America," the hymn now reads "Americas, 
Americas" (<I>Greenville</I> [S.C.] <I>News,</I> 2/19/96).



