<A NAME = "TOP"></A>
<H1 ALIGN = CENTER>
What in the World!
</H1>

<P ALIGN = CENTER>A news service prepared by <A HREF =
"http://www.bju.edu/">Bob Jones University</A> for the local church

<P ALIGN = CENTER>Volume 20, Number 06

<H4 ALIGN = CENTER>
[ <A HREF="#GOV">Government</A>
| <A HREF="#REL">Religion</A>
| <A HREF="#SOC">Society</A>
]
</H4>

<HR>


<A NAME = "GOV"></A><H2>Government</H2>

<P>&#182; The abortion pill could be legal in the 
U.S. within six months now that an advisory panel of the Food and 
Drug Administration (FDA) has approved it. Opponents will try to stop 
final approval of RU-486 by stressing its side effects, which can 
include severe contractions, headaches, dizziness, and heart palpitations. 
FDA advisors said they were concerned that some women might skip the 
last follow-up exam, a necessary step to catch failed abortions (<I>NIRR,</I> 
8/5/96).

<P>&#182; Two tourists visiting a resort in Morocco 
last June were arrested and sentenced to a month in prison for giving 
a Moroccan a Christian tape. The tourists were an American, Cheralene 
Menchaca, and a Spaniard, Maria Lopez. Police arrested them after 
they gave a hotel worker an audio cassette containing a Christian 
testimony and hymns recorded in Arabic. The judiciary commuted the 
prison sentence to a fine, accepting an $80 bond and deporting the 
women. During their three-day detention, the women were denied access 
to their embassies or to a lawyer (<I>Compass Direct,</I> 7/25/96).

<P>&#182; In October the U.S. Supreme Court will 
hear a case involving the right of prolifers to speak or hold signs 
within a 15-foot "floating bubble." That buffer zone moves around 
the city, attached to abortion clinic staff and mothers seeking abortions. 
In 1992 a federal district judge introduced the concept of bubble 
zones when he prohibited pro-lifers from picketing outside Rochester 
and Buffalo abortion clinics. The case is called <I>Schenk</I> v. 
<I>Pro-choice Network of Western New York.<BR>
&#160;&#160;&#160;</I>This is the first time since 1994 that the Court has agreed to 
hear an abortion-related case. The 1994 case allowed limits on prolife 
speech as long as they did not burden "more speech than necessary 
to serve a significant government interest." Ever since then, lower 
courts have been issuing a confusing array of restrictions on speech 
(<I>NRL News,</I> 5/7/96; <I>National Liberty Journal,</I> 9/96).

<A NAME = "REL"></A><H2>Religion</H2>

<P>&#182; Hal Lindsey, best-selling author of <I>The 
Late Great Planet Earth,</I> is now hosting a weekly program for Trinity 
Broadcasting Network. TBN is headed by charismatic speakers Paul and 
Jan Crouch, who actively support various ecumenical groups and the 
Roman Catholic Church. Lindsey's program is called the International 
Intelligence Briefing (<I>Foundation,</I> 5-6/96).

<P>&#182; The American Bible Society has already 
earned a bad reputation for copyrighting Today's English Version (1966), 
the Good News Bible (1976), and the Contemporary English Version (1991). 
Now it is being questioned for cooperating closely with the Roman 
Catholic Church. Father Robert J. Robbins is vice chairman of the 
ABS church relations and volunteer activities committees. The <I>ABS 
Record</I> (5/96) says he "helps guide the American Bible Society 
in working with its vital network of church supporters and volunteers." 
He also serves on the executive committee (<I>Foundation,</I> 5-6/96).

<P>&#182; A call for a new ecumenical movement has 
been issued in <I>Christian Century</I> (8/14/96). "Those inside 
and outside the traditional ecumenical movement sense that something 
is missing," writes S. Mark Heim, professor of theology at Andover 
Newton Theological School in Newton Centre, Massachusetts. The old 
ecumenical organizations represent only a limited number of Christians, 
and they no longer address the most divisive issues, says Heim. Recent 
divisions focus not on denominational creeds, but on the role of government, 
social policy, economics, gender, race, and culture.

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;Heim is encouraged that the leaders of the World Council of 
Churches and the National Council of Churches have begun to speak 
about their need to be transformed into some wider movement. "Meanwhile," 
says Heim, "exciting movements toward Christian unity have been taking 
place quite apart from the councils." For example, he says, the charismatic 
movement, parachurch movements, Promise Keepers, and InterVarsity 
Fellowship "have brought Christians together across historical divisions 
and nurtured a transdenominational identity."

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;Heim hopes that Christians in the United States will mark the 
beginning of the third millennium of the church by drafting a simple 
document "expressing repentance for the failings of Christians and 
churches, affirming a few elements of common faith, and making commitments 
to seek God's forgiveness and help to better embody Christ's love 
for all people in our society."

<P>&#182; Promise Keepers welcomes female pastors 
leading male members, said Louis Monroe, a Baptist pastor who is Promise 
Keepers director for the state of Missouri.  A report in the <I>St. 
Louis Post-Dispatch</I> (7/13/96) also claimed, "Initially most participants 
were members of evangelical churches or had no churches. Now it attracts 
mainline Protestants and Catholics. It recently began recruiting Mormons" 
(<I>Christian News,</I> 7/29/96).  

<A NAME = "SOC"></A><H2>Society</H2>

<P>&#182; The rock group Newsboys has released a 
video study course for Sunday Schools. The ad states: "This 4-week 
youth study course uses the powerful medium of music, live concert 
footage, exclusive personal interviews, dramatic sketches and more 
to challenge your teens to live their lives in a way that draws others 
to Christ."<BR>
&#160;&#160;&#160;The course is based on the band's latest album, <I>Take Me to Your 
Leader.</I> Strang Communications Co., the publisher of <I>Charisma</I> 
magazine and writer of the study materials, says: "With Christian 
rock music as a backdrop, the course gives teens an opportunity to 
grow in their faith." The $49.95 program includes discount coupons 
for two Newsboys CDs (<I>Charisma,</I> 9/96).

<P>&#182; On June 28 MTV was scheduled to host the 
first nationally televised dating game for homosexuals. MTV combined 
efforts with <I>Out</I> magazine to air the show Singled Out (<I>AFA 
Journal,</I> 8/96).   

<P>&#182; A mob of Muslims destroyed ten church 
buildings and crippled a pastor in Surabaya, Indonesia. The 1,000-strong 
mob attacked Sunday services on June 9, according to Baptist Press. 
Police found a list of some fifty churches targeted for destruction. 
Government and Muslim leaders have been working to counter the rapid 
spread of Christianity (<I>NIRR,</I> 6/24/96).

<P>&#182; Lesbian film maker Debra Chasnoff has 
completed a new movie she hopes will become part of every school district's 
curriculum. <I>It's Elementary: Talking about Gay Issues in School</I> 
is meant to be a guideline for educators to use for introducing homosexuality 
into grade schools. Most of the film's scenes were shot in classrooms 
where teachers were already iscussing homosexuality with elementary 
children. "We wanted to demystify what it would look like to have 
age-appropriate discussions in the classroom," said Chasnoff (<I>AFA 
Journal,</I> 8/96).

