<BODY>
<A NAME = "TOP"></A>
<H1 ALIGN = CENTER>
What in the World!
</H1>

<P ALIGN = CENTER>A news service prepared by <A HREF =
"http://www.bju.edu/">Bob Jones University</A> for the local church

<P ALIGN = CENTER>Volume 20, Number 01

<H4 ALIGN = CENTER>
[ <A HREF="#GOV">Government</A>
| <A HREF="#REL">Religion</A>
| <A HREF="#SOC">Society</A>
]
</H4>

<HR>

<A NAME = "GOV"></A><H2>Government</H2>
<P>&#182; The IRS has issued guidance to tax-exempt
organizations on the rules against involvement in politics:
"Organizations exempt from federal income tax as organizations
described in section 501(c)(3) of the Internal Revenue Code are
prohibited by the terms of their exemption from participating
or intervening, directly or indirectly, in any political
campaign on behalf of, or in opposition to, any candidate for
public office.  

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;"Charities, educational institutions, and
religious organizations, including churches, are among those
tax exempt under this code section. These organizations cannot
endorse any candidates, make donations to their campaigns,
engage in fund raising, distribute statements, or become
involved in any other activities that may be beneficial or
detrimental to any candidate" (Church Law & Tax Report, 7-8/96).

<P>&#182; On June 12 a federal district court struck down a
provision of the new communications law aimed at regulating
"indecent" content on the World Wide Web (World, 6/22/96).

<P>&#182; On April 15 the U.S. Supreme Court left standing a
lower court ruling that Chicago can refuse to permit worship
services in a commercially zoned area. Dozens of church leaders
in the Chicago area have been denied building permits. In
addition, Chicago has cited zoning violations in closing about
thirty South Side storefront churches. A coalition of forty
churches had filed a class-action suit, claiming that the
zoning ordinance violated their constitutional right to freedom
of religion (Christianity Today, 5/15/95; Baptist Challenge, 6/96).

<P>&#182; On June 5 the Canadian parliament banned
discrimination against homosexuals in federal agencies and
federally regulated companies. Homosexual rights bills have
been introduced in the U.S. Congress, but none has passed
(Christian News, 6/17/96).

<P>&#182; Five Christian women belonging to house churches in
the northern Xinjiang province of China were detained and
tortured by Chines police in mid-March. According to a report
from Hong Kong, the police burst in on a home meeting and
arrested the five women leaders.  One woman had her front teeth
knocked out. Witnesses said police used boiling water to force
confessions.  It is feared they will all be sent to labor
camps. The rise in arrests and beatings may be linked to an
anti-crime campaign that targets any "illegal" acts (Compass
Direct, 5/30/96).  <A NAME = "REL"></A><H2>Religion</H2>

<P>&#182; Christians, Jews, Buddhists, Muslims, Hindus, and
Sikhs were among the religious leaders who participated in the
Stand for the Children rally June 1 at the capitol. "For Jesus,
the greatest sin one could commit was to cause children to
stumble," United Methodist Bishop Melvin Talbert, president of
the National Council of Churches, said at an ecumenical service
at the National Cathedral on the eve of the conference (NIRR, 6/24/96).  

<P>&#182; Jews, Roman Catholics, and evangelical Protestants
met last May to discuss common social concerns at the Center
for Jewish and Christian Values. Rabbi Yechiel Eckstein, an
Orthodox Jew and head of the International Fellowship of
Christians and Jews, founded the center last year to "reverse
the moral decline in our nation by bringing together Jews and
Christians in support of a common set of principles and public
policies." Sen. Daniel Coats (R-Ind.), an evangelical, joined
Sen. Joseph Lieberman (D-Conn.), an Orthodox Jew, as cofounders.

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;Leaders who attended the recent forum
included Gary Bauer, head of the Family Research Council, and
David Neff, editor for Christianity Today. Conspicuously absent
were mainline Protestants. After the conference, the center
planned to produce position papers on the family, compassion,
loyalty, honesty, work, responsibility, and human life
(Washington Times, 5/23/96).

<P>&#182; An increasing number of Anglican bishops are
ordaining practicing homosexuals to the priesthood. Last May
the previous archbishop of Canterbury, Lord Runcie, admitted
that he knowingly ordained homosexuals. He described as
"ridiculous" a 1991 document of the House of Bishops that
permits homosexual relations by lay members but not by clergy.
The current archbishop, George Carey, is adamant that
homosexual clergy be celibate (Christian News, 6/3/96).

<P>&#182; On May 1 nearly 200 leaders gathered to discuss
Mission America, an ambitious plan to reach 4,000 U.S.
communities by the year 2001. To achieve this goal, leaders
will hold 1,000 "city consultations" each year, beginning in
1997, to seek ways to work together in evangelism. Leaders
believe that divisive walls must be broken down if the country
is to be evangelized.  Joseph Stowell, president of Moody Bible
Institute, told participants that God historically moves only
when His body is unified. About 100 denominations and
parachurch ministries have joined Mission America (Charisma, 7/96).

<A NAME = "SOC"></A><H2>Society</H2>

<P>&#182; One in five intensive-care nurses have hastened the
death of terminally ill patients, according to responses by
over 850 nurses given an eight-page, anonymous questionnaire.
Some 58 nurses said they acted without the knowledge of
doctors, families, or the patients themselves. Most nurses who
killed patients said they gave overdoses of narcotics and
falsified medical records to protect themselves. The study, led
by Dr. David Asch of the University of Pennsylvania, was
released in the New England Journal of Medicine (National
Liberty Journal, 7/96).  

<P>&#182; The 27th annual Dove Awards were oriented toward
youth and a harder-edged, rock 'n' roll sound, observers said.
The awards, presented in 40 categories, are voted by members of
the Gospel Music Association. Winners of the awards, presented
April 25 at the Grand Ole Opry House in Nashville, included
rappers DC Talk (best artist), Point of Grace (best group),
Michael W.  Smith (songwriter of the year), Gary Chapman (best
male vocalist), and CeCe Winans (best female vocalist) (NIRR,
5/13/96).

<P>&#182; Teens should not have to tell parents about
abortions, says the American Academy of Pediatrics (AAP).
According to USA Today, the AAP claims parental consent laws
force teens to wait and have riskier abortions later in their
pregnancies (AFA Journal, 7/96).

<P>&#182; At a March meeting the nation's largest trade
association urged America's doctors to explore the use of the
anti-cancer drug methotrexate as an abortifacient.  Researchers
who have been experimenting with the drug presented their
findings at the annual meeting of the National Abortion
Federation (NAF). Planned Parenthood wants to make the
procedure available through its 152 affiliates across the
country by year's end&#160;&#160;&#160;(NRL News, 4/12/96).

<HR>


<P><I>What in the World!</I> is published by <A HREF =
"http://www.bju.edu/">Bob Jones University,</A> Greenville, South
Carolina 29614 to help believers know what the devil is up to.
Free church subscriptions: 864-242-5100, ext. 3074

