<HEAD>
<TITLE>
What in the World!
</TITLE>
<LINK REV="OWNER" HREF="mailto:bjup@bju.edu">
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<A NAME = "TOP"></A>
<H1 ALIGN = CENTER>
What in the World!
</H1>

<P ALIGN = CENTER>A news service prepared by <A HREF =
"http://www.bju.edu/">Bob Jones University</A> for the local church

<P ALIGN = CENTER>Volume 20, Number 03

<H4 ALIGN = CENTER>
[ <A HREF="#GOV">Government</A>
| <A HREF="#REL">Religion</A>
| <A HREF="#SOC">Society</A>
]
</H4>

<HR>


<A NAME = "GOV"></A><H2>Government</H2>

<P>&#182; Three federal agencies flew a rainbow banner to
celebrate June as Gay Pride Month, according to the <I>Clarion-Ledger</I> 
(6/13/96). They were the Department of Commerce, the Environmental 
Protection Agency (EPA), and the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA). 
All 45,000 FAA employees were encouraged to attend "voluntary" activities. 
The Department of Commerce gave a month of lectures designed to create 
a "safer and more respectful workplace" for homosexual workers (<I>AFA 
Journal,</I> 8/96).

<P>&#182; After nine months of briefing by the State 
Department, the new ambassador to China never heard about the persecution 
of house church leaders. Jim Sasser, former U.S. Senator from Tennessee, 
learned about diplomacy, trade, persecution of Buddhists in Tibet, 
and even violations of women's rights. However, on the eve of his 
departure, he was stumped by a human rights delegation's request to 
talk about the house church movement. Sasser asked, "What is a house 
church?" China's house church movement is perhaps the largest evangelical 
movement in the world, with as many as 80 to 100 million Christians 
(<I>AFA Journal,</I> 8/96).

<P>&#182; Since President Clinton took office, convictions 
against pornographers are down and the $8 billion industry is thriving. 
"You never hear Clinton or [Attorney General] Janet Reno speaking 
about this as a priority," says Patrick Trueman, former chief of 
the Justice Department's Child Exploitation and Obscenity Section 
(CEOS). The General Accounting Office is investigating charges that 
the CEOS has been leaking information to porn kingpins, even while 
Trueman was chief (<I>Insight,</I> 7/22/96).

<P>&#182; Edmond, Oklahoma, must remove a cross 
on its official seal because it violates the First Amendment. On May 
13 the U.S. Supreme Court refused to hear an appeal by city officials. 
Thirty-one years ago Edmond adopted the emblem. Three justices dissented, 
seeing no evidence that the plaintiffs had suffered injury. Federal 
circuit courts have upheld similar attacks against city seals since 
1985. Ironically, the high court refused last May to review a suit 
challenging the national motto, "In God We Trust" (<I>Human 
Events</I>, 7/5/96).

<P>&#182; Russian security chief Alexander Lebed 
has pledged to tighten visa restrictions on foreign workers and said 
he is "categorically against" foreign religious workers on Russian 
soil. Orthodox Christianity, Islam, and Buddhism are Russia's only 
"established, traditional religions," he said. President Boris Yeltsin 
appointed Lebed, who finished third in the first round of presidential 
elections, to head the Security Council (<I>NIRR,</I> 7/22/96).

<A NAME = "REL"></A><H2>Religion</H2>

<P>&#182; This year's March for Jesus drew an estimated 12
million Protestants and Roman Catholics to the streets in 170
countries on May 25. "Believers crossed denominational and
racial lines to march, pray, and sing choruses," says a report
in <I>Charisma</I> (8/96).<BR>

&#160;&#160;&#160;"Churches in cities came together simply to
express their unity and common faith," said Tom Pelton,
director of the March for Jesus USA. The movement has steadily
grown since its start in 1987, and global marches are planned
until the year 2000.

<P>&#182; In a speech on July 3, Pope John Paul II discussed
"the fundamental role that Mary's faith played and continues 
to play as regards the salvation of the human race." Mary was asked 
"to believe in a virginal motherhood that has no precedent in the 
Old Testament." The divine plan was carried out "with the collaboration 
of the human person. Mary, believing in the word of the Lord, cooperates 
in the fulfillment of that announced motherhood" (<I>Christian News,</I> 
7/15/96).

<P>&#182; The Christian Reformed Church in North 
America has stood by its 1995 decision to ordain women. The annual 
synod--the denomination's top decision-making body--declined 
24 petitions challenging women's ordination. Some conservatives said 
they were doubtful they could remain in the denomination (<I>Christian 
News,</I> 7/1/96).

<P>&#182; Dr. Bill Rudd, the new chairman of the General
Association of Regular Baptists' Council of Eighteen, is sending 
church members to Promise Keepers rallies. According to the <I>Muskegon</I> 
[Mich.] <I>Chronicle</I> (5/10/96) Rudd's associate pastor, Eric Strattan, 
"traveled with two bus loads of men sponsored by Calvary Baptist 
Church last year to attend the Promise Keepers rally in the [Pontiac, 
Michigan] Silverdome." This year the church planned to send three 
bus loads to the Silverdome rally in May.<BR>

&#160;&#160;&#160;Mark Jackson, the GARBC's outgoing interim
national representative, wrote in his final column in the
<I>Baptist Bulletin</I> (6/96) that Promise Keepers' Chicago
rally was "openly ecumenical" and "it is hard to understand how
so many of our Regular Baptist men are unwittingly involved"
(<I>Calvary Contender,</I> 8/1/96).

<A NAME = "SOC"></A><H2>Society</H2>

<P>&#182; Michael Card, "the Christian music industry's 
resident theologian," has produced a joint album with a leading Roman 
Catholic musician, John Michael Talbot. "<I>Brother to Brother</I> 
glows with a warm and joyous ecumenism," says <I>CCM</I> magazine 
(7/96). "Doing this project has enabled us to become real friends," 
says Card. "And along the way, the denominational lines have become 
really meaningless to me, and to John, too."<BR>

&#160;&#160;&#160;Card has authored four books and recorded
sixteen albums. Talbot, "Christian music's meditative monk,"
has authored nearly a dozen books on theology, recorded nearly
three dozen albums, and founded a Franciscan monastic community
in the Ozark mountains.

<P>&#182; A number of public schools are showing a video series
titled <I>The Power of Choice,</I> which uses the techniques 
of "values clarification" and "ethical decision-making" to undermine 
belief in moral absolutes. Traditional moral reasoning is skewed as 
old-fashioned and irrelevant. One video is titled "Raising Your Parents." 
The consensus of the group is that fathers and mothers should try 
to be "friends" and abandon their pretensions to authority (<I>AFA 
Journal,</I> 7/96).

<P>&#182; Alyson Publications has produced a sequel to the
infamous children's book <I>Daddy's Roommate.</I> Called <I>Daddy's 
Wedding,</I> it is designed for children ages 2 to 6. The illustrations 
include a homosexual kiss (<I>AFA Journal,</I> 8/96).

<P>&#182; Publishers Clearinghouse recently did a direct mail
promotion focusing on <I>Playboy</I> magazine. The mailing 
offered two pornographic books as free gifts, along with the magazine 
subscription. Customers can also order <I>Penthouse</I> magazine on 
its 800 number, but this fact is not mentioned in any promotions. 
Publishers Clearinghouse is known for its multi-million-dollar sweepstakes 
(<I>AFA Journal,</I> 8/96).

<HR>


<P><I>What in the World!</I> is published by <A HREF =
"http://www.bju.edu/">Bob Jones University,</A> Greenville, South
Carolina 29614 to help believers know what the devil is up to.
Free church subscriptions: 864-242-5100, ext. 3074

