<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
What in the World!
</TITLE>
<LINK REV="OWNER" HREF="mailto:bjup@bju.edu">
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<A NAME = "TOP"></A>
<H1 ALIGN = CENTER>
What in the World!
</H1>

<P ALIGN = CENTER>A news service prepared by <A HREF =
"http://www.bju.edu/">Bob Jones University</A> for the local church

<P ALIGN = CENTER>Volume 20, Number 05

<H4 ALIGN = CENTER>
[ <A HREF="#GOV">Government</A>
| <A HREF="#REL">Religion</A>
| <A HREF="#SOC">Society</A>
]
</H4>

<HR>


<A NAME = "GOV"></A><H2>Government</H2>

<P>&#182; The Federal Election Commission (FEC) 
has filed a lawsuit against the Christian Coalition for allegedly 
crossing the line dividing voter education and partisanship. The coalition 
distributes candidates' statements on various issues, without endorsing 
or opposing any candidate. Yet the FEC accused the Christian Coalition 
of producing its voter guides "in coordination, cooperation and/or 
consultation" with Republican campaigns. Money spent on such "express 
advocacy" for candidates must be reported as political contributions, 
the FEC said. Yet the FEC gave no specific evidence of the coalition's 
illegal "coordination" with candidates (<I>Conservative Chronicle,</I> 
8/14/96; <I>National Liberty Journal,</I> 9/96).

<P>&#182; Prolife protesters are still being arrested. 
The Rutherford Institute has asked the U.S. Supreme Court to hear 
two cases. One involves Marilyn Hatch, the first person charged with 
violating the Freedom of Access to Clinic Entrances Act (FACE). She 
participated in a protest next door to a Milwaukee abortion clinic. 
When arrested, she was sitting quietly praying and carrying a sign. 
The other case involves protesters who silently petitioned in a Fargo, 
North Dakota, neighborhood. Police charged them with violating an 
ordinance which prohibits protesting in front of a single residence. 
In a recent case the Supreme Court found that residential picketing 
is constitutional (<I>National Liberty Journal,</I> 9/96).

<P>&#182; Communist China is pursuing three simultaneous 
campaigns that have hurt Christians: a "spiritual civilization" 
campaign, an anti-crime campaign, and an anti-Western campaign. <I>Spiritual 
civilization</I> refers to traditional Chinese values of selflessness 
and virtue. "Though the campaign usually is rather dull and harmless, 
consisting of no more than pep talks on how to be selfless, sometimes 
it can take a sinister turn, where people are called upon to criticize 
and attack the foreign virus," warns Robin Munro of Human Rights 
Watch Asia.

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;In China's anti-crime campaign, Christians are soft targets 
for local party cadres who need to fill their quotas of arrests. Between 
April and June of this year, over 300 Christians were arrested for 
participating in "illegal" groups. China's anti-Western campaign 
attacks Christianity as a foreign influence. Officials fear the rising 
interest in religion among youths. "Religion has certainly moved 
to the center of the political stage," says China watcher Anthony 
Lambert. "Mao and other top leaders rarely bothered with religious 
policy, but now we see China's two main leaders--Li Peng and Jiang 
Zemin--personally involved with religious matters" (<I>Compass 
Direct,</I> 7/25/96).

<A NAME = "REL"></A><H2>Religion</H2>

<P>&#182; Hundreds of Buddhists and Christians 
from around the world gathered in Chicago this summer to explore ways 
to combat common problems, such as crime, poverty, and disease. DePaul 
University hosted the conference, "Socially Engaging Buddhism and 
Christianity."<BR>
&#160;&#160;&#160;"We can describe this century as a century of bloodshed, a century 
of war," said the Dalai Lama. "The next century should be a century 
of dialogue." One of the main Christian representatives was Tom Baima, 
director of the Office of Ecumenical and InterReligious Affairs for 
the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Chicago (<I>Insight,</I> 9/9/96).

<P>&#182; The design for the world's largest homosexual 
cathedral was unveiled July 8. Once completed, the $20-million Cathedral 
of Hope in Dallas, Texas, will be longer than two football fields, 
taller than Notre Dame, and have a seating capacity of 2,500. "No 
one has ever given gay people any sense of status or worth," explained 
the openly homosexual architect Philip Johnson, age 90. "I think 
this is exactly the right thing to be going for" (<I>Christian News,</I> 
7/15/96).

<P>&#182; A <I>60 Minutes</I> feature last Easter 
gave a "warm and sympathetic" picture of Mormonism, according to 
a report in <I>Christian Century</I> (8/14/96). Correspondent Mike 
Wallace opened the segment by announcing that the church was entering 
the mainstream. As the president of the Church of Jesus Christ of 
Latter-day Saints (LDS), Gordon B. Hinkley, told Wallace, Latter-day 
Saints are "not weird."

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;According to <I>Christian Century,</I> "Rather than speaking 
of themselves as Mormons, Latter-day Saints increasingly refer to 
themselves as Christians." A sign of this new attitude is the change 
of the LDS logo last year to emphasize the words "Jesus Christ." 
The church is removing from public view its rituals and distinctive 
theological claims--tiered heavens, proxy baptisms, and endless 
progression toward godhood.

<P>&#182; Orthodox, Roman Catholic, and mainline 
Protestant church leaders have signed a statement calling on the Senate 
to expand its war on global poverty by shifting money from military 
spending to foreign economic aid. The statement said modest reductions 
in defense spending would "likely enhance the actual security of 
Americans by helping lift the burden of poverty that continues to 
make much of the world desperate and therefore dangerous."

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;The 29 signers came from groups as diverse as the American 
Baptist Churches, the Reformed Church in America, and the Unitarian 
Universalist Service Committee (<I>Christian News,</I> 7/22/96).

<P>&#182; Women preachers can now baptize converts, 
officiate at communion, and perform weddings, following a historic 
vote at the general assembly of the 300,000-member Church of God of 
Prophecy. The denomination is "getting more in line with where most 
. . .  Pentecostal groups are," said Leed Grady, executive editor 
of Charisma. The only remaining major restriction on women is the 
ability to serve as bishops (<I>Christian News,</I> 7/22/96).  

<A NAME = "SOC"></A><H2>Society</H2>

<P>&#182; The National Education Association (NEA) 
passed its usual series of liberal, political resolutions at its annual 
convention in July. The NEA is the nation's largest union. Its delegates 
voted to endorse President Clinton for reelection by a 91% margin, 
a higher approval rating than he enjoys in the Democratic party. The 
NEA had more delegates at the Democratic National Convention than 
any state. The NEA's political action committee--the fifth 
largest in the nation--gave 99% of its money to Democrats in the 
1994 elections.

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;NEA resolutions continue to support abortion rights, homosexual 
rights, sex education for kindergartners, "global education," and 
preschool education in the public schools from birth through age eight. 
It continues to oppose "deleterious programs," such as tax credits 
for private schools and voucher plans. It still opposes standardized 
testing for students and competence testing for teachers (<I>Phyllis 
Schlafly Report,</I> 8/96).



<HR>


<P><I>What in the World!</I> is published by <A HREF =
"http://www.bju.edu/">Bob Jones University,</A> Greenville, South
Carolina 29614 to help believers know what the devil is up to.
Free church subscriptions: 864-242-5100, ext. 3074

