<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
What in the World!
</TITLE>
<LINK REV="OWNER" HREF="mailto:bjup@bju.edu">
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<A NAME = "TOP"></A>
<H1 ALIGN = CENTER>
What in the World!
</H1>

<P ALIGN = CENTER>A news service prepared by <A HREF =
"http://www.bju.edu/">Bob Jones University</A> for the local church

<P ALIGN = CENTER>Volume 20, Number 10

<H4 ALIGN = CENTER>
[ <A HREF="#GOV">Government</A>
| <A HREF="#REL">Religion</A>
| <A HREF="#SOC">Society</A>
]
</H4>

<HR>


<A NAME = "GOV"></A><H2>Government</H2>

<P>&#182; A 100-foot cross that has stood on San 
Francisco's highest peak for 60 years must be removed, while a 10-ton 
statue of a pagan Aztec serpent god, constructed at taxpayer expense 
in San Jose, California, may stay. A U.S. court of appeals made these 
rulings in separate cases last August (<I>Alliance Life,</I> 10/23/96).

<P>&#182; For the first time in the U.S., a judge 
has required a state to extend insurance benefits to homosexual couples. 
Judge Stephen L. Gallagher ruled on August 8 that Oregon Health Sciences 
University discriminated against the domestic partners of three homosexual 
employees. The judge said that the state must provide insurance to 
the partners of all homosexual state workers who sought coverage (<I>Baptist 
Challenge,</I> 10/96).

<P>&#182; The U.S. Supreme Court has agreed to decide 
whether states may allow doctor-assisted suicide. The court will 
hear arguments in cases from New York and Washington, states which 
allow doctors to prescribe life-ending drugs for mentally competent 
patients who are terminally ill. The court will probably rule on the 
cases next July (<I>Baptists Today,</I> 10/24/96).

<P>&#182; Leaders of the Orthodox church in Romania 
have set up a number of militia-like groups to terrorize minorities. 
According to the Romanian Evangelical Alliance, the groups break church 
windows, burn cars, and beat believers, often with the approval of 
the police and local politicians. A woman four months pregnant was 
beaten, thrown to the ground, and kicked in the stomach by an Orthodox 
priest and his followers "just because she was a Baptist," according 
to Iacob Dumitru, executive secretary of the alliance. Last Spring 
a radio station of the Romanian Missionary Society was temporarily 
closed after Orthodox Archbishop Pimen asked the government to intervene, 
calling the broadcasters "defilers of our forefathers' faith" (<I>Compass 
Direct,</I> 9/19/96).

<A NAME = "REL"></A><H2>Religion</H2>

<P>&#182; George Carey, the Church of England's 
archbishop of Canterbury, has lashed out at fundamentalists who place 
the Bible "above and beyond human inquiry." Carey says, "Maintain 
as high a doctrine of Scripture as you like, so long as your doctrine 
of Christ is higher." He also noted, "The Anglican Church is a broad 
church and there is room in our fellowship for great variety--for 
traditionalists, evangelicals, Anglo-Catholics, liberals, and charismatics" 
(<I>Evangelical Methodist,</I> 9/96).

<P>&#182; The Week of Prayer for Christian Unity 
in January has become an annual event in Rome. Pope John Paul II uses 
this week as an opportunity to participate in ecumenical events and 
to encourage efforts to reestablish visible unity among Christians. 
The pope culminates the week with a mass, inviting Orthodox, evangelical, 
Anglican, and mainline leaders to be present, although they do not 
share in the eucharist (<I>Ecumenical Trends,</I> 9/96).

<P>&#182; Twenty-one churches and religious groups 
in the former Soviet Union have agreed to form a Christian Interconfessional 
Consultative Committee. The committee will promote cooperation and 
mutual understanding among the Orthodox, Roman Catholic, and Protestant 
denominations (<I>Christian Century,</I> 10/23/96).

<P>&#182; A team of eight Southern Baptists recently 
met with eight Roman Catholics to discuss the inerrancy of Scripture. 
It was the second of a series of annual meetings aimed at clearing 
away misunderstandings. While both groups affirmed inerrancy, they 
had different definitions. Southern Baptists insisted on the Bible's 
historical accuracy, but the Catholic team saw inerrancy more as a 
matter of divinely inspired usefulness.<BR>
&#160;&#160;&#160;Next year's meeting will continue the discussion of Scripture, with 
detailed focus on the Vatican II document <I>Dei Verbum.</I> In succeeding 
years, the teams will examine soteriology, ecclesiology, missiology, 
and religious liberty (<I>Baptists Today,</I> 10/24/96).

<P>&#182; Conservative Southern Baptists in Virginia 
voted unanimously September 16 to form their own state convention. 
It appears to be the first time in the 151-year history of the SBC 
that a state has two competing conventions. "Moderates," who control 
the state convention, caused the split by shifting money to the liberal 
Cooperative Baptist Fellowship (<I>Indiana Baptist,</I> 9/24/96).

<P>&#182; Walt Kallestad, pastor of the fastest-growing 
Evangelical Lutheran Church in America, is planning to start a "hip, 
cutting edge television program aimed at young people 18-25 years 
old," reports <I>Arizona Republic</I> (8/24/96). "It is to be a 
fast-paced mix of music videos, on-the-scene broadcasts and the best 
in multimedia entertainment. . . . With help from the Billy Graham 
Evangelistic Association, Kallestad plans this winter to launch what 
may be the only religious broadcast of its kind in the country."

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;The program uses a new form of evangelism, called "entertainment 
evangelism," which Kallestad says is vital to the faith of the next 
generation. "If Jesus Christ were alive today," he claims,  "I'm 
certain he'd be using every form of entertainment that's out there 
to make God relevant and practical in people's lives." Kallestad's 
Community Church of Joy attracts 1,100 new members per year (<I>Christian 
News,</I> 9/23/96).

<A NAME = "SOC"></A><H2>Society</H2>

<P>&#182; Family Bookstores, a chain of 183 Christian 
stores, is "aggressively" stocking "alternative Christian music," 
says Bob Elder, senior music buyer for Family Bookstores. "A new 
crop of singers and songwriters . . . are exploring the fringes of 
Christian faith," says <I>Christianity Today</I> (10/7/96). "Christian 
alternative artists as a group have focused on innovative music and 
imaginative song lyrics, rather than words and harmonies now familiar 
in contemporary Christian music." The Christian music industry is 
taking steps to make Christian alternative bands more marketable. 
"You want to reach young listeners because they're your future customers," 
said Family Bookstores' Elder.

<P>&#182; A researcher for People for the American 
Way quit his job this summer because his conscience would not let 
him continue to "cook" numbers about censorship by the Religious 
Right. Marc Herman's essay in the October issue of <I>Harper's</I> 
caused a stir. He revealed that in 1993, when he told a superior that 
censorship appeared to be easing up, "he told me that he had faith 
I could make things look worse, that we needed to make it look worse. 
So I did" (<I>World,</I> 10/19/96).

<P>&#182; Last August a doctor in London aborted 
only one of two children in a mother's womb because she "couldn't 
afford twins." The British Medical Authority (BMA) did not oppose 
the abortion because it involved the "health of the mother," who 
was suffering from anxiety (<I>Law & Justice,</I> vol. 5, #9).

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;Although seldom discussed, fetal reduction has become
common in the United States. "We probably are doing an average of one to 
two a week," claims Dr. Norman Ginsberg, a fertility specialist at 
Chicago's Illinois Masonic Medical Center. He has been conducting 
the procedure since the early 1980s. The procedure has become common 
among women who receive several through in vitro fertilization in 
hopes that at least one will survive (<I>National Liberty Journal,</I> 
10/96).

<P>&#182; As many as 35,000 women and girls--some 
as young as age 8--are being held as sex slaves by traditional 
religious leaders in the West African nations of Ghana, Togo, Benin, 
and Nigeria. The Anti-Slavery Society of Australia reports that females 
are given voluntarily by their families "in order to appease the 
gods and to atone for wrongs committed by their relatives, usually 
male relations" (<I>Baptists Today,</I> 10/24/96).

<P>&#182; A list of the top ten sponsors of sex, 
violence, and profanity on prime time network television was compiled 
after a watchdog group monitored the networks from May 5 to June 1. 
The top sponsor was Sony, followed by such big names as Hyundai (#4), 
Merrill Lynch (#5), MCI (#7), Toyota (#8), and Honda (#10) (<I>AFA 
Journal,</I> 9/96).

<P>&#182; Michael Eisner, chairman of the Walt Disney 
Company, is on the board of trustees of a homosexual advocacy group 
called Hollywood Supports. Two other managers from Walt Disney belong 
to the board--the president and the chairman of the motion pictures 
department. This fact casts serious doubts on the company's assertions 
that it does not cater to the homosexual lifestyle (<I>AFA Journal,</I> 
9/96).

<P>&#182; Hollywood is turning to a new group to 
embody the forces of evil: Christians. According to an article in 
<I>World</I> (9/21/96), "Hollywood has been facing a villain crisis. 
Formula plots require bad guys, but now that the Soviet Union has 
folded, Communist spies pose little threat, while depicting Middle 
Eastern terrorists comes across as politically incorrect ethnic stereotyping." 
A new movie depicts a "nightmarish future vision" of American under 
the control of the Religious Right.

<P>&#182; A recent expos&eacute; in <I>Charisma</I> 
(11/96) describes how "some of the nation's most popular celebrities 
are out to win souls for the occult." Shirley MacLaine is the "grande 
dame of Hollywood New Age spokespersons," but a new crop of stars 
has arisen. Scientology, a combination of high-tech Buddhism and New 
Age ideas, has "taken Hollywood by storm." Stars who publicly subscribe 
to Scientology include John Travolta, Kristie Alley, Tom Cruise, and 
his wife Nicole Kidman. Travolta's recent success has given him a 
chance to testify how Scientology has changed his life for the better.

<P>&#182; Peter Kreeft, an ecumenical Roman Catholic 
priest and author, is quoted in the <I>CEC Journal</I> (9-10/96): 
"But there is a fourth way Mary links us to Christ; literally by 
her blood. . . . Christ's literal blood, which redeemed us, was our 
blood because it was Mary's blood. . . . Christ took our blood only 
because He took Mary's blood. So he shed his own blood, our human 
race's blood, to redeem us, to redeem the human race through the mediation 
of Mary" (<I>Calvary Contender,</I> 11/1/96).



<HR>


<P><I>What in the World!</I> is published by <A HREF =
"http://www.bju.edu/">Bob Jones University,</A> Greenville, South
Carolina 29614 to help believers know what the devil is up to.
Free church subscriptions: 864-242-5100, ext. 3074

