<HEAD>
<TITLE>
What in the World!
</TITLE>
<LINK REV="OWNER" HREF="mailto:bjup@bju.edu">
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<A NAME = "TOP"></A>
<H1 ALIGN = CENTER>
What in the World!
</H1>

<P ALIGN = CENTER>A news service prepared by <A HREF =
"http://www.bju.edu/">Bob Jones University</A> for the local church

<P ALIGN = CENTER>Volume 20, Number 11

<H4 ALIGN = CENTER>
[ <A HREF="#GOV">Government</A>
| <A HREF="#REL">Religion</A>
| <A HREF="#SOC">Society</A>
]
</H4>

<HR>


<A NAME = "GOV"></A><H2>Government</H2>

<P>&#182; The National Endowment for the Arts and 
the National Endowment for the Humanities will be funded at the same 
levels as last year. Though the Republican-controlled House and Senate 
voted to reduce the 1997 budget, the money was restored by the House-Senate 
conference committee. Although a few safeguards against controversial 
art were implemented, last year's explicit ban against funding offensive 
material was quietly dropped (<I>World,</I> 11/2/96).

<P>&#182; A Louisiana judge is allowing four liberal 
religion professors at Louisiana Baptist College to sue conservatives 
in the Louisiana Baptist Convention who sent out "malicious and derogatory" 
letters about the professors in an attempt to "deprive them of public 
confidence." Judge Tom Yeager rejected claims that the case should 
be thrown out of court as a church-state matter. The judge wrote, 
"The petitioners are not ministers of a 'church,' but rather professors 
at Louisiana College. The Louisiana Baptist Convention is not a 'church,' 
but rather an association of 'messengers' from various Baptist churches 
in Louisiana" (<I>Baptists Today,</I> 10/24/96).

<P>&#182; Evangelists to the Mormons in Utah have 
filed suit against state officials and city police officers who allegedly 
harassed them at the Utah State Fair. For the past eight years, Kurt 
and Cindy Van Gorden have set up an information booth at the state 
fair. On September 14 of this year, state fair officials ordered the 
couple to turn off their video camera, saying it violated a contract 
they had signed prohibiting photography. The couple maintained that 
their contract allowed them to monitor their exhibit as a theft deterrent.

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;As the dispute unfolded Cindy Van Gorden began taking snapshots. 
The suit alleges that police and security guards knocked her down 
and searched inside her blouse for her camera after she refused to 
relinquish it. The suit also alleges that she was handcuffed and questioned 
without having been read her rights (<I>Christianity Today,</I> 11/11/96).

<P>&#182; Vietnam's growing house church movement 
experienced a summer of persecution after the Communist Party demanded 
a harder line on religion in June. House church leaders in Ho Chi 
Minh City told <I>Compass Direct</I> (10/17/96), "Our leaders are 
not just detained for a few days, but are sentenced to three years 
in jail." Thirteen house church leaders are known to be serving a 
minimum of 20 months each.

<A NAME = "REL"></A><H2>Religion</H2>

<P>&#182; A woman preached from the pulpit during 
Founder's Week activities for Moody Bible Institute. The office of 
Dr. Joseph Stowell III, the school president, defended the school's 
actions: "The Moody Bible Institute does not believe that a woman 
should be ordained to the authority of the pastorate, but that a woman 
may function in the specific role of preaching. She may not have the 
authority of the pastorate, but she may preach the Word of God from 
the pulpit of a local church" (<I>Keystone Baptist,</I> 8/96).

<P>&#182; Six hundred people participated in the 
second annual State of the World Forum, held in San Francisco, October 
2-6. Last year Mikhail Gorbachev, former Communist leader of 
the Soviet Union, brought Ted Turner, George Bush, Bill 
Gates, and other world leaders to the forum to form a "global brain 
trust."<BR>
&#160;&#160;&#160;This year a "council of the wise" laid the "ground rules for 
resolving disputes and problems" around the world. In his welcoming 
address, Gorbachev told the crowd, "If we leave the world to its 
own devices . . . it will mean new sufferings, the death of many people 
from hunger, epidemics and wars." He asserted, "The alternative 
to the existing world order can only emerge as a result of a new human 
dimension of progress. . . . We envision a revolution of the mind, 
a new way of thinking" (<I>Christian News,</I> 11/4/96).

<P>&#182; The Council of Christians and Jews (CCJ), 
a British interfaith body, has banned evangelizing among its members. 
CCJ presidents include the archbishop of Canterbury, George Carey, 
and the archbishop of Westminster. Basil Hume, a Roman Catholic cardinal 
in the CCJ, has threatened to expel anyone who uses the council for 
missionary activity. Paul Mendel, CCJ director, explained the ban: 
"There has been infiltration into some of our branches of people 
who by their presence upset others and disrupt the branches. If one 
wants to missionise, there are other places and other times" (<I>Christian 
News,</I> 10/28/96).

<P>&#182; Mary Mild, the new director for personnel 
services in the American Baptist Church, bemoans the fact than only 
5% of American Baptist pastors are women. In an interview with ABC's 
<I>WATCHword</I> (Fall 1996), she said, "It's my strong belief that 
every church should have two pastors--one woman and one man." 
The ABC is a member of the liberal World Council of Churches (<I>Calvary 
Contender,</I> 11/15/96).

<A NAME = "SOC"></A><H2>Society</H2>

<P>&#182; Walt Disney Company is closely involved 
in Hollywood Supports, a homosexual advocacy group that helps companies 
to form homosexual employee groups and to implement insurance plans 
that pay for live-in homosexual partners. The board of trustees of 
Hollywood Supports includes Disney's chairman Michael Eisner, Disney's 
president, and the chairman of Disney's motion pictures department 
(<I>AFA Journal,</I> 9/96).

<P>&#182; Word Records has kept Sandi Patty under 
contract even after she admitted to years of adultery with backup 
singer Don Peslis. Both divorced their spouses and married on August 
6, 1995. Patty's albums were pulled from the shelves during the 1995 
Christmas season, but a new Christmas album, <I>O Holy Night</I>, 
has now been released (<I>CCM,</I> 10/95; <I>Aspire,</I> 12/96-1/97).

<P>&#182; "Some of the nation's most popular celebrities 
are out to win souls for the occult," says an article in <I>Charisma</I> 
(11/96). Shirley MacLaine is the "grande dame of Hollywood New Age 
spokespersons," but a new crop of stars has arisen. Scientology, 
a combination of high-tech Buddhism and New Age ideas, has "taken 
Hollywood by storm." Movie stars who publicly subscribe to Scientology 
include John Travolta, Kirstie Alley, Tom Cruise, and his wife Nicole 
Kidman. With his recent film successes, Travolta has been testifying 
how Scientology changed his life.

<P>&#182; Australia's Northern Territory has allowed 
the world's first legally assisted suicide. Bob Dent, 66, who was 
suffering from cancer, was allowed to take deadly drugs under a euthanasia 
law passed earlier this year (<I>Baptists Today,</I> 10/24/96).



<HR>

