<HEAD>
<TITLE>
What in the World!
</TITLE>
<LINK REV="OWNER" HREF="mailto:bjup@bju.edu">
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<A NAME = "TOP"></A>
<H1 ALIGN = CENTER>
What in the World!
</H1>

<P ALIGN = CENTER>A news service prepared by <A HREF =
"http://www.bju.edu/">Bob Jones University</A> for the local church

<P ALIGN = CENTER>Volume 19, Number 09

<H4 ALIGN = CENTER>
[ <A HREF="#GOV">Government</A>
| <A HREF="#REL">Religion</A>
| <A HREF="#SOC">Society</A>
]
</H4>

<HR>


<A NAME = "GOV"></A><H2>Government</H2>

<P>&#182; On April 2 a federal appeals court struck 
down New York's ban on physician-assisted suicide. One month earlier 
another appeals court struck down a similar law in Washington state. 
The court said that the New York law is not "rationally related to 
any legitimate state interest." According to the ruling, the law 
violates the equal protection clause of the Fourteenth Amendment because 
the state has made an irrational distinction between withdrawing treatment 
and direct killing (<I>NRL News,</I> 4/12/96).

<P>&#182; Barrington, Rhode Island, will not collect 
trash at churches any more, news reports said. The town ended the 
weekly pickups after the American Civil Liberties Union filed a federal 
lawsuit on behalf of several residents who claimed that providing 
such taxpayer-funded services violates the Constitution (<I>NIRR,</I> 
4/1/96).

<P>&#182; A "parental rights" movement has arisen 
following well-publicized clashes between parents and the government 
over such issues as sex and values education, condom distribution, 
AIDS testing, abortion counseling, home schooling, and corporal punishment. 
A coalition combating efforts to affirm parental rights includes the 
National Education Association, the Parent-Teacher Association, the 
American Civil Liberties Union, the National Abortion and Reproductive 
Rights Action League, and Americans United for Separation of Church 
and State. Child-welfare organizations are also concerned about restrictions 
on their ability to investigate child abuse. During its recent term, 
the U.S. Supreme Court let stand three lower-court decisions against 
parental rights.

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;At least 28 state legislatures are considering legislation 
that promote family rights. Congress is also considering a "Parental 
Rights and Responsibility Act" (<I>Christian News,</I> 4/29/96).

<P>&#182; A new campaign has been launched to force 
churches to comply with IRS rules on political activity. Americans 
United for Separation of Church and State (AU) is calling its campaign 
Project Fair Play. The first target is a large Southern Baptist church 
in Texas. AU is urging the IRS to investigate Second Baptist Church 
in Houston, which has encouraged members to vote for particular candidates 
in the Republican party.<BR>
&#160;&#160;&#160;"Most American churches responsibly comply with IRS rules barring 
partisan politicking," said Barry Lynn,  the head of AU. "But those 
who don't should give up their tax-exempt status" (<I>Baptists Today,</I> 
4/4/96).

<A NAME = "REL"></A><H2>Religion</H2>

<P>&#182; Practicing homosexuals could be ordained 
to the ministry in certain circumstances, according to a report by 
the Evangelical Church in Germany (EKD). The report says such ordinations 
should only happen in "individual cases" where there is an "ethically 
responsible" homosexual lifestyle. The 24 members of the EKD represent 
the overwhelming majority of Protestants in Germany (<I>Christian 
News,</I> 4/8/96).

<P>&#182; The Promise Keepers "men's movement" 
has inspired cooperative programs in various denominations, including 
the Southern Baptist Convention and the Roman Catholic Church. The 
SBC's Brotherhood Commission has launched Men's Ministries. The Catholic 
church has developed two separate men's groups: Saint Joseph's Covenant 
Keepers and Ministry to Black Catholic Men. PK representatives have 
been invited to speak at an upcoming Catholic men's conference in 
Steubenville, Ohio.

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;In spite of his support for PK, Jim Burton of the Brotherhood 
Commission is concerned about the shifting loyalties of men who attend 
PK's large rallies. "Some of our guys come home wearing shirts and 
hats, and they want to start Promise Keepers groups rather than work 
as a member of their local church," Burton says. "Some of these 
guys identify themselves as Promise Keepers, and they see themselves 
as separate from other men's ministries in the church" (<I>Christianity 
Today,</I> 4/29/96).

<P>&#182; Atheism is the fastest growing American 
belief, says a recent report in <I>Washington Times</I>. Up to 8% 
of adult Americans now say they are atheists. At the 55th annual convention 
of the America Humanist Association, the Humanist of the Year Award 
went to Richard Dawkins, a biologist and writer from Oxford University. 
"Science has all the virtues of religion, but none of its vices," 
he said in his keynote address. "The main vice of religion is faith." 
To inculcate minors with religion is akin to "mental child abuse," 
he said (<I>Christian News,</I> 3/18/96).

<P>&#182; "Mainline Protestant clergy seem to be 
drifting in an even more liberal theological direction," concludes 
a six-year survey of nearly 8,000 pastors in eight denominations, 
ranging from the Southern Baptist Convention to the Presbyterian Church 
(USA). "The theological divide among Protestant clergy is probably 
widening, as those in the conservative denominations remain relatively 
stable in beliefs and identifications" (<I>Christianity Today,</I> 
4/29/96).

<A NAME = "SOC"></A><H2>Society</H2>

<P>&#182; Roman Catholics at Pat Robertson's Regent 
University set up the Stations of the Cross on the campus lawn on 
Good Friday. "It's been wonderful to witness [other] Christian students 
come out here and watch us. They realize we love the Lord as much 
as they do," said Keith Fournier, executive director of the American 
Center for Law and Justice, which is located on the school grounds 
(<I>NIRR,</I> 4/15/96).

<P>&#182; During an ABC interview with presidential 
candidate Patrick Buchanan, George Will asked about teaching creationism 
in public schools. Samuel Donaldson chimed in, "Did He do it in six 
days?" When Buchanan replied, "God did it, Sam, according to the 
Bible," Donaldson retorted, "That's what the Bible says, Mr. Buchanan. 
Said He did it in six days, and the seventh day, He rested." At the 
close of the program, Will commented, "Pat Buchanan economics are 
the equivalent of creationism . . . no serious person believes it" 
(<I>Human Events,</I> 3/1/96).

<P>&#182; Half (49%) of born-again Christians in 
America believe "the devil, or Satan, is not a living being but is 
a symbol of evil," according to a new Barna survey. Four in ten (39%) 
believe that "if a person is generally good, or does enough good 
things for others during their life, they will earn a place in heaven." 
Three in ten (30%) claim that "Jesus Christ was a great teacher, 
but he did not come back to physical life after he was crucified." 
A similar number (29%) believe that "when he lived on earth, Jesus 
Christ was human and committed sins, like other people." Surprisingly 
only 15% of born-again Americans <I>disagree</I> with the statement 
that "the Bible is totally accurate in all of its teachings" (<I>Baptist 
Bible Tribune</I>, 4/15/96).



<HR>


<P><I>What in the World!</I> is published by <A HREF =
"http://www.bju.edu/">Bob Jones University,</A> Greenville, South
Carolina 29614 to help believers know what the devil is up to.
Free church subscriptions: 864-242-5100, ext. 3074

