<HEAD>
<TITLE>
What in the World!
</TITLE>
<LINK REV="OWNER" HREF="mailto:bjup@bju.edu">
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<A NAME = "TOP"></A>
<H1 ALIGN = CENTER>
What in the World!
</H1>

<P ALIGN = CENTER>A news service prepared by <A HREF =
"http://www.bju.edu/">Bob Jones University</A> for the local church

<P ALIGN = CENTER>Volume 19, Number 12

<H4 ALIGN = CENTER>
[ <A HREF="#GOV">Government</A>
| <A HREF="#REL">Religion</A>
| <A HREF="#SOC">Society</A>
]
</H4>

<HR>


<A NAME = "GOV"></A><H2>Government</H2>

<P>&#182; Efforts to tax church property seem to 
be widening. The first publicized effort is a referendum in Colorado 
that will be voted on in November. Now Syracuse, New York, has joined 
the fight. The mayor has pointed out that 58.7% of all property in 
the city is tax-exempt, and the city suffered a $16 million shortfall 
last year. So Mayor Roy Bernardi is proposing that non-profit institutions 
such as churches, universities, and hospitals, pay a "core service 
fee" to cover such basic services as road maintenance and police 
protection (<I>Baptists Today</I>, 5/23/96).

<P>&#182; On April 12 a judge in Los Angeles granted 
a homosexual man custody of a retarded eight-year-old girl over the 
protest of her biological mother, whose visitation rights were also 
limited to a single phone call a week. The judge ruled that the man 
would provide a better home than the mother, who has other children 
living with her (<I>World,</I> 4/20/96).

<P>&#182; Christian landlords cannot use their religious 
beliefs as a reason not to rent to unmarried couples, the California 
Supreme Court has ruled. The case involved Chico landlady Evelyn Smith, 
a Presbyterian, who refused to rent to unmarried couples out of fear 
that God would judge her. The state's department of fair employment 
and housing had ruled that California's open-housing law prohibited 
landlords from asking prospective tenants their marital status. A 
state appeals court then overturned the ruling, finding that the Religious 
Freedom Restoration Act supersedes state open-housing laws. But the 
supreme court rejected the lower court's arguments (<I>NIRR</I>, 4/29/96).

<P>&#182; Social services departments around the 
country are exceeding their constitutional authority to enter homes, 
interview children, and even do physical examinations of naked children. 
Upon a report of physical or sexual abuse, regardless of whether it 
is corroborated, it is routine for many departments to insist upon 
inspection of the home, interviews with children, and physical examinations 
by the social worker. But these departments do not have this authority, 
according to the Home School Legal Defense Association (<I>Teaching 
Home</I>, 5-6/96).

<A NAME = "REL"></A><H2>Religion</H2>

<P>&#182; A charismatic pastor in Detroit has begun 
blessing water and serving it to parishioners. Since mid-December, 
hundreds of people have claimed to be healed of physical, emotional, 
and spiritual problems after drinking the "miracle water."Wayne 
T. Jackson believes the Holy Spirit told him that He would begin to 
perform miracles through something as simple as a cup of water.<BR>
&#160;&#160;&#160;After doctors confirmed several healings, the media picked up the 
story. Since then, calls have flooded the ministry from people seeking 
help, including politicians, celebrities and doctors. Because of overflow 
crowds, the ministry has had to book convention centers and arenas 
for special meetings <I>(Charisma</I>, 6/96).

<P>&#182; Last February Desmond Tutu, Archbishop 
of South Africa, became the highest-ranking Anglican to call for the 
ordination of practicing homosexuals. He repeated his support in a 
foreword to a collection of liturgies for homosexuals, called <I>We 
Were Baptized Too</I>, which includes a "celebration of coming out" 
(<I>Christian News,</I> 2/19/96).

<P>&#182; The 15th National Workshop on Christian-Jewish 
Relations, to be held October 27-30, is expected to draw 1,500 to 
2,000 participants. "This is the largest gathering of Jews and Christians 
in the world for conciliation, understanding and collaboration," 
said Rabbi Robert Lennick of Greenwich, one of the conveners. The 
theme of the conference is "Seeking God: The Challenge of Being Religious 
in America." Cosponsors include the Home Mission Board of the Southern 
Baptist Convention, the National Council of Churches, the National 
Conference of Catholic Bishops, and the American Jewish Committee. 
This year some Muslims are expected to attend (<I>Christian News,</I> 
2/26/96).

<P>&#182; A Catholic youth evangelist is coordinating 
a huge interdenominational outreach at the Olympics. As chairman of 
the Youth Executive Committee for the North American Renewal Service 
Committee (NARSC), Jim Murphy will bring together mainline Protestants, 
nondenominational Christians, Pentecostals, and charismatic Catholics. 
NARSC plans to establish prayer sites throughout greater Atlanta and 
to hold informal concerts and rallies to follow up street witnessing 
(<I>Charisma</I>, 6/96).

<A NAME = "SOC"></A><H2>Society</H2>

<P>&#182; "Leaders of contemporary Christian music 
are worried about the meaning of their success." This is the subject 
of a series of interviews by James Long, a columnist for <I>CCM</I> 
magazine, published in <I>Christianity Today</I> (5/20/96). Musician 
Michael Card says, "When I look at Christian music as an industry, 
I'm always discouraged by it. The direction and value system are getting 
worse faster than any of us can imagine. There's no community in Christian 
music, but instead there's competition, commercialism, and individualism." 
He continues, "The lyrics of a good number of the songs don't betray 
anything specially Christian--they may have some moral message, 
but not a lot of the big songs are identifiably Christian."<BR>
&#160;&#160;&#160;Stan Moser, who quit as CEO for Star Song Records last November 
after 26 years in CCM, said, "To be candid, I look at the majority 
of the music I hear today and think it's virtually meaningless." 
He adds, "There is a growing chasm between CCM and the church--between 
what's actually happening in the real world of ministry, or even in 
the music ministry of the church, and what we're doing in CCM. In 
fact, I would probably be more inclined to call the industry '<I>commercial</I> 
Christian music,' rather than 'contemporary Christian music.' "

<P>&#182; Some 200 hymns and Christmas carols should 
be dropped from the Church of Scotland's hymnbook because they contain 
outdated theological concepts or exclusivist language, a church committee 
has recommended. For example "God Rest Ye Merry Gentlemen" was considered 
offensive because it ignores women (<I>NIRR,</I> 5/13/96).

<P>&#182; Christmas, Thanksgiving, and the Fourth 
of July were not among the dates to remember in a calendar published 
by the California Teachers Association. The union calendar did include 
Buddha's birthday, Gay and Lesbian Pride Month, and the Commemoration 
of the World War II Internment of Japanese-Americans (<I>Christian 
News</I>, 5/6/96).

<P>&#182; Several major companies are helping to 
launch new homosexual publications on the World Wide Web. Apple Computer 
has been listed as a "founding sponsor" of the online version of 
Out. AT&amp;T is a sponsor of GaySource (<I>AFA Journal,</I> 4/96). 



<HR>


