<HEAD>
<TITLE>
What in the World!
</TITLE>
<LINK REV="OWNER" HREF="mailto:bjup@bju.edu">
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<A NAME = "TOP"></A>
<H1 ALIGN = CENTER>
What in the World!
</H1>

<P ALIGN = CENTER>A news service prepared by <A HREF =
"http://www.bju.edu/">Bob Jones University</A> for the local church

<P ALIGN = CENTER>Volume 20, Number 12

<H4 ALIGN = CENTER>
[ <A HREF="#GOV">Government</A>
| <A HREF="#REL">Religion</A>
| <A HREF="#SOC">Society</A>
]
</H4>

<HR>


<A NAME = "GOV"></A><H2>Government</H2>

<P>&#182; A church-state case that could have national 
ramifications is working its way through state courts in South Carolina. 
Herb Silverman was denied an application to become a notary public 
because he crossed out the word <I>God.</I> An atheist, Silverman 
argues that the state requirement to acknowledge a "supreme being" 
violates his right to religious liberty (<I>Baptists Today,</I> 11/7/96).

<P>&#182; San Francisco has proposed a law to license 
group sex clubs if they provide "safe-sex" monitors and paraphernalia. 
Supervisor Tom Ammiano said the law was not designed to promote sex, 
but to help prevent the spread of AIDS and other sexually transmitted 
diseases (<I>Christian News,</I> 11/4/96).

<P>&#182; The Canadian Supreme Court has agreed 
to hear an appeal by a homosexual who was fired by a Christian college. 
Delwin Vriend was dismissed as a laboratory coordinator in 1991 after 
the King's University College in Edmonton, Alberta, discovered he 
was homosexual (<I>National Liberty Journal,</I> 11/96).

<A NAME = "REL"></A><H2>Religion</H2>

<P>&#182; The evangelical magazine <I>Christianity 
Today</I> (11/11/96) devoted a full-page "memoriam" to Henri J. Nouwen, 
a Roman Catholic theologian who died September 21. The introduction 
stated: "Acknowledged as one of the world's great spiritual writers, 
the renowned Catholic theologian left behind a wealth of insights 
that have brought encouragement and ministered to thousands."

<P>&#182; A presbytery of the Presbyterian Church 
(USA) in Greater Atlanta has voted to retain Erin Swensen on the clergy 
roles even though she has had a sex change. The denomination first 
ordained Eric Swensen in 1973. This is the first time that any mainline 
church has upheld the ordination of a transsexual (<I>Christian News,</I> 
11/4/96).

<P>&#182; The Association of Theological Schools 
has pressured Southern Baptist Theological Seminary to alter its hiring 
policy. In 1995 the association cited Southern for "deficiencies 
requiring remediation" after president Al Mohler and school trustees 
refused to hire a man who held liberal views on homosexuality, abortion, 
and women in ministry. The trustees have agreed to allow faculty members 
to interview and evaluate teaching candidates, although the president 
and trustees still have final say (<I>Baptists Today,</I> 11/7/96).

<P>&#182; A recent issue of<I> Christianity Today</I> 
(11/11/96) featured the ministry of Chris Seay, 24, who pastors "one 
of the most successful new churches in Texas." Seay, who wears sneakers, 
baggy jeans, and a bland shirt, "looks more like the lead singer 
for an alternative rock band" than a successful pastor, the article 
says.

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;He delivers his talk on a stool in the middle of the  stage 
"in a spontaneous and self-deprecating style, borrowed in part from 
TV's David Letterman." A recent talk was typical--"a meandering 
monologue based on the R-rated Richard Gere movie <I>Primal Fear.</I>"

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;According to the article, the church is "trying to translate 
the gospel into a language that is relevant for the baby busters." 
Seay is a third-generation Southern Baptist minister. He launched 
University Baptist Church in January 1995. The church, located near 
Baylor University, now attracts nearly 1,100 young people for Sunday 
services.

<P>&#182; Wicca, which centers on goddess worship, 
is generally considered the largest and fastest growing "neopagan 
movement," according to <I>New Age Journal</I> (9-10/96). Wicca is 
practicing its faith more openly, according to sociologist Mary Jo 
Neitz, who has studied the movement since 1987. Large festivals attract 
many visitors. There are also "public teaching covens," where inquirers 
can learn about Wicca without joining. Some Wiccan groups, such as 
the Aquarian Tabernacle Church near Seattle, have large, public worship 
services. A Wiccan seminary in Nashua, New Hampshire, offers classes 
and home study. The Church and School of Wicca in New Bern, North 
Carolina, offers a 12-lesson witchcraft correspondence course (<I>Christian 
News,</I> 10/28/96).

<P>&#182; In a statement released October 24, Jerry 
Falwell confirmed that Thomas Road Baptist Church, Lynchburg, Virginia, 
has begun sending money to the Southern Baptist Convention ($1,000 
per month). Half the money goes to the national convention and the 
rest goes to the new state convention that broke away from the liberals 
in September.

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;Falwell explained his decision: "While we have no intention 
of discontinuing our support to our missionaries who are affiliated 
with many different fellowships and faith mission boards, we fully 
intend to take our permanent stand with the national and Virginia 
Bible-believing conservatives who have rescued the Southern Baptist 
Convention from theological liberalism. Thomas Road Baptist Church 
will continue to be what Southern Baptist churches have always been--independent 
and autonomous. We are now happy to work in voluntary cooperation 
with Southern Baptist churches."

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;Falwell's spokesman, Mark DeMoss, later denied reports that 
Falwell had joined the SBC: "The church maintains its independence 
and did not join the Convention." Falwell told his congregation that 
he did not know at the time he gave the first $1,000 contribution 
that monetary gifts earn a church voting rights within the convention 
(<I>Sword of the Lord,</I> 11/15/96).

<A NAME = "SOC"></A><H2>Society</H2>

<P>&#182; Jars of Clay, whose 1995 debut album 
became a platinum seller, has been performing in secular 21-and-over 
clubs. In an interview with CCM (11/96), lead vocalist Dan Haseltine 
defended the band: "We've tried hard to break that separation 
of Christian band and mainstream band because as far as we're concerned 
there really shouldn't be that separation. We don't want our music 
to be just for the Christian marketplace."

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;Greg Frey, music buyer for Baptist Bookstores, supports Jars 
of Clay: "There would be no reason that we would pull something from 
a shelf just because they're visiting those types of venues. If they 
can do what they're doing out there and still maintain their commitment, 
it's great." Bob Elder, the senior buyer for Family Bookstores, agrees, 
"I couldn't be happier with who they are and what they've done and 
how meek they've been about it."

<P>&#182; Seventy percent of the nation's 46 million 
smokers try to quit each year but less than one third succeed, according 
to the Centers for Disease Control. Smoking-related diseases claim 
an estimated 419,000 American lives each year (<I>Christian News,</I> 
11/4/96).



<HR>

