<TITLE>
What in the World!
</TITLE>
<LINK REV="OWNER" HREF="mailto:bjup@bju.edu">
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<A NAME = "TOP"></A>
<H1 ALIGN = CENTER>
What in the World!
</H1>

<P ALIGN = CENTER>A news service prepared by <A HREF =
"http://www.bju.edu/">Bob Jones University</A> for the local church

<P ALIGN = CENTER>Volume 20, Number 02

<H4 ALIGN = CENTER>
[ <A HREF="#GOV">Government</A>
| <A HREF="#REL">Religion</A>
| <A HREF="#SOC">Society</A>
]
</H4>

<HR>

<A NAME = "GOV"></A><H2>Government</H2>

<P>&#182; Lawton Chiles, Democratic governor of Florida, has
vetoed a bill that would have allowed voluntary student prayer
at graduations and other school events. "It is better for us to
reverently honor prayer as individuals, in our places of
worship, in our homes and in our hearts," the veto message said
(Greenville [S.C.] News, 6/1/96).

<P>&#182; Sculptures of Noah and Jonah's whale will be removed
during a proposed facelift of the Children's Zoo in New York's
Central Park, according to First Things. The committee in
charge of redesigning the zoo says the statues reflect a
religious theme and public funds should not be used. Park
Commissioner Henry J. Stern argues that Noah should not be
viewed as a biblical character, but as the first
conservationist and should stay (AFA Journal, 7/96).

<P>&#182; A U.S. district judge has ordered a Mississippi
school district to stop allowing prayers over the school
intercom and classroom prayers before lunch. "The Bill of
Rights was created to protect the minority from tyranny by the
majority," Judge Neal Biggers said. School officials "may not
facilitate, participate in, endorse, encourage, invite or
sponsor classroom prayer by students." Biggers also ordered the
district to stop teaching classes called Bible or A Biblical
History of the Middle East.  American History classes may not
show the videotapes The King Is Born, He Is Risen, or America's
Godly Heritage (Baptists Today, 6/27/96).

<P>&#182; On May 21 Hungary's parliament adopted legislation
giving homosexuals in long-term relationships legal and
financial rights equal to those granted heterosexuals. "It is
another sign of the Americanization of attitudes and lifestyle
which is gathering pace throughout Eastern Europe," lamented
Lorant Hegedus, head of the Reformed Church in Hungary
(Christian News, 6/3/96 & 6/10/96).

<A NAME = "REL"></A><H2>Religion</H2>

<P>&#182; The general secretary of the World Alliance of
Reformed Churches has given his backing to a proposal for a
universal Christian council to resolve the issues dividing the
church. "The year 2000 is a special opportunity for Catholic,
Orthodox, Protestant and Pentecostal Christians to begin a
process leading to a universal council. The ultimate goal of
such a council is a common confession of faith and the
celebration of the Eucharist together," he said (ENI, 6/27/96).

<P>&#182; Brother Andrew, famous for smuggling Bibles behind
the Iron Curtain, explains his witnessing strategy to Muslims:
"I find it so easy now to pray with Muslim fundamentalists. I'm
not saying I'm one of them or they are one of us. I'm saying
there are no barriers. I can only enter into their world of
thinking if I have a theology that makes them no less than I
am. And I realize they can never love my Savior if they do not
first love me. So I do everything to get into their circles and
then they accept me. Then I present Christ to them, and they
will accept Christ as Savior" (Compass Direct, 5/30/96).

<P>&#182; It is estimated that there are as many Buddhists in
America as there are Episcopalians. These Americans practice
many forms of Buddhism that mostly retain the distinct
character of national origin: Japanese, Burmese, Vietnamese,
Chinese, Tibetan. But since World War II, a new phenomenon has
emerged: the rise of American teachers and of a distinctly
American form of Buddhism.  <BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;Buddhist
publishing is also blooming in America. A nonprofit publishing
house in Berkeley recently published the entire Tibetan
Buddhist canon, bound in 755 volumes. More than 80 scholars are
currently translating the entire Chinese Buddhist canon
(Religion BookLine, 5/15/96).

<P>&#182; An unscheduled series of revival services--now known
as the "Pensacola Outpouring"--is entering its second year. The
services began when an evangelists visited an Assemblies of God
congregation in Pensacola, Florida. Over 400,000 people have
attended. The pastor, John Kilpatrick, believes the outpouring
will continue for years.  <BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;"What is most
unique about this revival is its contagious quality," says a
report in Charisma (6/96).  "When people visit, they often take
the shaking, the weeping and the heavy sense of conviction to
their own churches, whether they are Pentecostal, Southern
Baptist, Episcopal or United Methodist. Even Roman Catholics
from nearby Mobile, Alabama, have been touched."

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;"The defining moment of this revival,"
according to the report, was an 8-minute testimony by a
19-year-old college student, Alison Ward. "As she spoke, Alison
shook in a manner so awkward that a casual observer might think
she suffered from cerebral palsy. Then, while trembling
violently, she issued a plea so heartfelt that those in the
room say they heard God speaking through her." The testimony
was caught on videotape and has been distributed by the
thousands. When churches show the clip, people often weep and
fall under conviction.

<P>&#182; One missionary in six leaves the mission field to
return home before the end of his or her first term of service
for reasons that are preventable. This was the finding of a
two-year research project involving 453 agencies, sponsored by
a commission of the World Evangelical Fellowship. "Some should
never have gone, others were not equipped, others were not
supported on the field," commission director William Taylor
told Christianity Today (6/17/96).

<A NAME = "SOC"></A><H2>Society</H2>

<P>&#182; Disney's newest animated film, The Hunchback of Notre
Dame, is family entertainment "gone adult," according to an
article in USA Today. The newspaper reported the film includes
a voluptuous gypsy dancer that "heaven knows most dads in the
audience" will surely notice. "In one song, we have [a
character] sing the church liturgy but also sing of twisted
sexual fantasies," said Alan Menken, the composer of
Hunchback's music, who added that Disney chief Michael Eisner
said "even if it goes PG, he would not compromise the material."

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;At the annual Southern Baptist last June,
the SBC passed a resolution calling on Baptists to boycott
Disney parks, movies, and products to protest the company's
conscious shift away from its leadership in family values. SBC
leaders cited efforts by Disney to support homosexual rights
and to promote objectionable films through its subsidiary
Miramax (Baptist Courier, 6/27/96).

<P>&#182; For the first time an openly Satanic rock band with
blatantly Satanic lyrics has gone mainstream. Smells Like
Children hit number 59 on Billboard magazine's music charts,
alongside Garth Brooks and Hootie and the Blowfish. Marylin
Manson, the lead singer and namesake of the band, is a
self-avowed follower of the Church of Satan. The video Sweet
Dreams are Made of This has appeared on MTV's Top Twenty
countdown (AFA Journal, 7/96).

<HR>


<P><I>What in the World!</I> is published by <A HREF =
"http://www.bju.edu/">Bob Jones University,</A> Greenville, South
Carolina 29614 to help believers know what the devil is up to.
Free church subscriptions: 864-242-5100, ext. 3074

