<HEAD>
<TITLE>
What in the World!
</TITLE>
<LINK REV="OWNER" HREF="mailto:bjup@bju.edu">
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<A NAME = "TOP"></A>
<H1 ALIGN = CENTER>
What in the World!
</H1>

<P ALIGN = CENTER>A news service prepared by <A HREF =
"http://www.bju.edu/">Bob Jones University</A> for the local church

<P ALIGN = CENTER>Volume 20, Number 04

<H4 ALIGN = CENTER>
[ <A HREF="#GOV">Government</A>
| <A HREF="#REL">Religion</A>
| <A HREF="#SOC">Society</A>
]
</H4>

<HR>


<A NAME = "GOV"></A><H2>Government</H2>

<P>&#182; Bill Clinton has become the first president to grant
an interview with a homosexual magazine. He also appeared 
on the cover of the magazine, <I>The Advocate.</I> Clinton spoke in 
generalities when questioned on homosexual issues, deferring to local 
and state governments to make laws concerning homosexuals (<I>AFA 
Journal,</I> 8/96).

<P>&#182; As the prison population in the United States grows,
the number of paid chaplains is declining. Saving money is not
the only reason for the decline. The Religious Freedom Restoration 
Act (1993) has caused some legislators to conclude that because they 
cannot afford to hire chaplains for all denominations, chaplaincy 
programs should be eliminated altogether. A positive side of the chaplaincy 
cuts is renewed interest in volunteer prison ministries in evangelical 
churches (<I>Charisma,</I> 8/96).

<P>&#182; Since President Clinton took office, the 
staff of the so-called drug czar has fallen from 147 to 25. The budget 
for drug interdiction has been cut 39% since 1993. Federal drug case 
loads fell 10.3% from fiscal 1992 to fiscal 1995. Among 12- to 17-year-olds 
marijuana use has almost doubled since 1992. In 1995, LSD experimentation 
among high school seniors reached the highest level in twenty years. 
In the first half of 1995, cocaine-related emergency room cases were 
up 65% compared to the first half of 1991. Over the same period, admissions 
involving heroin rose 120% (<I>Human Events,</I> 8/2/96).

<P>&#182; A federal district court in Maryland has 
ruled against a church in Cumberland that wanted to demolish an old 
monastery building to make way for a new multipurpose center. Because 
city officials had included the Catholic monastery in a historic district, 
they refused to allow its destruction.

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;The decision is a blow against the
Religious Freedom Restoration Act (RFRA). The law was crafted
in response to the Supreme Court's <I>Smith</I> decision
(1990), which ruled that governments have a right to limit
religious liberty as long as the law applies to everyone, even
if it lacks a compelling interest. The Supreme Court has not
yet ruled on the constitutionality of the RFRA (<I>Christian
Century,</I> 7/3/96).

<P>&#182; Three house church leaders have been beaten 
to death by Chinese police in the last three months in a fierce crackdown 
launched countrywide by authorities against unregistered Christians. 
Scores of believers have been arrested. In April alone more than 300 
house churches were closed in Shanghai (<I>Compass Direct,</I> 6/27/96).

<A NAME = "REL"></A><H2>Religion</H2>

<P>&#182; Delegates assembled in San Francisco, 
June 24-28, to create a "United Religions" organization to complement 
the UN. But sharp differences emerged early in the meetings. The host, 
Episcopal Bishop William Swing, clashed with a Korean Buddhist over 
who should get credit for the idea. These same two leaders clashed 
over the possible location of its headquarters.

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;Swing clashed with another leader over
how United Religions should deal with fundamentalism. Robert
Muller, a retired UN assistant secretary-general, argued that
peace will be impossible without the taming of fundamentalism.
He believed the United Religions must profess faithfulness
"only to the global spirituality and to the health of this
planet." In contrast, Swing asserted that fundamentalists are
not the enemies of peace and should be included in the dialogue
(<I>Christian News,</I> 7/8/96).

<P>&#182; Billy Graham's crusade in Minneapolis 
last June was assisted by 60 denominations representing 1,075 churches, 
including 119 Roman Catholic parishes and 269 Lutheran congregations. 
According to <I>Christianity Today</I> (7/15/96), the last time Graham 
held a crusade in the Twin Cities (1973) local Catholic churches gave 
no support and Lutherans gave only nominal support. Martin Fleming, 
director of evangelization for the Twin Cities archdiocese, credits 
an increased ecumenical spirit.

<P>&#182; The number of churches switching denominations 
is accelerating, reaching well into the hundreds, according to a report 
in the <I>Wall Street Journal.</I> Lutheran churches are going 
charismatic, Pentecostal churches are turning Episcopalian, charismatic 
churches are becoming Orthodox, and so on. The Charismatic Episcopal 
Church, for one, has benefited from the trend. Since 1992 the young 
denomination has grown from five to more than a hundred churches.<BR>

&#160;&#160;&#160;Increasingly, the switch is caused by a
minister's "revelation" of belonging to the wrong church. In
the past, such a minister would have quietly resigned. But
these days, he simply tells his church, "This is really not
where we belong," says Lyle Scaller, a retired Methodist
minister who has studied trends among denominations. That
forces hard choices and difficult adjustments among church
members (<I>Christian News,</I> 6/24/96).

<P>&#182; The president of Mercer University has 
issued a public apology for the Southern Baptist Convention's statement 
in June urging an aggressive effort to evangelize Jews. R. Kirby Godsey 
wrote, "As one person who calls himself a Baptist, I want to apologize 
for the religious bigotry and misguided rhetoric of a people who call 
themselves Southern Baptists. . . . I am grieved by the arrogance 
of that assembly [in New Orleans] and embarrassed by the apparent 
abandonment of the Baptist principle of respect for religious diversity. 
. . . Like Jesus, we can only ask for forgiveness, 'for they know 
not what they do' " (<I>Baptists Today,</I> 7/25/96).

<A NAME = "SOC"></A><H2>Society</H2>

<P>&#182; "Schools and universities have an obligation 
to ensure that all students, regardless of sexual orientation, are 
provided with a safe school environment free of harassment, intimidation, 
and discrimination." The National Education Association (NEA) issued 
this statement in the wake of the Supreme Court's decision to strike 
down Colorado's constitutional amendment that invalidated local protection 
for homosexuals. More school districts and universities need to adopt 
homosexual rights policies, the NEA claimed (<I>Education Week,</I> 
5/29/96).

<P>&#182; In children's Bibles today, not only are 
the harsher elements of biblical accounts often omitted, but the image 
of a personal God has evolved to the point where in some books "God 
is lonely if people don't love him," says Ruth B. Bottigheimer, author 
of a new book tracing the history of children's Bibles. "If there's 
any single trend . . . , tradition gets more and more expurgated so 
there's less and less content," she said (<I>Greenville</I> [S.C.] 
<I>News,</I> 6/1/96).

<P>&#182; Among 228 low-income students studied 
by the University of Michigan, 46% of fifth graders and 55% of eighth 
graders had engaged in sex (<I>Christian News,</I> 5/27/96).

<HR>


<P><I>What in the World!</I> is published by <A HREF =
"http://www.bju.edu/">Bob Jones University,</A> Greenville, South
Carolina 29614 to help believers know what the devil is up to.
Free church subscriptions: 864-242-5100, ext. 3074

