<TITLE>
What in the World!
</TITLE>
<LINK REV="OWNER" HREF="mailto:bjup@bju.edu">
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<A NAME = "TOP"></A>
<H1 ALIGN = CENTER>
What in the World!
</H1>

<P ALIGN = CENTER>A news service prepared by <A HREF =
"http://www.bju.edu/">Bob Jones University</A> for the local church

<P ALIGN = CENTER>Volume 19, Number 06

<H4 ALIGN = CENTER>
[ <A HREF="#GOV">Government</A>
| <A HREF="#REL">Religion</A>
| <A HREF="#SOC">Society</A>
]
</H4>

<HR>


<A NAME = "GOV"></A><H2>Government</H2>

<P>&#182; The Clinton administration is trying to 
force a group of Christians at the Department of Transportation (DOT) 
to accept the view that homosexual behavior is okay. To be recognized 
as an official employee group, the DOT Christian Prayer and Fellowship 
Group has been told they must accept a diversity policy statement, 
which says that homosexuality is an acceptable alternative lifestyle. 
This clause could allow unrepentant homosexuals to assume leadership 
positions in the group. Earlier the DOT drew headlines for recognizing 
an employees group known as GLOBE (Gay, Lesbian, and Bisexual Employees) 
(<I>AFA Journal,</I> 3/96).

<P>&#182; A sign that reads "The World Needs God" 
must be removed from a government building in Hillsboro, Illinois, 
because it promotes Christianity over other religious or non-religious 
beliefs, a U.S. district judge has ruled. The sign was placed there 
in 1942 by the Federated Women's Bible Club. The building was used 
as a courthouse until a new building was completed in 1993. Officials 
argued the sign was part of their county's history and was meant to 
be non-sectarian (<I>NIRR,</I> 2/19/96).

<P>&#182; Cuba has closed hundreds of newly formed 
Protestant house churches in recent months and tightened controls 
on evangelistic activities in an effort to slow the expansion of the 
church. Mass meetings in public areas and open air evangelism are 
generally prohibited, and the government does not grant permission 
to construct additional buildings. Though tolerated in the past, house 
churches are technically illegal and vulnerable to closure at any 
moment.<BR>
&#160;&#160;&#160;Church leaders face many forms of official harassment, including 
bugs on their telephone lines, secret police who monitor their movements, 
and informants who infiltrate their congregations. In December 1995 
the government prohibited the sale of paper, ink, typewriters, computers, 
and spare parts for printing presses and photocopy machines to religious 
organizations. Technicians who repair office machines for churches 
face dismissal from their jobs (<I>NNI,</I> 2/6/96).

<A NAME = "REL"></A><H2>Religion</H2>

<P>&#182; "United Religions"--the tentative 
name for a new international, interfaith organization--is being 
promoted among world leaders by Episcopal Bishop William Swing of 
California. He hopes that dialogue among world religions will help 
root out war.

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;United Religions would assemble the world's faiths much in 
the way the United Nations assembles the nations of the world. Religious 
leaders would discuss major issues of the day, press peacemaking initiatives 
with governments and private agencies, and dispatch teams of religious 
diplomats to ease tensions in politically troubled areas.

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;Swing first unveiled the idea after he led last year's interfaith 
service on the 50th anniversary of the United Nations. He hopes to 
sponsor a charter-writing conference this summer in San Francisco 
(<I>Christian News,</I> 2/12/96).

<P>&#182; Pope John Paul II has called on Catholics 
to respect the "spiritual riches of Hinduism, Buddhism and Islam," 
and he said he particularly regretted tensions with Jews. In a January 
14 address he said the Second Vatican Council called for "reciprocal 
esteem, dialogue and cooperation for the true good of man" (<I>Christian 
News,</I> 2/12/96).

<P>&#182; Nearly 40,000 pastors and other clergy 
attended the opening rally of the Promise Keepers 1996 Clergy Conference 
for Men at Atlanta's Georgia Dome February 13. "This is biblical 
unity, this is historic stuff," PK founder Bill McCartney told reporters. 
All the major denominations were represented, including the Roman 
Catholic Church, organizers said. This "men's movement" encourages 
men to be more committed to their families and their faith.

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;From modest beginnings in 1991, Promise Keepers has grown into 
a 300-staff operation with a $64 million budget last year. More than 
725,000 men attended 13 conferences in 1995. PK plans more than 20 
men's conferences this year, pushing the theme "Break Down the Walls." 
McCartney is calling for 1 million men to attend a Washington, D.C., 
rally in September 1997 to show concern for the nation's spiritual 
condition (<I>NIRR,</I> 2/19/96; <I>Christian News,</I> 2/12/96).

<P>&#182; A professor at Jerry Falwell's Liberty 
University has spoken approvingly of purgatory. Philosophy professor 
Gary R. Habermas conceded that the name <I>purgatory</I> sets off 
alarms in most Protestant minds. But he says that might change if 
believers read a definition by Peter Kreeft, a Protestant who converted 
to Catholicism. "That portrait isn't much different from what some 
leading evangelical scholars call the 'intermediate state' between 
death and Paradise." According to a November 11 report in the <I>Hutchinson</I> 
[Kans.] <I>News,</I> Habermas said, "If the word offends you, call 
it 'Heaven's kindergarten' " (<I>Baptist Challenge,</I> 2/96).

<P>&#182; Mormonism is growing fast in the 1990s, 
but more slowly than in previous periods, according to <I>Sunstone,</I> 
an independent Mormon magazine. If the growth rate for this decade 
continues, the Mormon Church's overall gain in the 1990s will be 46%, 
compared with 67% in the 1960s and 73% in the 1980s. Even at the slower 
rate of growth, the Mormon church is expected to reach a membership 
of 265 million by 2080 (<I>NIRR,</I> 2/5/96).

<A NAME = "SOC"></A><H2>Society</H2>

<P>&#182; Baylor University, the nation's largest 
Baptist school, will allow dances on campus beginning this spring. 
The school always has forbidden dances on campus, but sororities, 
fraternities, and other groups have had off-campus dances for several 
years. Dancing can be a wholesome activity that allows young people 
to meet in a friendly environment, said president Robert Sloan, a 
former student who met his wife at an off-campus dance. Baylor will 
not allow alcohol or "obscene or provocative" dancing, he said (<I>NIRR,</I> 
2/19/96).

<P>&#182; Nowhere does the media differ from public 
values more strikingly than on homosexuality, according to a study 
by the <I>Times-Mirror</I> Center for the People and the Press. According 
to the survey, 53% of Americans believe homosexuality should be discouraged, 
while a mere 4% of national media members hold that same view. Not 
one national media executive believes homosexuality should be discouraged 
(<I>National Liberty Journal,</I> 1/96).

<P>&#182; Of the world's 6,721 languages, only a 
third--or 2,065--have some or all of the Bible. According to 
Wycliffe Bible Translators, only 299 of these languages have an adequate 
translation of the whole Bible, while only 752 have an adequate New 
Testament. Wycliffe estimates that between 1,000 and 2,000 of the 
remaining languages need Bible translation (<I>Pulse,</I> 2/2/96).

<HR>

<P><I>What in the World!</I> is published by <A HREF =
"http://www.bju.edu/">Bob Jones University,</A> Greenville, South
Carolina 29614 to help believers know what the devil is up to.
Free church subscriptions: 864-242-5100, ext. 3074

