<HEAD>
<TITLE>
What in the World!
</TITLE>
<LINK REV="OWNER" HREF="mailto:bjup@bju.edu">
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<A NAME = "TOP"></A>
<H1 ALIGN = CENTER>
What in the World!
</H1>

<P ALIGN = CENTER>A news service prepared by <A HREF =
"http://www.bju.edu/">Bob Jones University</A> for the local church

<P ALIGN = CENTER>Volume 20, Number 07

<H4 ALIGN = CENTER>
[ <A HREF="#GOV">Government</A>
| <A HREF="#REL">Religion</A>
| <A HREF="#SOC">Society</A>
]
</H4>

<HR>


<A NAME = "GOV"></A><H2>Government</H2>

<P>&#182; The IRS has been asked to investigate 
two large Baptist churches in Texas for their involvement in politics. 
Americans United for Separation of Church and State has been targeting 
churches as part of its election-year campaign, Project Fair Play. 
The first complaint came in April against a ministry of Second Baptist 
Church in Houston, which allegedly printed materials encouraging members 
to vote for particular candidates. The most recent complaint is against 
Second Baptist Church in Lake Jackson, which mailed more than 7,000 
letters to other churches calling for the defeat of candidates, including 
President Clinton, who favor abortion rights (<I>Baptists Today,</I> 
8/12/96).

<P>&#182; KFUO-AM, a religious radio station in 
St. Louis, has spent $1 million fighting the Federal Communications 
Commission (FCC), which has threatened to take away its license. The 
Lutheran Church--Missouri Synod, which owns the station, is accused 
of not hiring enough minorities. Although the station has proved its 
hiring of minorities has exceeded the percentage required by law, 
the station lacks sufficient proof from the 1980s that its recruitment 
of minorities was sufficiently aggressive.<BR>
&#160;&#160;&#160;The tactics used against this station could easily be employed against 
conservative talk radio stations. Congress is moving to protect the 
station's rights of free speech and religious expression under the 
First Amendment (<I>Human Events,</I> 9/20/96).

<P>&#182; The closure of house churches continues 
in Cuba. During June and July three churches from three different 
denominations in Havana were closed, according to Open Doors. Each 
of the three churches supervised more than ten house churches, which 
were also forced to close. Authorities also forced one 80-member church 
in Havana to destroy its worship facility (<I>Compass Direct,</I> 
8/22/96).

<P>&#182; One of China's most famous Christian leaders 
has voluntarily closed his house church in Beijing after pressure 
to register with authorities. Since the beginning of 1996 the Religious 
Affairs Bureau has pushed a nationwide campaign to register all religious 
meetings by the end of the year. Now in his eighties, pastor Alan 
Yuan has spent more than twenty years in jail for his faith (<I>Compass 
Direct,</I> 8/22/96).

<A NAME = "REL"></A><H2>Religion</H2>

<P>&#182; Sun Myung Moon, the cult leader of the 
Unification Church who claims to be the Messiah, attracted famous 
evangelical speakers to a recent Washington conference. Among the 
speakers at the Family Federation for World Peace conference were 
Christian Coalition executive director Ralph Reed, Family Research 
Council president Gary Bauer, and Concerned Women for America president 
Beverly LaHaye. Moon and his fourth wife also addressed the conference, 
which attracted 1,500 participants from around the globe. (Moon has 
divorced his three previous wives.)

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;When asked why the Christian Coalition chose to associate with 
Moon, spokesman Mike Russell said, "They're working to strengthen 
the family and so are we. Ralph doesn't agree with every organization 
he speaks to." Bauer said, "I don't see why Christians should censor 
themselves out of any forum in which our perspectives can be heard" 
(<I>Christian Century,</I> 9/11/96).

<P>&#182; Ron Sider, president of Evangelicals for 
Social Action, has written an editorial for <I>Christianity Today</I> 
(8/12/96) urging Christians to join together in creating a pro-life 
ethic that means more than being anti-abortion: "A new coalition 
of evangelicals, African American and Hispanic Christians, the historic 
peace churches, mainline Protestants, and Catholics could contribute 
substantially to the renewal of our society in the next two decades--if 
we could agree to cooperate and develop a biblically balanced consistent 
ethic of life. If we do not, we will have ourselves to blame for our 
persistently frustrating options, and the immoral, inconsistent society 
they reflect."

<P>&#182; Yet another prophecy of the Jehovah's 
Witnesses has proved wrong, forcing them to change their teaching. 
Since the late 1960s the cult had been proclaiming that the world 
would end before "the 1914 generation" passed away. This prediction 
has appeared in various forms on the masthead of the cult's magazine 
<I>Awake!</I> The latest version has been dropped: "the Creator's 
promise of a peaceful and secure new world before the generation that 
saw the events of 1914 passes away." It now states: "the Creator's 
promise of a peaceful and secure new world that is about to replace 
the present wicked, lawless system of things" (<I>Christian Research 
Newsletter,</I> Summer 1996).

<P>&#182; The Unitarian Universalist Association 
voted June 25 to endorse the legalization of same-sex marriages, the 
first U.S. denomination to do so (<I>Christian News,</I> 7/1/96).

<A NAME = "SOC"></A><H2>Society</H2>

<P>&#182; A dismal array of statistics reveals that 
the nation's churches are not reaching America for Christ, religion 
pollster George Barna reports. Church attendance is suffering a five-year 
decline. Only 37% of U.S. adults attend church on a given weekend--the 
lowest level in two decades. Weekly Bible reading has also declined. 
The percentage of adults who say they read the Bible in a typical 
week has dropped from 47% in 1992 to 34% today (<I>Baptist Courier,</I> 
8/15/96).

<P>&#182; Michael English, who in 1994 won six Dove 
Awards from the Gospel Music Association, including artist of the 
year, sings of a break with his Christian roots in his first secular 
album, <I>Freedom Field:</I> "Old man religion, I've got your name; 
the best part of my years were wrapped up, tied in your thang." English 
now records mainstream pop. "Your Love Amazes Me," the first single 
released from <I>Freedom Field,</I> quickly entered the top 20 on 
<I>Billboard</I>'s adult contemporary chart (<I>Christian News,</I> 
9/16/96).

<P>&#182; Mott Media's Library of World Heroes for 
Christian Youth includes a biography of Mother Theresa. It advertises 
the Sowers Series as "26 character building biographies showing the 
spiritual dimension in the lives of famous people. Handsomely illustrated 
and enticingly written, these books will help your young people learn 
to appreciate their history and learn Christian values from some of 
the most inspiring individuals who have ever lived" (<I>Homeschooling 
Today,</I> 9-10/96).

<P>&#182; In 1994 Americans spent considerably more 
on lotteries than they gave to their churches, according to Associated 
Baptist Press. The U.S. Census Bureau says Americans spent $26.6 billion 
on state lotteries, while the <I>Yearbook of American and Canadian 
Churches</I> shows that in the same year total contributions to churches 
in America was $19.6 billion (<I>Christian Century,</I> 9/11/96).



<HR>


<P><I>What in the World!</I> is published by <A HREF =
"http://www.bju.edu/">Bob Jones University,</A> Greenville, South
Carolina 29614 to help believers know what the devil is up to.
Free church subscriptions: 864-242-5100, ext. 3074

