<HEAD>
<TITLE>
What in the World!
</TITLE>
<LINK REV="OWNER" HREF="mailto:bjup@bju.edu">
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<A NAME = "TOP"></A>
<H1 ALIGN = CENTER>
What in the World!
</H1>

<P ALIGN = CENTER>A news service prepared by <A HREF =
"http://www.bju.edu/">Bob Jones University</A> for the local church

<P ALIGN = CENTER>Volume 19, Number 07

<H4 ALIGN = CENTER>
[ <A HREF="#GOV">Government</A>
| <A HREF="#REL">Religion</A>
| <A HREF="#SOC">Society</A>
]
</H4>

<HR>


<A NAME = "GOV"></A><H2>Government</H2>

<P>&#182; A controversial CIA provision allows the 
CIA director to recruit clergy and missionaries for special covert 
activities, if circumstances warrant. Normal CIA rules prohibit using 
any "U.S. clergy or missionary" for intelligence activities. CIA 
Director John Deutch told Congress journalists would be recruited, 
too, if "unique and special threats to national security" exist. 
Religious groups said the loophole undermines the trust their workers 
have established in foreign countries (<I>NIRR,</I> 3/4/96).

<P>&#182; President Clinton  has said he will support 
a ban on partial-birth abortions if the bill includes exemptions to 
protect women from serious health consequences or death. The president's 
position is a smoke screen to preserve unrestricted abortion, said 
Douglas Johnson of the National Right to Life. Senate testimony showed 
that "health is simply not an issue" in this procedure, he said. 
A version of the bill already includes an exemption for endangerment 
of a woman's life (<I>NIRR,</I> 3/18/96).

<P>&#182; <I>The Teaching Home</I> (3-4/96) has 
published a summary of home-school laws in the fifty states. Thirty-five 
states have adopted home-school statutes or regulations. Ten states 
require home-school parents to meet specific qualifications. Eight 
of these states require a high school diploma or GED (Ariz., N.Mex., 
N. C., Ohio, Pa., Ga., Tenn., S. C.). North Dakota requires a college 
degree or passage of a "teacher's test," and West Virginia requires 
parents to have a GED or high school diploma <I>and</I> remain four 
years ahead of the student. Four states--Maine, Mass., R.I., and 
Utah--give superintendents, school boards, or the state commissioner 
the authority to "approve" home schools.

<P>&#182; The Lesbian, Gay, and Bisexual College 
Conference of the Southeastern U.S. won a federal court fight to hold 
a two-day meeting last February at the University of Alabama at Tuscaloosa. 
Republican state officials, including Gov. Fob James and Attorney 
General Jeff Sessions, had tried to block the meeting. It included 
seminar discussions on forms of sexual perversion (<I>NIRR,</I> 3/4/96).

<P>&#182; Dr. Jack Kevorkian has been acquitted 
again of assisted suicide. He has participated in 27 assisted suicides 
since he began his crusade in June 1990. The jury foreman, Bishop 
Donald Ott, supervisor of Michigan's 200,000 United Methodists, had 
advocated assisted suicide as early as 1993 in a weekly column (<I>NRL 
News,</I> 3/15/96).

<A NAME = "REL"></A><H2>Religion</H2>

<P>&#182; Luis Palau launched an 8-week crusade 
in Chicago on April 4. Over 1,500 churches are participating. Attempts 
to secure official endorsement by a Roman Catholic diocese have been 
unsuccessful, although individual priests are involved in leadership. 
Supporters include Erwin Lutzer, pastor of Moody Church; Joseph Stowell, 
president of Moody Bible Institute; and Bill Hybels, pastor of the 
Willow Creek Community Church (<I>Christianity Today,</I> 4/8/96).

<P>&#182; At the final session of the Promise Keepers 
Clergy Conference for Men in Atlanta, Bill McCartney invited the 39,024 
attendees to partake in communion as a sign of unity in Christ. He 
encouraged Roman Catholic priests and others to leave if it would 
violate their conscience. Hardly anyone left the stadium. McCartney 
told reporters that denominational differences greatly concern Promise 
Keepers because they impede unity. "I am not saying that we should 
dismantle our denominations and ignore our distinctives, but that 
we should concentrate on the 95% where we agree" (<I>NIRR,</I> 3/4/96).

<P>&#182; "Christians who argue for the 'objective' 
truth of Jesus are making a tactical error," says a recent article 
in <I>Christianity Today</I> (3/4/96). "Jesus' Peculiar Truth" was 
written by William H. Willimon, an ordained United Methodist pastor 
and dean of the chapel and professor of Christian ministry at Duke 
University, Durham, North Carolina.<BR>
&#160;&#160;&#160;Willimon believes, "The truth is a person, personal. . . . What 
the God of Israel and the church promises us is not absolute truth 
reduced to propositions but the reality of the kingdom of God and 
eternal communion with the One who is the way, the truth, and the 
life." He concludes: "So, in a way, we Christians do believe that 
all truth is relative. All truth, all truthful living is relative 
to the life, death, and resurrection of Jesus."

<P>&#182; During his recent visit to Latin America, 
Pope John Paul II called for all who had abandoned the fold to return: 
"All those who have at some time prayed to the Most Holy Virgin, 
even though they may have strayed from the Catholic church, conserve 
in their hearts an ember of faith which can be revived. The Virgin 
awaits them with maternal arms open wide." He complained about non-Catholic 
"sects and new religious groups, who sow confusion and uncertainty 
among Catholics." His strategy to combat defections appears to be 
a partial return to traditional Catholic emphases. For example, he 
ended every speech by exalting Mary (<I>Christianity Today,</I> 4/8/96).

<P><B>Correction:</B> <I>The Los Angeles Times</I> reported that 
Gary R. Habermas, a philosophy professor at Liberty University, said 
of <I>purgatory,</I> "If the word offends you, call it 'Heaven's 
kindergarten.' " In fact, he was quoting Peter Kreeft, a Roman Catholic 
philosophy professor at Boston College, to show that there are portraits 
of purgatory not much different from what some evangelical scholars 
call the "intermediate step."

<A NAME = "SOC"></A><H2>Society</H2>

<P>&#182; Twelve predominantly black churches in 
the South have been burned since December, but no arrests have been 
made. Federal investigators believe that racists may be responsible 
for burning these churches. Ten of the fires, including four in Louisiana 
and four in Alabama, damaged or destroyed rural Baptist churches. 
The congregations are small and had little or no property insurance 
(<I>Christianity Today,</I> 4/8/96).

<P>&#182; There was no place for God among the eight 
thousand professors and theologians who attended last November's joint 
annual meeting of the American Academy of Religion (AAR) and the Society 
of Biblical Literature (SBL). "The sad truth is that the vast majority 
of those teaching religion to the next generation of Americans are 
engaged in a profound undermining of biblical religion," said a report 
in <I>World</I> (2/10/96).

<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;The meeting celebrated the 50th anniversary of the findings 
of a library of Gnostic texts. New Testament scholars declared that 
the Gnostic Gospel of Thomas had finally been elevated to the status 
of the canonical gospels. In addition to seminars on Buddhism, Hinduism, 
Jainism, Islam, and American Indian animism, the AAR welcomed the 
study of the occult, pagan mysticism, muted forms of witchcraft, feminism, 
and homosexual studies.



<HR>


