<HEAD>
<TITLE>
What in the World!
</TITLE>
<LINK REV="OWNER" HREF="mailto:bjup@bju.edu">
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<A NAME = "TOP"></A>
<H1 ALIGN = CENTER>
What in the World!
</H1>

<P ALIGN = CENTER>A news service prepared by <A HREF =
"http://www.bju.edu/">Bob Jones University</A> for the local church

<P ALIGN = CENTER>Volume 20, Number 08

<H4 ALIGN = CENTER>
[ <A HREF="#GOV">Government</A>
| <A HREF="#REL">Religion</A>
| <A HREF="#SOC">Society</A>
]
</H4>

<HR>


<A NAME = "GOV"></A><H2>Government</H2>

<P>&#182; The military is attempting to prevent 
chaplains from speaking out on current moral issues. Earlier this 
year the Roman Catholic Church urged its members to support a federal 
ban on partial birth abortions (later vetoed by President Clinton). 
The campaign encouraged parishioners to contact their congressional 
representatives. However, barely a week after the Catholic Church's 
Chancery Office for the Archdiocese for the Military Services, USA, 
informed chaplains of its Project Life Postcard Campaign, the Air 
Force formally prohibited them from participating. To do so would 
be "lobbying," explained the Air Force Judge Advocate General. The 
other services similarly gagged their chaplains. The Pentagon later 
clarified its order, allowing chaplains to disucss current topics 
in sermons, but not to encourage mailing postcards to Congress (<I>Conservative 
Chronicle,</I> 9/4/96).

<P>&#182; Public schools replace the authority of 
parents once children enter school, according to a federal judge. 
The case involves a child in Texas who was questioned without his 
parent's knowledge. During the interrogation, the boy was forced to 
strip so that a female worker of the Children's Protective Services 
could check for signs of a paddling. When the parents found out, they 
immediately filed suit. District Judge Melinda Harmon ruled that "parents 
give up their rights when they drop the children off at public school" 
(<I>AFA Journal,</I> 9/96).

<P>&#182; Three Nigerian Christian colleges have 
been closed down because they did not teach Islam as part of their 
school curriculum. The closures have dealt a blow to recent moves 
by ecumenical churches to retake control of their schools, seized 
by the government forty years ago. National policy requires the teaching 
of Islamic Religious Knowledge side by side with Christian Religious 
Knowledge. About half of all Nigerians are Muslims (<I>Compass Direct,</I> 
8/22/96).

<P>&#182; Chinese officials demolished five church 
buildings last May in the coastal city of Wenzhou, which some have 
called China's "Jerusalem." This was a startling reversal of policy 
in a town that had been remarkably tolerant of unregistered churches. 
Two churches that were dynamited had more than 1000 members (<I>Compass 
Direct,</I> 8/22/96).

<A NAME = "REL"></A><H2>Religion</H2>

<P>&#182; Robert Schuller, pastor of Crystal Cathedral, 
will hold his 27th Institute for Successful Church Leadership, January 
27-30. According to an ad in <I>Christianity Today</I> (9/11/95), 
keynote speakers include John Wimber of Vineyard Christian Fellowship;  Bill 
Hybels of Willow Creek Community Church (South Barrington, Illinois); 
and David Yonggi Cho of Yoido Full Gospel Church (Seoul, Korea). The 
conference is sponsored by Churches Uniting in Global Mission. Members 
of CUGM sign a simple statement that they seek "a spirit of unity 
that is truly Catholic, Protestant, Orthodox, Evangelical, and Charismatic."

<P>&#182; Dr. Kenneth Kantzer, a leading figure 
in new evangelicalism, was asked in an interview by <I>Christianity 
Today</I> (9/16/96), "What is your assessment of the Evangelicals 
and Catholics Together statement?" Although he agreed that the document 
ran ahead of the evangelical constituency and had some ambiguity in 
terminology, he reaffirmed: "I do not for a moment deny the Christianity 
of any true Roman Catholic. Many Roman Catholics are certainly evangelical. 
We share the faith of the Apostles' Creed and the seven ecumenical 
councils of the ancient church. We need each other in our battles 
against secularism and materialism." He added, "Yet there are crucial 
differences that we dare not gloss over, like the hierarchical authoritarianism 
of the Roman clergy and the gospel of salvation by grace through faith."

<P>&#182; The Anglican Church of Canada has 
rescinded a national prohibition against extending health care coverage 
to partners of homosexual employees (<I>Record,</I> Summer 1996).

<P>&#182; The Interfaith Alliance, formed two years 
ago to counter the Christian Coalition, is asking local, state, and 
federal candidates across the country to sign a "pledge of civility" 
promising to repudiate "the use of religion as a weapon" in the 
public arena. The group, which claims 30,000 members, has launched 
a "Road to Renewal" campaign of voter education aimed at challenging 
what it called "religious political extremists."<BR>
&#160;&#160;&#160;The "civility pledge" urges candidates to "challenge anyone or 
any organization asserting that a particular candidate is sanctioned 
by God." It also asks the candidate to promise to refuse campaign 
contributions "from organizations or individuals who practice or 
advocate exclusion or intolerance." Although members of the Interfaith 
Alliance have come to an agreement on poverty issues, they have been 
sharply divided on homosexuality and abortion (<I>Christian News,</I> 
7/22/96).

<P>&#182; Charles Stanley, pastor of a large Southern 
Baptist church in Atlanta, told <I>Charisma</I> (9/96) that he is 
not charismatic but "I have no problem with the Pentecostal movement. 
. . . People ask me, 'Do you have charismatic people in your meetings?' 
Absolutely! Then they ask, 'Do you like that?' Absolutely! It makes 
for a good mixture." Stanley adds, "If somebody loves God, who cares 
what kind of title they [<I>sic</I>] have?"

<A NAME = "SOC"></A><H2>Society</H2>

<P>&#182; Evangelicals and Roman Catholics are getting 
abortions at alarming rates, according to an Alan Guttmacher study 
published in <I>Detroit News</I> (8/9/96). The study, conducted in 
1994 and 1995, questioned nearly 10,000 women who aborted their babies. 
It found that 31% of the women claimed to be Roman Catholic, and 18% 
claimed to be evangelical or born-again Christians. About 23% of Americans 
belong to the Catholic Church, while about 42% claim to be born-again  (<I>Christian 
News,</I> 9/16/96).

<P>&#182; Openly homosexual writers dominate the 
staffs of some top-rated shows on television. "In short, when it 
comes to sitcoms, gays rule," wrote David Ehrenstein in the May issue 
of <I>Los Angeles</I> magazine. <I>Friends, Wings, Seinfeld, Murphy 
Brown, Roseanne,</I> and <I>Mad About You</I> all can claim a homosexual 
on the writing staff. "To write a show about flight attendants and 
not have one of them be gay would be a sin," says Jamie Wooten, who 
helped create <I>The Crew. </I>A<I> U.S. News</I> poll found that 
less than one-third of the Hollywood executives quizzed were concerned 
about homosexual activity on TV, but 75% of Americans in the same 
poll were concerned (<I>AFA Journal,</I> 9/96).

<P>&#182; Scientists are now prescribing a synthetic 
growth hormone, introduced in 1985, to children who are merely short 
for their ages. The substance was originally designed for children 
with growth hormone deficiency (<I>Science News,</I> 9/7/96).

<P>&#182; Ralph Reed, executive director of the 
Christian Coalition, has published a new book to prove that his organization 
is "surfing the mainstream." <I>Active Faith: How Christians Are 
Changing the Soul of American Politics</I> claims, "Liberals have 
been correct throughout history on issues of social justice while 
we have been neglectful or derelict in applying the principles of 
our faith to establishing justice in a fallen world." Reed "embraces 
the goals of the Social Gospel (though not the means) and the War 
on Poverty," according to a review in <I>Christian Century</I> (8/28/96), 
and he takes "religious conservatives to task for their past and 
present sins, including anti-Semitism, anti-Catholicism, gay-bashing 
and, in particular, racism." 



<HR>


<P><I>What in the World!</I> is published by <A HREF =
"http://www.bju.edu/">Bob Jones University,</A> Greenville, South
Carolina 29614 to help believers know what the devil is up to.
Free church subscriptions: 864-242-5100, ext. 3074

