</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Math Curriculum and Evaluation Standards  
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<A NAME = "TOP"></A>

<H1 ALIGN = CENTER>Math Curriculum and Evaluation Standards
</H1>

<H2 ALIGN = CENTER>by Tammie Jacobs, M.Ed.
</H2>

<P ALIGN = CENTER>
[ <A HREF = "contents.html">Tips for Teachers Contents</A>
| <A HREF = "../../home.html">BJUP Home Page</A> ]
</P>

<HR>


<P>The publication of Curriculum Evaluation Standards for School Mathematics by the
National Council of Teachers of Mathematics in 1989 focused on the need for change in
mathematics education. Mathematics is no longer viewed as a collection of rules and
procedures to learn without understanding. Since today's jobs require fewer mechanical skills
and more analytical skills, higher-level math knowledge is expected of every student in
school. To ensure each student would receive proper instruction, the National Council of
Teachers of Mathematics cited standards for each grade division. The following are the
standards listed for kindergarten through twelfth grade:

<H3>Curriculum Standards for Grades K-4</H3>
<OL>
<LI>Mathematics as Problem Solving
<LI>Mathematics as Communication
<LI>Mathematics as Reasoning
<LI>Mathematics as Connections
<LI>Estimation
<LI>Number Sense and Numeration
<LI>Concepts of Whole Number Operations
<LI>Whole Number Computation
<LI>Geometry and Spatial Sense
<LI>Measurement
<LI>Statistics and Probability
<LI>Fractions and Decimals
<LI>Patterns and Relationships
</OL>

<H3>Curriculum Standards for Grades 5-8</H3>
<OL>
<LI>Mathematics as Problem Solving
<LI>Mathematics as Communication
<LI>Mathematics as Reasoning
<LI>Mathematics as Connections
<LI>Number and Number Relationships
<LI>Number Systems and Number Theory
<LI>Computation and Estimation
<LI>Patterns and Functions
<LI>Algebra
<LI>Statistics
<LI>Probability
<LI>Geometry
<LI>Measurement
</OL>

<H3>Curriculum Standards for Grades 9-12</H3>
<OL>
<LI>Mathematics as Problem Solving
<LI>Mathematics as Communication
<LI>Mathematics as Reasoning
<LI>Mathematics as Connections
<LI>Algebra
<LI>Functions
<LI>Geometry from a Synthetic Perspective
<LI>Geometry from an Algebraic Perspective
<LI>Trigonometry
<LI>Statistics
<LI>Probability
<LI>Discrete Mathematics
<LI>Conceptual Underpinnings of Calculus
<LI>4. Mathematical Structure
</OL>

<P>The first four standards of each division focus on mathematical processes. Students
solve real-life problems using reasoning to plan and explain their work. They communicate
their work with others through oral and written communication. What is learned is then
connected to other math problems and to non-mathematical situations. These four process
standards influence the instruction and assessment of the remaining content standards.

<P>The publication of Curriculum and Evaluation Standards for School Mathematics fueled
the flame for change in math education. Changes in curriculum, methodology, and
assessment procedures are now in the forefront. Four years ago most Christian schools had
little knowledge or interest in the standards. Today, Christian schools and home school
parents are checking to see of math curriculums meet the standards.

<P>The Christian teacher needs to be alert to the fact that not all the current trends in
math coincide with Christian philosophy. Changes being promoted in many states influence
more than teaching-material improvements. Guidelines for the physical classroom, social
expectations, intellectual environment, classroom organization, assessment procedures, and
the teacher's role have been redefined. Teachers are being directed to teach math according
to the interests of the students, to the neglect of sequential skill development and the aid of
good textbooks. Whole math is a merging term that coincides with the idea of whole
language. Literature is used as a springboard to find the students' interest and integrate the
teaching of math, as well as other subjects, into these areas of interest. Teachers no longer
have an authoritative role; instead, they become an equal member of the learning group.
These are some of the areas in which Christian educators need to be cautious when
implementing the standards.

<P>The pendulum has swung from the far right of teaching math by drill and
memorization to the far left of teaching whole math. A Christian teacher does not have to be
compromised to give increased attention to estimation and number sense or to use
manipulatives in the teaching of math understanding, but he must always be on guard that his
methods coincide with a Christian philosophy of education.

<HR>


<P>Tammie Jacobs holds an M.Ed. in Elementary Education. Following a stint as a
classroom teacher, she is an author at Bob Jones University Press, coordinating the
development of a revised math program.
<HR>
<H6>All contents &#169;1994, BJU Press. All rights reserved.
</H6>
