<!--DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC
faq.htm
New Nov4,96 (at Diabetes Monitor)
By Rick Mendosa with help from Tim Berners-Lee, Marc Andreessen, Bill Gates, and
Will Vasquez
This file is safe for children. We endorse the SafeSurf concept-->
<HTML><HEAD>
<META http-equiv="PICS-Label" content='(PICS-1.0
"http://www.classify.org/safesurf/" l gen t for "http://www.mdcc.com" r
(SS~~000 1 SS~~100 1))'
NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Rick Mendosa with help from Tim Berners-Lee, Marc Andreessen, Bill Gates, and Will Vasquez">
<TITLE>On-line Resources for Diabetics</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#DFFFFF" background="bd2.gif"TEXT="#000000" link="000088" alink="CC6600" vlink="CC6600">
<a name="top"></a><a name="_top"></a>
<table>
<td>
<IMG src="spinstar.gif" height=47 width=47 ALT=" " align=left>
</td><td>
<h2><strong>
<font SIZE="+3"><A HREF="index.htm" TARGET="_top">D</a></FONT><font color="#ff00cc">IABETES</font>
<FONT SIZE="+3"><a href="with.htm" TARGET="_top">M</a></FONT><font color="#ff00cc">ONITOR:</font>
<br>
<FONT face="Rockwell, Comic Sans MS, Arial">
On-line Resources for Diabetics
</FONT>
</td><br>
</table>
<IMG SRC="red-line.gif" width=100% Height=2 ALT=" ">
</h2></strong>
<center>
<h3><b>By Rick Mendosa</b>
<br>(Used with Permission)</h3>
<p>
Most Recent Update: February 10, 1997
<p>
</center>
<HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=center SIZE=2 NOSHADE>
<blockquote><blockquote>
<p>
<A HREF ="d.gif"></a><img src="d.gif" align=left alt=D>iabetics have the power to manage their diabetes, whether it is Type I or Type II.  That's because diabetes is one 
disease where poor treatment leads to complications that are much worse than the disease itself and where 
successful treatment depends much more on the patient than on the doctor. 
<p>
The Internet is a wonderful help in diabetes management because there is so much information and support and so 
many services offered. But like just about everything else on the Internet and the rest of on-line space, this support 
and these information resources for diabetics are fragmented and hard to find. This Web page brings 
together in one place descriptions of and links to all those places where diabetics can find resources that they can use. 
Those links that I think are especially valuable are marked in <FONT COLOR="Red">red.</FONT>
<p> 
This Web page, with one major exception (see below) covers the major divisions of the Internet and 
other on-line services:
<p>
<ul>
<li><a href="#Mailing Lists">Mailing Lists</a><br>
<li><a href="#Usenet Newsgroups">Usenet Newsgroups</a><br>
<li><a href="#Internet Relay Chat">Internet Relay Chat</a><br>
<li><a href="#CompuServe">CompuServe</a><br>
<li><a href="#Prodigy">Prodigy</a><br>
<li><a href="#America Online">America Online</a><br>
<li><a href="#Delphi">Delphi</a><br>
<li><a href="#Local BBS's">Local BBS's</a><br>
</ul>
<p>
Because of the explosion in number of Web sites, in order for it to load in a reasonable time it's now 
necessary to divide this FAQ into separate Web pages. In February 1995 when I started to keep 
track of &quot;On-line Resources for Diabetics&quot; the Internet had two mailing lists, 
two newsgroups, and six Web sites dealing with diabetes. By November 1996 the number of diabetes 
Web sites had increased to more than 160. 
<p>
This page will continue to include mailing lists, newsgroups, IRC, and non-Internet resources. From 
this page you will also be able to jump to six separate pages listing different Web sites. Within each group  
I list them in the order that I discovered them, which corresponds fairly closely with how long they 
have been active:
<p>
<ul>
<li><a href="genl.htm">General</a>
<li><a href="org.htm">Organizations and Charities</a>
<li><a href="univ.htm">Universities and Hospitals</a>
<li><a href="company.htm">Companies</a>
<li><a href="mag.htm">Publications</a>
<li><a href="govt.htm">Government</a>
</ul>
<p>
I especially want to draw your attention to a summary of information about the glycemic index (GI) that I prepared 
together with Tere Griffin. The GI shows how 
quickly different foods make glucose available, something of great importance to diabetics. The GI is a separate 
link on my home page at<br>
<a href="http://www.cruzio.com/~mendosa/gi.html">http://www.cruzio.com/~mendosa/gi.html</a>
<p>
My review of a new book about the glycemic index is yet another link on my home page at<br>
<a href="http://www.cruzio.com/~mendosa/gifactor.html">http://www.cruzio.com/~mendosa/gifactor.html</a>
<p>
Are you interested in the closest thing yet to a miracle food for diabetics? If you are, you may want to check out my
<a href="http://www.cruzio.com/~mendosa/chanadal.html"> chana dal </a> page.
<p>
<HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=center SIZE=2 NOSHADE>
This Web page addresses the following questions:







<p>
<ul>
<li>Where can I find other on-line sources of information about diabetes?
<p>
<li>How can I get on (or off) different diabetes-related mailing lists?
</ul>
<p>
<h1>I. INTERNET</h1>
<p>
<h2>A. <a name="Mailing Lists">Mailing Lists:</h2> All messages to subscribe or signoff (unsubscribe) to mailing lists must be sent to the listserv address, not the addresses used to send mail to other members. Do not use a subject line or a signature. The form of the body of the message is different for each list and must be precisely as shown below.
<p>
<ol>
<li><h3> <FONT COLOR="Red">Diabetic</FONT></h3> is a forum for the open discussion of diabetic concerns by the people directly involved - 
the diabetic patient.  The most active mailing list with more than 700 subscribers. 
<p>
To join the diabetic list send email to <a href = "mailto:listserv@Lehigh.EDU">listserv@Lehigh.EDU </A>with 
the message: <br>
subscribe diabetic firstname lastname
<p>
Using your real name is mandatory.
<p>
To get off this list send email to <a href = "mailto:listserv@Lehigh.EDU">listserv@Lehigh.Edu</A> with the 
message:<br>
 signoff diabetic
<p>
Do not give your name. The listserver will pick it up from the automatic header information.
<p>
<li><h3> Type_one</h3> is temporarily down, according to listowner 
<a href="mailto:jamyers@netcom.com">John Myers.</a> When 
it is available, it is a low volume mailing list with an 
emphasis on issues and concerns of Type One, insulin dependent diabetics. 
<p>
To join type_one send email to <a href = "mailto:listserv@netcom.com">listserv@netcom.com</a>
 with the message: <br>
subscribe type_one name@address
<p>
Note the form for you name is different from most other mailing lists. For example, for my name I used subscribe type_one mendosa@cruzio.com, not Rick Mendosa as I did for the diabetic list.
<p>
To get off this list send email to <a href = "mailto:listserv@netcom.com">listserv@netcom.com</a> with the 
message: unsubscribe type_one name@address
<p>
For example, the body of the message I would write would say unsubscribe type_one mendosa@cruzio.com.
<p>
<li><h3>  The Diabetes-news</h3> mailing list is a weekly distribution only newsletter 
moderated by <a href="mailto:diabetes@best.com">Scott King.</a>  Each issue contains one or two 
diabetes-related news stories and a table of contents for <i>Diabetes Interview</i>, a monthly print
newspaper. 
<p>
To subscribe to the newsletter, send a message to <a href= "mailto:diabetes-news-request@lists.best.com">
diabetes-news-request@lists.best.com.</a> In the body of the message write:<br>
subscribe
<p>
You will receive an automatic message asking you to confirm your subscription.
<p>
If you would like to take your name off the mailing list, send a message to <a href= 
"diabetes-news-request@lists.best.com">diabetes-news-request@lists.best.com</a> from the address you 
subscribed. In the body of the message write:<br> 
unsubscribe 
<p>
<li><h3> Diabetes Talk</h3> is a discussion group for you to discuss issues 
presented in the diabetes-news newsletter that you may also subscribe to. In charge of this mailing list is 
<a href = "mailto: storm@best.com">Storm A King.</a>
<p>
To subscribe in digest form, send a message to 
<a href="mailto:diabetes-talk-request@lists.best.com">diabetes-talk-request@lists.best.com</a> with the
message: <br>
subscribe
<p>
To subscribe in normal form, send a message to 
<a href="mailto:diabetes-talk-request@lists.best.com">diabetes-talk-request@lists.best.com</a> with the
message: <br>
subsingle
<p>
If you would like to take your name off the mailing list, send a message to 
<a href="mailto:diabetes-talk-request@lists.best.com">diabetes-talk-request@lists.best.com</a> with the 
message: <br>
unsubscribe
<p>

<li><h3> DIABETES-EHLB </h3> is a moderated mailing list featuring the dissemination and archiving of 
electronic highlights bulletins (hence EHLB in its name) from a variety of international diabetes meetings. 
It is also available for discussion among subscribers. The moderator is 
<a href = "mailto: johnmack@hslc.org">John Mack.</a>
<p>
To subscribe, send a message to 
<a href="mailto:LISTSERV@SHRSYS.HSLC.ORG">LISTSERV@SHRSYS.HSLC.ORG</a>
with the message in this form:<br>
SUBSCRIBE DIABETES-EHLB firstname lastname
<p>
If you would like to take your name off the mailing list, send a message to
<a href="mailto:LISTSERV@SHRSYS.HSLC.ORG">LISTSERV@SHRSYS.HSLC.ORG</a> with the 
message in this form:<br>
SIGNOFF DIABETES-EHLB
<p>
<li> <h3> redALAD </h3> is a new Spanish-language mailing list for diabetes professionals: &quot;La 
redALAD es una cadena de profesionales interesados en la Diabetes
Mellitus que desean intercambiar ideas y conocimientos sobre esta
enfermedad en castellano. ALAD es la Asociacion Latino Americana de
Diabetes y esta red no es el vocero oficial de esta institucion sino el
esfuerzo personal de un grupo de medicos afiliados a ALAD.&quot; The moderator is <a href = 
"mailto:rolla@world.std.com">Arturo R. Rolla, MD.</a>
<p>
To subscribe, send a message to
<a href="mailto:majordomo@world.std.com">majordomo@world.std.com</a>
with the message in this form: <br>
SUBSCRIBE redALAD
<p>
If you would like to take your name off the mailing list, send a message to
<a href="mailto:redalad-request@world.std.com">redalad-request@world.std.com</a> with the message 
in this form:<br>
unsubscribe
<p>
<li> <h3>Best-of-Diabetic</h3> is a selection of messages made by <a href = 
"mailto:njs@scifi.squawk.com">Nick Simicich</a> of what he thinks are the best messages posted 
on Diabetic, the high-volume mailing list discussed above. You can receive the messages individually by sending a 
subscribe message to 
<a href = "mailto:best-of-diabetic-request@scifi.squawk.com">best-of-diabetic-request@scifi.squawk.com</a> 
with the message in this form:<br>
subscribe
<p>
If you would like to take your name off the mailing list send a message to 
<a href = "mailto:best-of-diabetic-request@scifi.squawk.com">best-of-diabetic-request@scifi.squawk.com</a> 
in this form: <br>
unsubscribe
<p>
You can receive the Best-of-Diabetic messages in digest form by sending a subscribe message to
<a href = "mailto:best-of-diabetic-digest-request@scifi.squawk.com">best-of-diabetic-digest-request@scifi.squawk.com</a> 
in this form:<br>
subscribe
<p>
If you would like to take your name off the digest version of the mailing list send a message to 
<a href = "mailto:best-of-diabetic-digest-request@scifi.squawk.com">best-of-diabetic-digest-request@scifi.squawk.com</a> 
in this form: <br>
unsubscribe
<p>
The Best-of-Diabetic archives  are available at <a href="http://scifi.squawk.com/best-of-diabetic.archive">http://scifi.squawk.com/best-of-diabetic.archive</a> and
<a href="http://scifi.squawk.com/best-of-diabetic-digest.archive">http://scifi.squawk.com/best-of-diabetic-digest.archive</a> or through 
majordomo file fetch.
<p>
<li> <h3>The Mid Maine Diabetes Discussion List </h3> is for the discussion of diabetes and is open to 
everyone, according to list owner <a href="mailto:bob@mint.net">Bob LeBlanc</a>. The list carries announcements on diabetes events and meetings in Maine and also carries 
diabetes-related information that is useful for anyone with diabetes. No flames are allowed. Chatting is fine as long 
as you put &quot;Chat&quot; on the subject line.
<p>
To subscribe, send a message to 
<a href="mailto:majordomo@mint.net">majordomo@mint.net</a>
with the message in this form:<br>
subscribe mmdd-list
<p>
If you would like to take your name off the mailing list, send a message to
<a href="mailto:majordomo@mint.net">majordomo@mint.net</a> with the 
message in this form:<br>
unsubscribe mmdd-list firstname lastname name@address
<p>
<li> <h3><FONT COLOR="Red">The Diabetes List</FONT> </h3> is a list for sharing support and information for people who have
diabetes. It provides a mixture of personal experiences, medical 
information, scientific news, and support for living with diabetes. In 
this mailing list you will find information about both type I and 
type II diabetes. To maintain the quality of this mailing list and to assure that the
rules and regulations are followed by all members, a Board of 
Overseers assists the listowner in enforcing the guidelines and 
in managing the list. 
<p>
To subscribe, send e-mail to <a href="mailto:majordomo@world.std.com">majordomo@world.std.com</a> with this in the
body of the message (not in the subject line):
<p>
subscribe diabetes
<p>
To unsubscribe, send e-mail to <a href="mailto:majordomo@world.std.com">majordomo@world.std.com</a>
with this in the body of the message (not in the subject line):
<p>
unsubscribe diabetes
<p>
To receive a digest, send e-mail to <a href="http://diabetes-digest-request@world.std.com">diabetes-digest-request@world.std.com</a>
with this in the body of the message (not in the subject line):
<p>
subscribe
<p>
Alternatively, send e-mail to <a href="http://majordomo@world.std.com">majordomo@world.std.com</a> 
with this in the body of the message (not in the subject line):
<p>
subscribe diabetes-digest
<p>
If you are already subscribed to the regular list, you must unsubscribe to avoid receiving both the digest and the 
individual posts. To subscribe to the digest and unsubscribe from the regular list in the same message,
send e-mail to <a href="http://majordomo@world.std.com">majordomo@world.std.com</a> with these two lines in the body
of the message:
<p>
subscribe diabetes-digest<br>
unsubscribe diabetes
<p>
To get back on the regular list and off the digest version, send e-mail to <a href="http://majordomo@world.std.com">majordomo@world.std.com</a>
 with these two lines in the body of the message:
<p>
subscribe diabetes<br>
unsubscribe diabetes-digest
<p>
<li> <h3>The Mini List </h3> is a small group organized by 
<a href="mailto:bwmeyers@netins.net">Brad Meyers</a>. The Mini List is gay and/or 
straight, 12 step, with open conversation not always related to diabetes. Brad is currently in the 
hospital, so the list is temporarily on hold. 
<p>
To join this list send him an 
e-mail message in any form you like. The only requirements are  not to be annoying or annoyed.
<p>
<li> <h3>One Step Diabetes Discussion List </h3> is an e-mail discussion list where you can exchange 
information, ideas, and opinions concerning all aspects of diabetes, as well as sharing your beliefs, if you are
 Christian.  But this list is open to anyone with diabetes in their life.
<p>
You can subscribe to this list be sending an e-mail with your request to
 <a href="mailto:belve@aol.com">belve@aol.com</a>
<p>
You can unsubscribe to this list by sending an e-mail to the same e-mail address.
<p>
<li> <h3>The International Society for Molecular Nutrition and Therapy&reg;</h3> at Philipps 
University of Marburg in Germany has a moderated mailing list that is open to anybody interested in nutritional 
aspects of chronic disease prevention, including diabetes.  The secretary general of ISMNT is
<a href="mailto:rupp@Mailer.Uni-Marburg.DE">Heinz Rupp, PhD.</a> The organization has 
a related Web page at <a href="http://cardiorepair.uni-marburg.de/ismnt.htm">http://cardiorepair.uni-marburg.de/ismnt.htm</a>
<p>
You can subscribe to this list be sending an e-mail with your request to
<a href="mailto:ismnt-request@Lists.Uni-Marburg.DE">ismnt-request@Lists.Uni-Marburg.DE</a>
with this in the body of the message (not in the subject line):<p>
subscribe
<p>
If you would like to take your name off the mailing list, send a message to
<a href="mailto:ismnt-request@Lists.Uni-Marburg.DE">ismnt-request@Lists.Uni-Marburg.DE</a>
with this in the body of the message (not in the subject line):<p>
unsubscribe
<p>
The ismnt-archives are available to subscribers. CONTENTS lists what subject lines are in each
archive file; TOPICS lists what archive files contain each subject.
Subscribers use the &quot;get&quot; command to see files in the archives by sending
the following commands to <a href="mailto:majordomo@lists.uni-marburg.de">majordomo@lists.uni-marburg.de</a> in the message
body:<br>
<p>
get ismnt CONTENTS (must be in capital letters)<br>
or<br>
get ismnt ismnt.9701  (which gets all of the messages sent in January 1997, the first month 
archived)
<p>             
Subscribers can also get a list of filenames and dates in the archive
by sending the following &quot;index&quot; command to <a href="mailto:majordomo@lists.uni-marburg.de">majordomo@lists.uni-marburg.de</a>
in the message body:<br>
index ismnt
<p>





</ol>
<p>
<h2>B. <a name="Usenet Newsgroups">Usenet Newsgroups:</h2>
<p>
<ol>
<li><h3> <a href = "news:misc.health.diabetes">Misc.health.diabetes</h3></a> is the broadest and most active 
diabetes newsgroup. It bills itself as a &quot;discussion of diabetes management in day to day life.&quot; 
<p>
<li><h3> <a href = "news:alt.support.diabetes.kids">Alt.support.diabetes.kids</h3></a> is a support group
 for children with diabetes and their families. It's mostly parents discussing the challenges of raising children
with diabetes.
<p>
<li><h3> <a href ="news:de.sci.medizin.diabetes">De.sci.medizin.diabetes</h3></a> is a 
German-language newsgroup focusing on diabetes.
<p>





</ol>
<h2>C. <a name= "Internet Relay Chat">Internet Relay Chat:</h2>
<p>
Three separate IRC networks let Internet users type back and forth to each other in real time. Each of these networks 
has a diabetes chat channel. The networks are DALnet, Efnet, and Undernet.
<p>
Using IRC is a good way to learn and get to talk in &quot;real time&quot; to others who have diabetes. Most 
traffic is in the evening, and you can arrange for your group of friends to meet you on a specific channel.
<p>
To use IRC you need client software on your computer. For Windows users a good choice is mIRC, 
version 4.52. It's available at several Web sites, including DALnet's excellent introduction to using 
IRC at <a href="http://www.dal.net/">http://www.dal.net/</a>. For Macintosh users, get 
ircle version 2.5. It's available at several Web sites, including MacUser's Software Central at 
<a href="http://www.zdnet.com/macuser/software/">http://www.zdnet.com/macuser/software/</a>
<p>
After you get the software it is easy to just long onto a server for one of these networks using the list that comes with 
the program. To join any on-going discussion type /join #diabetes, which will put you in the diabetes channel of any 
of the networks. DALnet and Undernet also have channels called diabetic; type /join #diabetic to go 
there.








<p>
<h1>II. <a name="CompuServe">COMPUSERVE
</h1><p>
Diabetes and Hypoglycemia Forum is CompuServe's very active and well organized group. It has 
launched a campaign to make it known that that want a cure for diabetes and 
ask people to wear a gray ribbon in support.  It also includes an extensive archive, which 
CompuServe calls a &quot;library.&quot; You no longer have to pay extra for the forum.
<p>
To get to the Diabetes Forum, type &quot;go diabet&quot; without the quotation marks.
<p>
<h1>III.<a name="Prodigy"> PRODIGY
</h1><p>
Diabetes Topic is Prodigy's somewhat less active group. 
<p>
Jump to Medical Support BB and choice the diabetes topic.
<p>
<h1>IV. <a name="America Online">AMERICA ONLINE
</h1><p>
AOL has two types of online support groups available to its members:
<p>
<ul>
<li>One is the DM resource is a support group area. To find it, from the main menu,  select GO to Lifestyles 
and Interests. Then select Better Health and Fitness. Next select the Message Center, then Self-Help and 
Support Groups, and finally the DM bulletin board.
<p>
<li>AOL's other resource is weekly on-line &quot;meetings:&quot;
<p>

One weekly meeting is in a &quot;room&quot; set aside for discussions of diabetes, starting at 8:30 pm
 EST each Sunday evening. 
<p>
Another weekly meeting is called Diabetic Kids for the parents and caregivers of diabetic children. 
This group meets in a private room called Diabetic Kids, starting at 9:00 pm EST each Thursday evening. 

</ol>
<p>
<h1>V. <a name="Delphi">DELPHI
</h1><p>
Delphi also has a diabetes forum. Here you can get your questions asked, cyber-socialize with other people with 
diabetes and conduct live chats. 
<p>
To get there go Custom 255.
<p>
<h1>VI. <a name="Local BBS's">LOCAL BBS'S
</h1><p>
<ol>
<li>The Black Bag BBS in Collegeville, Pennsylvania, has news, message boards and files on a variety of medical topics. Diabetes has its own area. You can also download a list of other health-related boards (the ones he shows as being DM-related - Sugar Free BBS and Diabetes Discussion - are listed below). Run by Dr. Edward Del Grosso, a radiologist, the Black Bag BBS is a Fidonet board and part of the international diabetes echo of some 3,500 systems. It can be reached by modem at (610) 454-7396 at up to 14.4 Kbps. The setup is the usual 8-1-N.
<p>
<li>The Sugar Free BBS in Hackensack, New Jersey, specializes largely in its diabetic message board. Run by SysOp Carl Zebooker, the Sugar Free BBS is another Fidonet board and part of the international diabetes echo of some 3,500 systems. It can be reached by modem at (201) 996-9397 at up to 14.4 Kbps. The setup is the usual 8-1-N.
<p>
<li>Diabetes Discussion BBS in Austin, Texas, is another Fidonet board and part of the international diabetes echo of some 3,500 systems. John Hargrove is the SysOp. Diabetes Discussion can be reached by modem at (512) 451-9737 at up to 28.8 Kbps. The setup is the usual 8-1-N.
<p>
<li>The Cracker Barrel BBS in Falmouth, Virginia, is run by Gary and Kevin Graham. This the world's largest board as far a number of medical echoes available, and it focuses diabetes. It has an active diabetes message section, extensive files, and links to Usenet newsgroups, including misc.health.diabetes and alt.support.diabetes.kids. The Cracker Barrel BBS is a Fidonet board and part of the international diabetes echo of some 3,500 systems. It can be reached by modem at (703) 899-2285 at up to 14.4 Kbps. The setup is the usual 8-1-N.
<p>
<li>The Guilde of High Sorcery BBS in San Diego, California, run by &quot;Lord Archmage,&quot; is another Fidonet board and part of the international diabetes echo of some 3,500 systems. It can be reached by modem at (619) 575-8249 at up to 28.8 Kbps. The setup is the usual 8-1-N. 
<p>
<li>Salata BBS in Redondo Beach, California, is devoted to cooking and recipes, health and nutrition. It has an on-line diabetic recipe database and other files available for downloading. This Fidonet board has Usenet access and is part of the international diabetes echo of some 3,500 systems. Karen Mintzias is the SysOp. Salata BBS can be reached by modem at (310) 543-0439 at up to 28.8 Kbps. The setup is the usual 8-1-N.
<p>
</ol>

<h1>OTHER SEARCH TOOLS</H1>
It is no longer possible for me to list every substantive Web page dealing with 
diabetes, although I do try to list all of the most useful ones that come to my attention and every other 
on-line resource. A recent Alta Vista advanced search for &quot;diabetes or diabetic&quot; turned up no fewer than 
40,000 Web pages where these terms were mentioned.
