<!--DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC
genl.htm
New Nov4,96 (at Diabetes Monitor)
By Rick Mendosa with help from Tim Berners-Lee, Marc Andreessen, Bill Gates, and
Will Vasquez
This file is safe for children. We endorse the SafeSurf concept-->
<HTML><HEAD>
<META http-equiv="PICS-Label" content='(PICS-1.0
"http://www.classify.org/safesurf/" l gen t for "http://www.mdcc.com" r
(SS~~000 1 SS~~100 1))'>
<TITLE>On-line Resources for Diabetics: General Web Sites</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#DFFFFF" background="bd2.gif"TEXT="#000000" link="000088" alink="CC6600" vlink="CC6600">
<a name="top"></a><a name="_top"></a>
<table>
<td>
<IMG src="spinstar.gif" height=47 width=47 ALT=" " align=left>
</td><td>
<h2><strong>
<font SIZE="+3"><A HREF="index.htm" TARGET="_top">D</a></FONT><font color="#ff00cc">IABETES</font>
<FONT SIZE="+3"><a href="with.htm" TARGET="_top">M</a></FONT><font color="#ff00cc">ONITOR:</font>
<br>
<FONT face="Rockwell, Comic Sans MS, Arial">
On-line Resources for Diabetics
</FONT>
</td><br>
</table>
<IMG SRC="red-line.gif" width=100% Height=2 ALT=" ">
</h2></strong>
<center>
<h2>General Web Sites</h2><br>
<h3><b>By Rick Mendosa</b>
<br>(Used with Permission)</h3>
<p>
Most Recent Update: February 10, 1997
</center>
<HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=center SIZE=2 NOSHADE>
<blockquote><blockquote>
<p>
<A HREF ="t.gif"></a><img src="t.gif" align=left alt=T>
his Web page brings 
together in one place descriptions of and links to only those general Web pages dealing with diabetes, 
but is linked to the seven other On-line Resources for Diabetes pages dealing with other Web pages,
other parts of the Internet, and other on-line services. Those links that I think are especially valuable are marked 
in <FONT COLOR="Red">red.</FONT>
<p>
<ol>
<li>The Lehigh Diabetic Archives is the repository of message sent on the Diabetic mailing lists, FAQs, and pictures of some members. 
<p>
If you have a SLIP/PPP account or lynx or similiar tools on a dial-up account, the URL is<br> 
<a href = "http://www.lehigh.edu/lists/diabetic/">http://www.lehigh.edu/lists/diabetic/</a>
<p>
Otherwise, ftp ftp.lehigh.edu and cd to the /pub/listserv/diabetic/ directory.
<p>

<li>Ian Preece maintains the Diabetic DataCentre in the United Kingdom with frequently asked 
questions about diabetes, software, medical news, late-breaking items of interest, and information 
for diabetic children and their parents. Its URL  is <br>
<a href="http://www.demon.co.uk/diabetic/">http://www.demon.co.uk/diabetic/</a>
<p>
He also maintains a related software archive of diabetic information in the
 United Kingdom. This archive includes software and photographs of some diabetics who are active on-line.
<p>
If you have a SLIP/PPP account or lynx or similiar tools on a dial-up account, the URL is<br> 
<a href="ftp://ftp.demon.co.uk/pub/diabetes/">ftp://ftp.demon.co.uk/pub/diabetes/</a>
<p>
Otherwise, ftp ftp.demon.co.uk and cd to the /pub/diabetes/ directory.
<p>

<li><FONT COLOR="Red">The Diabetes Monitor of the Midwest Diabetes Care Center</FONT> keeps getting better and 
better. One of the most valuable Web sites for diabetics, the Diabetes Monitor is also one 
of the most comprehensive and best designed. <a href="mailto:billq@mdcc.com">Dr. William W. Quick,</a> 
 a specialist in diabetes care and endocrinology, heads the Midwest Diabetes Care Center in 
Independence, Missouri, near Kansas City. The URL is
<br>
<a href="http://www.mdcc.com">http://www.mdcc.com</a>
<p>


<li><FONT COLOR="Red">Children with Diabetes</FONT> is a wonderful information 
resource dedicated to children with insulin-dependent diabetes and their parents maintained 
by <a href="mailto:jeffh@castleweb.com"> Jeffrey S. Hitchcock</a>. In spite of claims by 
another Web site, <i>Jeff's site</i> is the largest source of diabetes 
information on the Internet with more than 1,200 separate HTML files.
The URL is<br>
<a href="http://www.castleweb.com/diabetes/">http://www.castleweb.com/diabetes/</a>
<p>
One of the many great things on this excellent site is the Meter Bank, a way for people 
 to help other diabetics all over the world. Started to take advantage 
of a free meter offer, the Meter Bank founder organized a group effort to take 
advantage of the free meter offer so diabetics could get brand new meters free of charge.
The URL of the Meter Bank directly is <a href="http://www.castleweb.com/diabetes/d_07_010.htm">http://www.castleweb.com/diabetes/d_07_010.htm.</a>
<p>
Also here is a listing of prescription laws for insulin and syringes in each of the U.S. states and many 
countries. The URL is<br>
<a href="http://www.castleweb.com/diabetes/d_09_700.htm">http://www.castleweb.com/diabetes/d_09_700.htm</a>
<p>
Another excellent contribution that Jeff makes is by hosting chat rooms. These 
are sequential Web-hosted postings, not e-mail and not Internet Relay Chat (IRC). There are now five chat rooms at 
the Children with Diabetes web site:
<p>
<ul>
<li>Parents of kids with diabetes<br>
<li>Kids<br>
<li>Teens<br>
<li>Adults (with Type I)<br>
<li>Adults (with Type II)<br>
</ul>
<p>
You can reach the chat rooms by pointing your web browser at:<br>
<a href="http://www.castleweb.com/diabetes/d_0l_000.htm ">http://www.castleweb.com/diabetes/d_0l_000.htm </a>
<p>
<li>The PIGLET (Personalized Intelligently Generated Explanatory Text) system has been
developed to provide a tool for patients to browse through their own medical records.The
system allows users to access details on all aspects of Diabetes as well as information
which is personal to them. The URL is<br>
<a href="http://www.cee.hw.ac.uk/~alison/pigstart.html">http://www.cee.hw.ac.uk/~alison/pigstart.html</a>

<p>
<li>Harry Howisen's Diabetes Homepage has enough information about diabetes to have earned it lots of 
awards. However, unless you have a very fast connection you will want to turn off autoloading of in-line images,
which on this site are quite large and therefore slow to load.  It includes the Virtual Diabetic Game, the object of which is to get Derwood the Diabetic
through one adventure packed day without ending up in the hospital. The URL is <br>
<a href="http://www.nd.edu/~hhowisen/diabetes.html">http://www.nd.edu/~hhowisen/diabetes.html</a>
<p>
<li>Camp Sweeney, 75 miles north of Dallas-Fort Worth, Texas, is one of few camps in the country designed 
specifically for kids with diabetes. Camp Sweeney is owned and operated by the Southwestern Diabetic
 Foundation, a non-profit organization. Its URL is<br>
<a href="http://www.campsweeney.org/">http://www.campsweeney.org/</a>
<p>
<li>Medizin.de GmbH [German Medicine Inc.] in Munich is still under construction and has limited  information 
on diabetics in German  (the site links to an English-language version, which was also under
 construction when I looked). The URL is<br>
<a href="http://www.medizin.de/diabcare/intro.htm">http://www.medizin.de/diabcare/intro.htm</a>
<p>

<li>The now-defunct diabetes-max mailing list in Germany is archived and is now accessible on the Web  at: <br>
<a href="http://www.franken.de/users/daneel/C.Renner/dimail.html">http://www.franken.de/users/daneel/C.Renner/dimail.html</a>
<p>
<li><a href="mailto:aida@globalnet.co.uk">Dr. Eldon D. Lehmann</a> 
has made available a freeware program called AIDA, which  is a diabetes simulator for education and/or 
demonstration purposes for gaining an understanding about insulin dosage and dietary adjustments in 
insulin-dependent (type 1) diabetes. AIDADEM.EXE is now available in  a self-extracting archive program 
which runs under DOS on IBM PCs or compatibles.  When run, it produces a single file called
AIDADEMO.EXE, which is a demonstration program for the AIDA v4.0 diabetes
simulator. AIDAINST.EXE is a self-extracting archive program for the full freeware
simulator. You can download both the demo program and the full interactive simulator with your Web
browser from<br>
<a href="http://www.diabetic.org.uk/aida.htm">http://www.diabetic.org.uk/aida.htm</a><br>
The software is also available by ftp from the Software directory at <a href="ftp.diabetic.org.uk/pub/users/diabetes">ftp.diabetic.org.uk/pub/users/diabetes</a>
<p>
<li>CompuServe's Diabetes and Hypoglycemia Forum now maintains a Web site. 
 It has a good overview of the disease, several recent forum threads  and links 
to a few diabetes-specific pages. The URL is<br>
<a href="http://ourworld.compuserve.com/homepages/diabetes_forum">http://ourworld.compuserve.com/homepages/diabetes_forum</a>
<p>
<li>Curtise in San Francisco maintains a &quot;Friends and Family of Diabetics&quot; Web page where it says 
you can talk to other partners of diabetics. The URL is<br>
<a href="http://ourworld.compuserve.com:80/homepages/Curtise/">http://ourworld.compuserve.com:80/homepages/Curtise/</a>
<p>
<li>In the Netherlands, Coos Visser, who has Type I diabetes, maintains a diabetes page with information about 
Diabetes Vereniging Nederland. If you write him, he says he will email you information about diabetes. The URL is<br>
<a href="http://ourworld.compuserve.com:80/homepages/cvisser/diabetes.htm">http://ourworld.compuserve.com:80/homepages/cvisser/diabetes.htm</a>
<p>
<li>The Doctor's Guide to Diabetes Information & Resources has a great collection of links. Its URL is<br>
<a href="http://www.pslgroup.com/DIABETES.htm">http://www.pslgroup.com/DIABETES.htm</a>
<p>
<li><a href="mailto:mressler@nmaa.org">Marc A. Ressler</a>,  a SYSOP on 
CompuServe's Diabetes Forum, maintains an excellent Web page that doubles as an
introduction to the key diet and exercise section of that forum. The URL is
<a href="http://ourworld.compuserve.com/homepages/branded/diabetes.htm">http://ourworld.compuserve.com/homepages/branded/diabetes.htm</a>
<p>

<li>The Banting Museum & Education Center in London, Ontario, Canada, is certainly 
an appropriate Web site to include here, since it was Dr. Frederick Banting who 
discovered insulin at the 
University of Toronto in 1921-22, and the museum is in the house where he lived and 
practiced medicine. He was at that time a young surgeon in London, Ontario. In 1923 he
won the Nobel prize in Physiology or Medicine for his lifesaving discovery. 
The site is a must-see for anyone interested in diabetes. The graphics are like wandering 
through an excellent museum, and the explanations are first-rate. The URL is<br>
<a href="http://www.diabetes.ca/banting/banting.htm">http://www.diabetes.ca/banting/banting.htm</a>
<p>
<li>The files of frequently asked questions (FAQs) of the misc.health.diabetes Usenet 
group are much more valuable -- and much less argumentative -- than the newsgroup itself. 
It addition to the FAQ itself, here are discussions of insulin pumps and diabetes software. 
The URL is<br>
<a href="http://www.landfield.com/faqs/diabetes/">http://www.landfield.com/faqs/diabetes/</a>
<p>
<li>The CenterWatch Clinical Trials Listing Service is an international listing of clinical 
research trials run by a publishing company that focuses on the clinical trials industry. 
You can use this listing to search for clinical trials, find out information 
about physicians and medical centers performing clinical research, and to learn about drug 
therapies newly approved by the Food and Drug Administration. When I looked at t
he 
site in May 1996 there were 58 diabetes trials underway (look under endocrinology). The 
	URL is<br>
<a href="http://www.centerwatch.com/">http://www.centerwatch.com/</a>
<p>

<li>Diabetes UK, run by <a href="mailto:sjs@sexton.win-uk.net">Steven J Sexton,</a>
contains useful information related to blood glucose meters, injection devices, lancets, books, news items from 
the BDA <i>Balance</i> magazine and other information & products that are available in the UK to assist in the 
management of diabetes.
<p>
In addition there is a wide range of software availiable for downloading data from blood glucose meters, providing 
information on diet and nutrition and an interactive educational program for simulating the effects of changes in the 
insulin regime of insulin dependent diabetics.  The URL of Diabetes UK is <br>
<a href="http://www.diabetic.org.uk">http://www.diabetic.org.uk</a>
<p>
<li>Medscape is for health professionals and interested consumers and features peer-reviewed articles, zoomable 
color graphics, self-assessment features, medical news, free Medline access, and annotated links to Internet resources. 
A search for &quot;diabetes&quot; returned 50 matches, the maximum that the system is set up to accept. The URL 
is<br>
<a href="http://www.medscape.com/">http://www.medscape.com/</a>
<p>
<li>The Diabetes Type IIr Resource and Discussion Page is a response to the reality that most of the existing 
on-line resources for diabetics &quot;are heavily slanted to the problems, needs and issues of the Type I insulin 
dependent diabetic.&quot; So says Webmaster <a href="mailto:hwagner@postoffice.ptd.net">Harvey 
Wagner.</a> His new site is under construction. The URL is<br>
<a href="http://home.ptd.net/~hwagner/2r.htm">http://home.ptd.net/~hwagner/2r.htm</a>
<p>
<li><FONT COLOR="Red">The Diabetes NetWork (D-Net)</FONT> is a site of the Computer Mediated Support for Diabetes
Self-Management project at Oregon Research Institute. You will find a host of resources available on D-Net to assist 
and support you in your diabetes self-care efforts. Some of the features you will find are diabetes specific 
information, nutrition, exercise and healthy eating tips, diabetes support groups, a live chat area, and individualized 
personal self care planning. The URL is<br>
<a href="http://dnet.ori.org/newuser/">http://dnet.ori.org/newuser/</a>
<p>
<li>Kristina's Room, a chat zone for parents of diabetic children, is a good place to go 
to meet other parents of diabetic children, to share ideas and problems 
and even just to unload some of the frustrations of dealing with diabetes 
everyday. The URL is at <br>
<a href="http://myspot.com/cgi-bin/nic-cgi/chatcenter2.pl">http://myspot.com/cgi-bin/nic-cgi/chatcenter2.pl</a>
<p>
<li>The WholeNurse Info on Diabetes Page is &quot;for nurses, patients, and 
medical personnel of all kinds.&quot; The URL is <br>
<a href="http://www.wholenurse.com/diabetes.htm">http://www.wholenurse.com/diabetes.htm</a>
<p>
<li><FONT COLOR="Red">Diabetes Information at Mediconsult.com</FONT> is a comprehensive 
source of information and services dedicated to patients and their relatives.
One of its missions is to provide free, easy to understand, accurate
and up to date information about diabetes. It includes 
an extensive drug database courtesy of The United States Pharmacopeial Convention, Inc. (USP). The drug 
database is located in the Drug Information section of Diabetes and includes
information on available brand names, proper use, and possible side
effects and contraindictions. 
Another excellent feature of the site is the &quot;Journal Club&quot; where 
medical writers choose several papers on diabetes from the medical
literature that are of interest to patients, relatives or
other interested users and summarize the content in layman terms. Also here is
the &quot;Support Group&quot; which allows users to post comments, ideas or
questions to a public diabetes bulletin board to encourage a sensible
discussion of topic pertaining to diabetes. Messages can be posted
anonymously if desired. The submission process is moderated to ensure
inappopriate messages are not posted. The URL is<br>
<a href="http://www.mediconsult.com/diabetes/">http://www.mediconsult.com/diabetes/</a>
<p> 
<li> HealthGate has free access to Medline. Its URL is<br>
<a href="http://www.healthgate.com/HealthGate/home.html">http://www.healthgate.com/HealthGate/home.html</a>
<p>
<li> Medline is also available free to all UK/USA residents on MEDLINEplus from Healthworks 
Online. The URL is<br>
<a href="http://www.healthworks.co.uk/hw/medline/medline.html">http://www.healthworks.co.uk/hw/medline/medline.html</a>

<p>
<li> The first Portuguese-language home page for diabetics comes from Brazil. It includes products, services, 
and lots of information for diabetics. They tell us that as soon as they get their own domain name the address will 
change to<br>
<a href="http://www.diabetes-br.com">http://www.diabetes-br.com</a>
<br>
Meanwhile, the URL is<br>
<a href="http://www.empresa.com/com/diabetes/">http://www.empresa.com/com/diabetes/</a>
<p>
<li> Denmark now has a diabetes Web site. It is, of course, in Danish and says that &quot;Diabetes/sukkersyge 
ONLINE Danmarks vist nok eneste Web specielt for diabetikere.&quot; Webmaster is 
<a href="mailto:diabetes@image.dk">Thomas Hansen.</a> The URL is<br>
<a href="http://www2.dk-online.dk/users/vilhelm/diabetes/">http://www2.dk-online.dk/users/vilhelm/diabetes/</a>
<p>
<li> Matthew J. Shim has put his thesis for a master of public health degree on-line. The subject is 
<i>Self-reported Diabetes in Hawaii: 1988-1993</i> and the URL is<br>
<a href="http://www.aloha.net/~mattman/diabetes.html">http://www.aloha.net/~mattman/diabetes.html</a>
<p>
<li> Diabetes is the leading cause of the development of a Charcot joint, or Charcot foot, today. Podiatrist 
Bret M. Ribotsky, D.P.M., has an excellent and technical paper on the management of diabetic charcot arthropathy at<br>
<a href="http://www.infowest.com/podiatry/medical/diabetic/complic/charcot.html">http://www.infowest.com/podiatry/medical/diabetic/complic/charcot.html</a>
<p>
<li> Diabetes Well is sponsored by the Pacific Medical Research Foundation (PMRF), a 
not-for-profit organization in Santa Clara, California. Founded by J. Joseph Prendergast, M.D., a 
diabetologist, PMRF is dedicated to the study, treatment, education, and eventual cure of diabetes and 
its physical complications. Note particularly the &quot;Bill Of Rights For People with 
Diabetes.&quot;The URL is<br>
<a href="http://www.diabeteswell.com/">http://www.diabeteswell.com/</a>
<p>
<li> Go to this page if you want to know what &quot;Human Insulin Hexamer&quot; looks like. The URL is<br>
<a href="http://www.artn.nwu.edu/Commercial/Hexamer.html">http://www.artn.nwu.edu/Commercial/Hexamer.html</a>
<p>
<li> Diabetes World is the Web page for the Diabetes List at diabetes@world.std.com. The Web 
page includes information about forthcoming events, a collection of FAQs, and guidelines for the 
Diabetes List. You have a choice of two URLs that will take you to the same place:<br>
<a href="http://www.cde.com/diabetes.world/">http://www.cde.com/diabetes.world/</a><br>
or<br>
<a href="http://www.cde.com/~diabetic/">http://www.cde.com/~diabetic/</a><br>
<p>
<li> Jo Ann Foster's Diabetes Information and Advice Page is based on her experience of being 
IDDM with many complications of diabetes. The URL is<br>
<a href="http://castaway.cc.uwf.edu/~jfoster/">http://castaway.cc.uwf.edu/~jfoster/</a>
<p>
<li> The Family's Guide to Diabetes is a guide for diabetic kids and their families based on the 
experience of 13-year-old Ryan Dinkgrave of Livonia, Michigan. The URL is<br>
<a href="http://www.geocities.com/HotSprings/1962/">http://www.geocities.com/HotSprings/1962/</a>
<p>
<li> &quot;Type 1 Diabetics in High School and College&quot; is an open forum where diabetics 
in high school and college can voice their experiences or problems. The URL is<br>
<a href="http://www.angelfire.com/pg1/diabetic/index.html">http://www.angelfire.com/pg1/diabetic/index.html</a>
<p>
<li> Diabetes Management Reports is a Web site devoted to bringing the power of computer 
software diabetes management to you. You enter information such as glucose values, insulin doses, 
or diet requirements. Then the Webmaster, David Grenda, processes the data using his computer 
analysis software and sends you an easy-to-read report via e-mail. The URL is<br>
<a href="http://getnet.com/~dgrenda/diabetes/david.htm">http://getnet.com/~dgrenda/diabetes/david.htm</a>
<p>
<li> The Mid Maine Diabetes Discussion List and its Web page were created to give people with 
diabetes in Mid-Maine -- actually all of Maine -- a place where they can discuss diabetes, get support 
and find out where they can get the help they need. The site will also post coming diabetes events, 
support group meetings, Web diabetes links, related medical sites, and happenings. Membership is 
not limited to people in Maine. If you have diabetes or an interest in it for whatever reason, you are 
welcome to subscribe to the list. Webmaster is <a href="mailto:bob@somtel.com">Bob LeBlanc.
</a> The URL is<br>
<a href="http://www.mint.net/mmddl/">http://www.mint.net/mmddl/</a>
<p>
<li> Daniel Klein is a Type I diabetic and lives in Berlin. That probably explains why his Web page 
is in German. His URL is<br>
<a href="http://ourworld.compuserve.com/homepages/Daniel_Klein/">http://ourworld.compuserve.com/homepages/Daniel_Klein/</a>
<p>
<li> The Discovery of Insulin On-line Resource Center is a magnificent Web site not to be missed 
by anyone with diabetes, whether on insulin yet or not. <a href="mailto:rbanting@cgocable.net"> 
Bob Banting,</a> a great-nephew of the principal discoverer, Sir Frederick Banting, is the 
Webmaster. The URL is<br>
<a href="http://web.idirect.com/~discover/">http://web.idirect.com/~discover/</a>
<p>
<li> &quot;Diabetes Mellitus from Western and TCM [Traditional Chinese Medicine] 
Perspectives,&quot; by <a href="mailto: CHAOTE1@aol.com"> Clinton Choate</a> is an 
extensive treatise. While the discussion of Western treatment of diabetes has little to add to that 
found elsewhere (and is even dated in its emphasis on sugar rather than fat), the section on 
Chinese medicine is most interesting. It includes acupuncture, diet, and herbs. The URL is<br>
<a href="http://acupuncture.com/Acup/Diabetes.htm">http://acupuncture.com/Acup/Diabetes.htm</a>
<p>
<li> <a href="mailto:carl@knighten.com">Carl Knighten</a> has a collection of about two 
dozen recipes for diabetics by <a href="mailto:kyoung@prstorm.bison.mb.ca">kyoung@prstorm.bison.mb.ca</a> 
 on his home page. The URL is
<a href="http://www.knighten.com/misc/diabetic.htm">http://www.knighten.com/misc/diabetic.htm</a>
<p>
<li> Hundreds of &quot;Diabetic Recipes&quot; are available on-line at<br>
<a href="http://godzilla.eecs.berkeley.edu/recipes/diabetic/">http://godzilla.eecs.berkeley.edu/recipes/diabetic/</a>
<p>
<li> Part of <a href="mailto:jlarsen@dietitian.com">Joanne Larsen's</a> Ask the 
Dietitian<sup>TM</sup>
site is a full page of questions and answers about diabetes. You can also check out a Weight/Calorie 
Calculator. 
The URL is <br>
<a href="http://www.dietitian.com./diabetes.html">http://www.dietitian.com./diabetes.html</a>
<p>
<li> The Philadelphia-based Diabetes Education and Research Center is a non-profit organization 
dedicated to the improved health of people with diabetes. The center
provides training and education to people with diabetes, their families, and caregivers,
conducts research, and is involved in local and national diabetes forums. The site includes a chat area  
and tips for managing your diabetes. The URL is<br>
<a href="http://www.libertynet.org/~diabetes/">http://www.libertynet.org/~diabetes/</a>
<p>
<li> The diabetes page of Health-Net, a interactive on-line medical information site, 
includes a good general outline of principles of nutrition for diabetics by Deborah Michael, MD, and 
whats new (Metformin). The URL is<br>
<a href="http://www.health-net.com/diabetes.htm">http://www.health-net.com/diabetes.htm</a>
<p>
<li> <a href="mailto:dfitz@endocrinologist.com">Endocrinologist David Fitz-Patrick, M.D.,</a> 
directs the Diabetes and Hormone Center of the Pacific in Honolulu, Hawaii. The center is a 
comprehensive state-of-the-art center for the diagnosis and treatment of diabetes and hormonal 
disorders. The center's diabetes page has several valuable features. One lets you enter your latest 
Hemoglobin<sub>A1c</sub> result and see what effect reducing it to 7.0 would have on your
 risk of eye complications, advanced eye disease, and of dying. Another lets you test your diabetes
 knowledge and how well you are taking care of yourself.
 The URL is<br>
<a href="http://www.endocrinologist.com/">http://www.endocrinologist.com/</a>
<p>
<li> The National Diabetes Education Initiative (NDEI) Web site for healthcare professionals is an online 
resource for medical education programs on Type II diabetes and insulin resistance. The URL is<br>
<a href="http://www.ndei.org/">http://www.ndei.org/</a>
<p>
<li> Cats are so much like the people that they also get diabetes. Feline 
Diabetes is a clearinghouse for information, questions, and links concerning diabetes in cats and is 
maintained by a <i>human</i> physician -- not a veterinarian -- <a href="mailto:raprice@interserv.com">Rebecca 
A. Price,</a> who is the owner of a diabetic cat. The URL is<br>
<a href="http://home.sprynet.com/interserv/raprice/diabetes.htm">http://home.sprynet.com/interserv/raprice/diabetes.htm</a>
<p>
<li> Riding (motorcycles) on Insulin is a forum for motorcycle riders who also happen to have 
Type I diabetes. The site is still under construction. The webmaster is <a href="mailto:smma@ioa.com">Gary</a> 
and the URL is<br>
<a href="http://www.ioa.com/home/smma/diabetes.html">http://www.ioa.com/home/smma/diabetes.html</a>
<p>
<li> The attractively-designed German Diabetes Forum includes information for diabetics, 
addresses of selfhelp groups, contact information for companies that sell diabetes supplies in 
Germany, and also has six German-language chat rooms, including areas for general diabetes 
discussion, pumpers, parents of diabetic children. The URL is<br>
<a href="http://diabetes-forum.com/ ">http://diabetes-forum.com/</a>
<p>
<li> <a href="mailto:cpa@pixie.co.za">Patrick Paterson </a> has the first diabetes links 
home page in South Africa, which he calls the &quot;Comp-Pat-Able Home Page.&quot; The URL 
is<br>
<a href="http://www.pix.za/os/cpa.htm">http://www.pix.za/os/cpa.htm</a>
<p>
<li> J.M. Kelly, an instructor in the allied health science department, Indiana University South 
Bend, has very nice Web page for children with diabetes. The URL is<br>
<a href="http://sun1.iusb.edu/~jkelly/jdb.html">http://sun1.iusb.edu/~jkelly/jdb.html</a>
<p>
<li> &quot;Dr Joe's Spanish & Portuguese pages&quot; about diabetes can be helpful for those 
who use those languages. The URL is<br>
<a href="http://www.traders.co.uk/insulintrust/drjoes.htm">http://www.traders.co.uk/insulintrust/drjoes.htm</a>
</ol>
<HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=center SIZE=2 NOSHADE>
<blockquote><P>
