<HTML><HEAD>
<META http-equiv="PICS-Label" content='(PICS-1.0
"http://www.classify.org/safesurf/" l gen t for "http://www.mdcc.com" r
(SS~~000 1 SS~~100 1))'>
<TITLE>On-line Resources for Diabetics: Government Web Sites</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#DFFFFF" background="bd2.gif"TEXT="#000000" link="000088" alink="CC6600" vlink="CC6600">
<a name="top"></a><a name="_top"></a>
<table>
<td>
<IMG src="spinstar.gif" height=47 width=47 ALT=" " align=left>
</td><td>
<h2><strong>
<font SIZE="+3"><A HREF="index.htm" TARGET="_top">D</a></FONT><font color="#ff00cc">IABETES</font>
<FONT SIZE="+3"><a href="with.htm" TARGET="_top">M</a></FONT><font color="#ff00cc">ONITOR:</font>
<br>
<FONT face="Rockwell, Comic Sans MS, Arial">
On-line Resources for Diabetics
</FONT>
</td><br>
</table>
<IMG SRC="red-line.gif" width=100% Height=2 ALT=" ">
</h2></strong>
<center>
<h2>Government Web Sites</h2>
<h3><b>By Rick Mendosa</b>
<br>(Used with Permission)</h3>
Most Recent Update: January 5, 1997

</center>

<HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=center SIZE=2 NOSHADE>

<blockquote><blockquote>

<p>

<A HREF ="t.gif"></a><img src="t.gif" align=left alt=T>his Web page brings 

together in one place descriptions of and links to only those government Web pages dealing with diabetes, 

but is linked to the seven other On-line Resources for Diabetes pages dealing with other Web pages,

other parts of the Internet, and other on-line services. Those links that I think are especially valuable are marked 

in <FONT COLOR="Red">red.</FONT>

<p>

<ol>

<li><FONT COLOR="Red">The National Institute of Diabetes and Digestive and Kidney Disease</FONT> of the National Institutes of

 Health (NIH) in Bethesda, Maryland, had patient information documents on diabetes and its complications

 and news releases. The documents include &quot;Diabetes Control and Complications Trial&quot; and

&quot;Diabetes Dictionary.&quot; 

<p>

The URL is <br>

<a href="http://www.niddk.nih.gov/NIDDK_HomePage.html">http://www.niddk.nih.

gov/NIDDK_HomePage.html</a>

<p>

<li>The World Health Organization in Geneva, Switzerland, has a gopher server with a small number of documents on diabetes.

<p>

If you have a SLIP/PPP account or lynx or similiar tools on a dial-up account, the URL is <br>

<a href="gopher://gopher.who.ch:70/11/.ncd/.diabetes">gopher://gopher.who.ch:70/11/.ncd/.diabetes</a>

<p>

Otherwise, gopher gopher.who.ch. Select WHO's major programmes.../, then Noncommunicable Diseases (NCD).../, then Diabetes.../.

<p>

<li>The Indian Health Service's "Patient Education Protocols" includes one for diabetes. The URL is <br>

<a href="http://www.ihs.gov/">http://www.ihs.gov/</a>

<p>

<li>The CDC Diabetes Home Page comes from the Division of Diabetes Translation, a division of the 

National Center for Chronic Disease Prevention and Health Promotion of the Centers for Disease Control and 

Prevention, an agency of the U.S. government. The division is responsible for translating scientific research findings 

into health promotion, disease prevention and treatment strategies. A valuable resource here is the 

&quot;National Diabetes Fact Sheet.&quot; Its URL is

<br>

<a href="http://www.cdc.gov/nccdphp/ddt/ddthome.htm">http://www.cdc.gov/nccdphp/ddt/ddthome.htm</a>

<p>

<li> Did you know that the IDDM1 gene maps to chromosome 6? You can find that out on the Gene Map of the 

Human Genome, which is  

now on-line from The National Center for Biotechnical Information of the National Institutes of Health. The Human 

Genome Project is expected to produce a sequence of DNA representing the functional blueprint and evolutionary 

history of the human species. If you are interested in the IDDM1 gene, these are some Web pages to study:<br>

<a href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/cgi-bin/SCIENCE96/nph-gene?IDDM1">http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/cgi-bin/SCIENCE96/nph-gene?IDDM1</a>

<a href="http://www3.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov:80/htbin-post/Omim/dispmim?222100">http://www3.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov:80/htbin-post/Omim/dispmim?222100</a>

<a href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/cgi-bin/SCIENCE96/chr?6">http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/cgi-bin/SCIENCE96/chr?6</a>

<p>

<li> The Diabetes Database of the National Institute of Diabetes and Digestive and Kidney Diseases 

(NIDDK) of the National Institutes of Health (NIH) provides titles, abstracts, and 

availability information on diabetes information and health education materials. The value of this 

database is that it lists a wealth of health promotion and education materials that are not indexed 

elsewhere. The URL is <br>

<a href="http://www.aerie.com/nihdb/ndic/dmdbase.html">http://www.aerie.com/nihdb/ndic/dmdbase.html</a>

<p>


</ol>
<HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=center SIZE=2 NOSHADE>
<p>
<a> <A HREF="faq.htm"><img alt="[Go to Main 
On-line Resources Page]" src ="next.gif"></a> Go to 
<A HREF="faq.htm">Main On-Line Resources Page </A>
<p>
<a> <A HREF="mag.htm"><img alt="[Go to Publications  
Web Page]" src ="previous.gif"></a> Go back 
to <A HREF="mag.htm">Publications On-line Resources Page </A><p>
<p>

<HR WIDTH=50% ALIGN=center SIZE=2 NOSHADE>
<blockquote><p>
&copy; Copyright 1997 Rick Mendosa. All Rights Reserved. 
<p>
You may quote part of this page in on-line documents and written publications, but please notify me 
so I can add a reference and make sure that you add pointers to the places where people can get the 
latest version. 
<p>
Permission to link this site to yours is not needed. Of course, I would be delighted to hear from you, 
especially if you have a new site that you think should be linked here. 
<p>
I have no control over the content or continued existence of any external on-line resources linked 
here, and I therefore cannot guarantee that they will function as promised. The appearance of a site on 
this list does not imply any endorsement by me. 
<p>
Since this information is constantly changing, readers are urged to email corrections and updates to 
me at <a href="mailto://mendosa@cruzio.com">mendosa@cruzio.com</a>.
</blockquote></blockquote>

<p>
