<body BGCOLOR="#DFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" ALINK="#0000FF" background="bd2.gif" VLINK="#FF0000">
<a name="top"></a><a name="_top"></a>
<table>
<td>
<IMG src="spinstar.gif" height=47 width=47 ALT=" " align=left>
</td><td>
<h2><strong>
<font SIZE="+3"><A HREF="index.htm" TARGET="_top">D</a></FONT><font color="#ff00cc">IABETES</font>
<FONT SIZE="+3"><a href="with.htm" TARGET="_top">M</a></FONT><font color="#ff00cc">ONITOR:</font>
<br>
<FONT face="Rockwell, Comic Sans MS, Arial">
About the <nobr>Midwest Diabetes Care Center</nobr></font>
</td><br>
</table>
<IMG SRC="red-line.gif" width=100% Height=2 ALT=" ">
</h2></strong>
<blockquote><P>

<STRONG><FONT SIZE="+2">W</FONT></STRONG>hether you are new to our practice, or a longtime patient, we welcome you, and we appreciate the opportunity to provide medical care and education.
<P>Thank you for taking this moment to read about our services.
Please share this information with any friend who might benefit from our services; we are accepting new patients with diabetes or other endocrine problems (such as thyroid disorders), and would be pleased to assist them and their physicians also.
<P>
We participate with many PPO&#0146;s and two HMO&#0146;s (CIGNA and MetraHealth/United Health Care),
and we accept assignment from Medicare.
It is important to understand
that <strong>if you have HMO or Medicare insurance,
you will need a referral</strong> from your Primary Care Physician to see us.
<P>
If you have any other questions, please call us at <STRONG>(816) 836-2222</STRONG>
or send E-mail to
<em>
<A HREF="mailto:monitor@mdcc.com">monitor@mdcc.com</A>
</em>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<center>
<IMG SRC="red-line.gif" Height=2 Width=50% ALT=" ">
<H2>
<FONT SIZE="+3">T</font>able of <FONT SIZE="+3">C</font>ontents</h2>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>
<A HREF="#htfu"><EM> How to find us</EM></A>
<BR> <A HREF="#hours"><EM> Hours</EM></A>
<BR> <A HREF="#pc"><EM> Telephone Calls</EM></A>
<BR> <A HREF="#oms"><EM> Our Medical Staff</EM></A>
<BR> <A HREF="#np"><EM> New Patients</EM></A>
<BR> <A HREF="#appt"><EM> Appointments</EM></A>
<BR> <A HREF="#nsp"><EM> Non-Smoking Policy</EM></A>
<BR> <A HREF="#ec"><EM> Emergency Care</EM></A>
<BR> <A HREF="#appt"><EM> Appointments</EM></A>
<BR> <A HREF="#ds"><EM> Diabetes Supplies</EM></A>
<BR> <A HREF="#hosp"><EM> Hospital Care</EM></A>
<BR> <A HREF="#lab"><EM> Laboratory Tests</EM></A>
<BR> <A HREF="#hych"><EM>  How You Can Help</EM></A>
</center>
<center>
<IMG SRC="red-line.gif" Height=2 Width=50% ALT=" ">
</center><P>
<a name="htfu"></a><H2><IMG SRC="greendot.gif" alt=" "> How to find us</H2>
The Midwest Diabetes Care Center is in Independence, Missouri.
We are in Suite 504 of the Truman-Forest Professional Building,
at 1515 West Truman Road,
adjacent to the COLUMBIA Independence Regional Health Center.

<UL>
<LI><H3><EM>From the North (North Kansas City and Liberty, Missouri, and Iowa):</EM></H3>
Take I-435 on the east side of the Kansas City metro area, southbound. From I-435, take the Truman Road exit eastbound, into Independence. Go east about three miles, and at the second signal light beyond the railroad overpass, turn right onto Forest, and immediately turn right again into the parking garage.
<p>
<strong>Or,</strong>
take Highway 291 south from Liberty, and turn west onto Truman Road. Continue through downtown Independence, past the Truman home, and turn left at the signal light at Forest, and immediately turn right into the parking garage.<P>
<LI><H3><EM>From the East (Blue Springs, Lee&#0146;s Summit, and Columbia, Missouri):</EM></H3>
Take I-70 westbound to either the Highway 291 exit or to Noland Road, and turn northbound; turn west onto Truman Road. Continue through downtown Independence, past the Truman home, and turn left at the signal light at Forest, and immediately turn right into the parking garage.<P>
<LI><H3><EM>From the South (southern Kansas City and Johnson County, Kansas):</EM></H3>
Take I-435 on the east side of the Kansas City metro area, northbound. From I-435, take the Truman Road exit eastbound, into Independence. Go east about three miles, and at the second signal light beyond the railroad overpass, turn right onto Forest, and immediately turn right again into the parking garage.<P>
<LI><H3><EM>From the West (Kansas City, MO and Topeka, Kansas)</EM>:</H3>
Take I-70 eastbound, then turn onto I-435 northbound. From I-435, take the Truman Road exit eastbound, into Independence. Go east about three miles, and at the second signal light beyond the railroad overpass, turn right onto Forest, and immediately turn right again into the parking garage.
</UL>
<a name="hours"></a>
<H2><IMG SRC="greendot.gif" alt=" "> Hours</H2>
The office is open to make appointments from 8:00 AM to 4:30 PM daily,
Mondays through Thursdays.
<!--, and 8:00 AM till noon on Fridays.-->
<P>
The first appointment time is usually 9:00 AM on Mondays and Tuesdays, and 10:00 AM on Wednesdays,
and the last is 4:30 PM.
<!--, Mondays through Thursdays.-->
We do not see office patients on Thursdays and Fridays.
<!--during the summer.
<!--On Fridays, we see emergency problems,
and have educational and followup sessions.-->
<a name="pc"></a>
<H2><IMG SRC="greendot.gif" alt=" "> Telephone Calls</H2>
Our <strong>main office number</strong> is <STRONG>(816) 836-2222</STRONG>.
<p>
<strong>Twenty-four hour medical coverage</strong> is available
by calling another number,
<STRONG>(816) 836-4444</STRONG>,
and leaving your phone number, name, and a brief message.
<p>
Our <strong>business office&#0146;s number</strong> is <STRONG>(816) 836-5579</STRONG>.
<P>
We encourage all patients to call with any questions that they have about diabetes or endocrine problems. However, it would be very unfair to other patients if the doctor answered every telephone call that occurs during regular office hours. The Diabetes Nurse Educators can answer many of your questions. For example, they can review your home blood glucose readings, suggest adjustments to your diabetes program, and answer any new questions that you might have. They will relay questions to the physician if necessary, and your call will be returned as soon as possible. If you have access to a fax machine, you can fax your recent home blood glucose readings to us ahead of time.<P>
<a name="oms"></a>
<H2><IMG SRC="greendot.gif" alt=" "> Our Medical Staff</H2>
Our professional staff are all Certified as Diabetes Educators by the National Certification Board for Diabetes Educators. The NCBDE evaluates knowledge of diabetes and its complications, educational principles, and also requires knowledge of the psychologic and social aspects of diabetes care.
<p>
<a name="wwq"></a>
The Medical Director of the Midwest Diabetes Care Centers program is
<A HREF="cv-wwq.htm">William W. Quick, MD,</a>
who is a specialist in diabetes care and endocrinology.
(Endocrinology is the branch of Internal Medicine
that is concerned with the hormone-producing glandular system.)
He is available for consultation and advice
for patients with diabetes,
and can provide ongoing specialty care
in consultation with your personal physician.
Bill, as he prefers to be called,
is a nationally-known expert in diabetes education, and
is a past president of the American Association of Diabetes Educators.
He is a Fellow of the American College of Endocrinology,
and a Fellow of the American College of Physicians,
and is certified as a specialist by
the American Board of Internal Medicine
in Endocrinology and Diabetes Care.
<p>
Because we feel that the care of diabetes
requires a team of health professionals,
our staff includes Diabetes Nurse Educators,
who are able to review all aspects
of diabetes with patients and their families.
They can teach techniques
such as home blood glucose monitoring
and the use of insulin delivery devices,
and answer your questions about diabetes.
<a name="np"</a>
<H2><IMG SRC="greendot.gif" alt=" "> New Patients</H2>
Bring a list of your current medications (or the pill bottles themselves),
your home blood glucose readings if you have been testing,
and photocopies of any lab tests that were done in the last six months.
<P>
Also, if you are using a blood glucose meter, bring it in at every visit,
and our staff will check it for accuracy.
<p>
Please bring your insurance I.D. card and/or insurance forms with you.
If your insurance requires authorization from your personal physician to see specialists,
we <strong>must</strong> have the signed authorization form before we can see you.
<P>
And, what NOT to do:  Don&#0146;t starve yourself by skipping meals
on the day of your office visit!
We won&#0146;t order any &#0147;fasting&#0148; lab studies at your first visit.
<a name="appt"</a>
<H2><IMG SRC="greendot.gif" alt=" "> Appointments</H2>
We see all patients on an appointment basis, and therefore request that you always call in advance, so that we can reserve time for you. If you are unable to keep your appointment,
please let us know, and we will reschedule your appointment.
<p>
To be fair to other patients who also want an appointment soon,
please telephone us if you find  you will be unable to keep your scheduled appointment.
If you do miss a scheduled appointment without notifying us in advance,
you will be charged for the missed appointment.
<P>
We will make every effort to honor all time commitments; whenever possible, you will be fully informed of any delay.
<a name="nsp"</a>
<H2><IMG SRC="greendot.gif" alt=" "> Non-Smoking Policy</H2>
Smoking is dangerous to everybody&#0146;s health. We do not permit smoking at our office.
<a name="ec"</a>
<H2><IMG SRC="greendot.gif" alt=" "> Emergency Care</H2>
We all realize that emergencies occur unpredictably, and we will try to respond to your problem promptly. If an emergency occurs, you can telephone our emergency number, (816) 836-4444, 24 hours a day. Dialing this phone number will automatically activate the beeper of the staff person who is &#0147;on call,&#0148; and if you leave your phone number, you will be called back promptly.
Of course, you may call your personal physician, or go directly to the Emergency Room of the nearest hospital.
<a name="billing"</a>
<H2><IMG SRC="greendot.gif" alt=" "> Billing</H2>
The Midwest Diabetes Care Center participates with many insurance plans,
including Medicare, Blue Cross/Blue Shield, 
many PPO&#0146;s, and two HMO&#0146;s (CIGNA and MetraHealth/United Health Care).
We will file your primary insurance claims electronically to your insurance company.
We ask that you file your secondary insurance yourself.
<p>
You will be expected to make a part payment or co-payment at every visit.
If you choose to pay off your entire balance at the time of service,
we will give you a 5% discount.
<P>
You will receive monthly statements
for any outstanding co-insurance
or deductible.
We expect payment of your balance due
within 15 days after receiving your statement,
unless you make other arrangements with our Office Manager.
There is a Repeat Billing Fee on all accounts over 90 days.
<P>
We want our payment policies to be fair to everyone;
if they do not fit your personal circumstances,
please notify the Midwest Diabetes Care Center staff,
and other arrangements may be made.
<P>
If you anticipate any difficulty in paying your bill promptly,
or have any questions about your account,
please call our business office between 8 and 11 AM, at (816) 836-5579.
Often a phone call will prevent a misunderstanding.
<P>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="visa-mc.gif" Height=29 Width=98 ALT=" Credit Cards ">
</CENTER>
<P>
We accept Visa and Mastercard. If you wish,
you can call us with your credit card number and pay your balance by telephone.
<a name="ds"</a>
<H2><IMG SRC="greendot.gif" alt=" ">Diabetes Supplies</H2>
As a service to our patients, we have information
and demonstration samples of most blood glucose meters,
and many other diabetes items.
Our Diabetes Nurse Educators
will be happy to show you the various devices,
so you can decide if they might be helpful to you.
We keep up-to-date with pricing information,
and have rebate coupons from the manufacturers.
<a name="hosp"</a>
<H2><IMG SRC="greendot.gif" alt=" "> Hospital Care</H2>
Dr. Quick is on the staff of three hospitals in the eastern part of the Kansas City metropolitan area:
<UL>
<LI>COLUMBIA Independence Regional Health Center
<LI>Medical Center of Independence
<LI>Saint Mary&#0146;s Hospital of Blue Springs
</UL>
If you are hospitalized for any reason, be sure to tell the physician in charge of your care that we have been caring for you. We can send any necessary information from your record directly by fax to any hospital. And if you are hospitalized at any of the hospitals listed above, you should ask your physicians to consult Dr. Quick, so he can help with your diabetic or endocrine care.
<a name="lab"</a>
<H2><IMG SRC="greendot.gif" alt=" ">Laboratory Tests</H2>
Depending on various factors, including insurance company rules,
any lab tests that are needed for your case might be obtained at your personal doctor&#0146;s office, or a laboratory close to the Midwest Diabetes Care Center office. We do perform fingerstick blood glucose and glycohemoglobin testing at the Midwest Diabetes Care Center. We will also recommend that you routinely bring in your own blood glucose meter if you have one, so that
our Diabetes Nurse Educators can check its accuracy with you.<p>
If the result of any lab test is not normal for your situation, we will notify you. If you wish to know whether
the results of lab tests have been received at the Midwest Diabetes Care Center, please call.<p>
We regularly send copies of your lab results to your personal physician, and to other doctors that you see, if appropriate.
If you want a personal report,
or an actual copy of your lab results, please ask.
<a name="hych"</a>
<H2><IMG SRC="greendot.gif" alt=" "> How You Can Help</H2>
<blockquote>
<H4><strong>Take charge of your own health!</strong></H4>
</blockquote>
Your participation as the most important member of your &#0147;health care team&#0148; will ensure you the best possible care.
<UL><LI>Let us know as far in advance as possible
if you will be unable to keep an appointment.
<LI>Please advise our staff of changes
in your insurance, address, or phone number which may have occurred since your last visit.
<LI>Check your statement carefully
when you receive it. The more quickly you notify us of any expected difficulty in paying your bill promptly, or of any apparent errors, the more quickly the issue can be resolved.
<LI>Tell the staff, or call the Midwest Diabetes Care Center at (816) 836-2222, if you have any comments or suggestions about additional ways that we can help you.</UL>
</ul>

<IMG SRC="red-line.gif" Height=2 Width=100% ALT=" ">
