<IMG SRC="red-line.gif" Height=2 Width=50% ALT=" ">
<h2>
<em><a href="#cnd">Cats and Dogs: Diabetes Information</a>
<br><a href="#cats">Cats: Diabetes Information</a>
<br><a href="#dogs">Dogs: Diabetes Information</a>
<br><a href="#ngs">Newsgroups: Diabetes Information</a>
<br><a href="#nodi">Veterinary Information and other websites (but without diabetes information)</a>
</em></h2>
<IMG SRC="red-line.gif" Height=2 Width=50% ALT=" ">
</center>


<blockquote><P>
<a name="cnd"></a>
<h3>Cats and Dogs: Diabetes Information</h3>

<IMG SRC="star.gif" height=14 width=14 alt=" ">
<em><a href="http://www.versa.com/ada/diabetes/cats&dogs.html">
Diabetes Mellitus in Dogs & Cats</a></em>
(&quot;http://www.versa.com/ada/diabetes/cats&dogs.html&quot;)
<br>
By Richard W. Nelson, DVM, and Edward C. Feldman, DVM


<a name="cats"></a>
<h3>Cats with Diabetes and Diabetes Information for cats</h3>

<IMG SRC="star.gif" height=14 width=14 alt=" ">
<EM><A HREF="http://www.halcyon.com/alancrab/gorby.page.html">
Gorby the Cat</A></EM>
(&quot;http://www.halcyon.com/alancrab/gorby.page.html&quot;)
<br>
A diabetic feline (with a photo!)
Is he a British Blue shorthair?
<br>
<IMG SRC="star.gif" height=14 width=14 alt=" ">
<EM><A HREF="http://www.zmall.com/pet_talk/cat-faqs/medical-info.html">
Medical Information about Cats</A></EM>
(&quot;http://www.zmall.com/pet_talk/cat-faqs/medical-info.html&quot;)
<br>
Includes some information about diabetes in cats.
<br>
<a name="grinm"></a>
<IMG SRC="star.gif" height=14 width=14 alt=" ">
<EM>
<a href="http://ban.libertel.montreal.qc.ca/~dmckilli/cats/cats.htm">
The Grin Mouse tolerates cats!</a></em>
(&quot;http://ban.libertel.montreal.qc.ca/~dmckilli/cats/cats.htm&quot;)
&#0147;Dennis is huge: 7 kilos (15 pounds for the Unmetrified among you), which is down from 14 kilos when Stef rescued him from the humane society in
1994. He is the sweetest cat on the planet, and also one of the great masters of the Way of Purr. He is an emminently respectable cat of commerce, and
a staunch federalist out of concern for his investments (besides, he is as red and white as a Canadian flag!).&#0148;
<br>
<a name="dinc"></a>
<IMG SRC="star.gif" height=14 width=14 alt=" ">
<EM>
<A HREF="http://web.vet.cornell.edu/public/fhc/diabetes.htm">
Diabetes in Cats</a></em>
(&quot;http://web.vet.cornell.edu/public/fhc/diabetes.htm&quot;)
Prepared by the American Association of Feline Practitioners and the Cornell Feline Health Center, Cornell University, College of Veterinary Medicine, Ithaca, New York

<a name="raprice"></a>
<br>
<IMG SRC="new3.gif" ALT=" New! ">
<IMG SRC="fourstar.gif" ALT=" ">
<EM>
<a href="http://home.sprynet.com/interserv/raprice/diabetes.htm">
Feline Diabetes Web Site</a></em>
(&quot;http://home.sprynet.com/interserv/raprice/diabetes.htm&quot;)

&#0147;This site is maintained by a HUMAN physician who is the owner of a diabetic cat. Input is welcome (and needed!) from all
other cat owners and interested people who would like to see a comprehensive information center for helping feline diabetics.&#0148;

<a name="dogs"></a>
<h3>Dogs with Diabetes and Diabetes Information for dogs</h3>

<IMG SRC="star.gif" height=14 width=14 alt=" ">
<EM>
<a href="http://www.familyinternet.com/pet/12-2-12.htm">
Endocrine Problems: 
Insulin Resistance</A></EM>
(&quot;http://www.familyinternet.com/pet/12-2-12.htm&quot;)
<br>
<IMG SRC="star.gif" height=14 width=14 alt=" ">
<EM>
<a href="http://www.sai.com/orgs/nhdrl/diabetes.html">
Diabetes Treatment in Dogs</A></EM>
(&quot;http://www.sai.com/orgs/nhdrl/diabetes.html&quot;)
<br>
From the New Hampshire Doberman Rescue League 

<a name="ngs"></a>
<h3>Newsgroups: Diabetes Information</h3>

<IMG SRC="star.gif" height=14 width=14 alt=" ">
&#0147;I did stumble into a very useful newsgroup, <EM><a href = "news:misc.health.diabetes">misc.health.diabetes</a></em>.  At 
first I was reluctant to put out a post there lest I offend some diabetic 
who objects to discussion of cat diabetes in that venue as somehow 
demeaning humans. 

I went ahead anyway and was pleased to get a very cordial reception and 
many there have dealt with cat and dog diabetes.  A lot of the 
contributors are RN CDEs. Another newsgroup that I considered was alt.pets.cats.  When I went 
there, I discovered a preposterous number of posts written in baby talk 
ostensibly by the cats themselves -- with allusions to their mommies.  I 
decided that newsgroup didn't have much promise.&#0148;
&#151;
<em><A HREF="mailto:hhgreen@erols.com">Harvey H. Green</A></em> (owner of a diabetic cat, Oliver)

<a name="nodi"></a>
<h3>Veterinary and other Websites about pets (without diabetes information)</h3>

