<!--DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC
bgm-ok.htm
New Mar15,96
William W. Quick, MD
A proud product of zYf Productions
This file is safe for children. We endorse the SafeSurf concept-->
<HTML><HEAD>
<META http-equiv="PICS-Label" content='(PICS-1.0
"http://www.classify.org/safesurf/" l gen t for
"http://www.mdcc.com" r (SS~~000 1 SS~~100 1))'>
<title>Diabetes Monitor - Meter Performance</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body BGCOLOR="#DFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" ALINK="#0000FF" background="bd2.gif" VLINK="#FF0000">
<a name="top"></a><a name="_top"></a>
<table>
<td>
<IMG src="spinstar.gif" height=47 width=47 ALT=" " align=left>
</td><td>
<h2><strong>
<font SIZE="+3"><A HREF="index.htm" TARGET="_top">D</a></FONT><font color="#ff00cc">IABETES</font>
<FONT SIZE="+3"><a href="with.htm" TARGET="_top">M</a></FONT><font color="#ff00cc">ONITOR:</font>
<br>
<FONT face="Rockwell, Comic Sans MS, Arial">
How to Assure that your Blood Glucose
Meter is <nobr>Working Accurately</nobr>
</FONT>
</td><br>
</table>
<IMG SRC="red-line.gif" width=100% Height=2 ALT=" ">
</h2></strong>
<blockquote><P>
<font color="#ff00cc">
 . . . as of March 15, 1996
</font><P>
<center><IMG SRC="red-line.gif" Height=2 Width=50% ALT=" ">
</center>
<blockquote><P><blockquote><P>
<center>
<h3>Checking your own blood sugar level is essential in managing your diabetes.
<p>Appropriate decisions regarding changes in your medications, meal plan, and exercise program can be made
only if the results of your blood tests are accurate.
</h3></center>
</blockquote></blockquote>
<p>
<center>
<IMG SRC="red-line.gif" Height=2 Width=50% ALT=" ">
</center>
<P>
<FONT SIZE="+2"><strong>F</strong></font>irst, we
suggest that your technique for doing your blood sugar testing be double-checked with the Diabetes Nurse Educator
every time that you visit the Diabetes Center. Our Diabetes Nurse
Educators have been trained in all of the currently-available methods of self-monitoring
of blood sugar, and we have all the popular meters available
at the Center. Even if you forgot to bring in your own
meter at the time of your visit, we can double-check with you
 how well you're doing the testing, using one of our meters of the same model as yours.
<P>
<FONT SIZE="+2"><strong>A</strong></font>lso, we suggest that you bring in your own meter from home at least
<strong>once every three months</strong>
to check on its accuracy. (It's probably easier to just plan
to bring it
in on every visit.)
When you bring in your meter, several things will be done:
<ul>
<li>The proper technique for the use of your meter will be reviewed with you.
<li>A fingerstick blood sample will be obtained and blood glucose readings will
be checked between your meter and one (or more!) of our meters.
(We routinely recheck our meters' accuracy weekly, and more often if problems, and
we're pretty confident they're reading accurately!)
<li>Liquid control solutions are available for all meters. These solutions
can also be used to evaluate your meter's performance.
</ul>

<FONT SIZE="+2"><strong>T</strong></font>he results of the testing will be recorded in your chart, and you may have a copy
of the report if you wish. Information in this report will include:
<ol>
<li>Date and time of the testing.
<li>Name of the Diabetes Nurse who did helped you with the testing.
<li>Indiction about the meters used, including whether your blood
was used or a control solution, whether you or the Diabetes Nurse
did the testing, and the expected values of the control solutions, if they were used.
<li>Any remedial action taken for unexpected results.
</ol>
<FONT SIZE="+2"><strong>O</strong></font>ne final word of advice about your meter:
<strong>Re-read the manual.</strong> You'll probably be surprised to find something that you overlooked the last time you looked!


</blockquote>
<IMG SRC="red-line.gif" Height=2 Width=100% ALT=" ">
<P><center><em><a href="#top">Return to the beginning of this document</a></em></center>
