<HTML><HEAD>
<META http-equiv="PICS-Label" content='(PICS-1.0
"http://www.classify.org/safesurf/" l gen t for "http://www.mdcc.com" r
(SS~~000 1 SS~~100 1))'>
<title>Diabetes Monitor - Neuropathy</TITLE></HEAD>
<body BGCOLOR="#DFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" ALINK="#0000FF" background="bd2.gif" VLINK="#FF0000">
<a name="top"></a><a name="_top"></a>
<table>
<td>
<IMG src="spinstar.gif" height=47 width=47 ALT=" " align=left>
</td><td>
<h2><strong>
<font SIZE="+3"><A HREF="index.htm" TARGET="_top">D</a></FONT><font color="#ff00cc">IABETES</font>
<FONT SIZE="+3"><a href="with.htm" TARGET="_top">M</a></FONT><font color="#ff00cc">ONITOR:</font>
<br>
<FONT face="Rockwell, Comic Sans MS, Arial">Diabetic Neuropathy
</FONT>
</td><br>
</table>
<IMG SRC="red-line.gif" width=100% Height=2 ALT=" ">
</h2></strong>
<blockquote><P>
<font color="#ff00cc">
 . . . as of February 1, 1997
</font></blockquote><P>

<center>
<IMG SRC="red-line.gif" Height=2 Width=50% ALT=" ">
</center>
<blockquote><P><blockquote><P><center><h3>
Diabetes neuropathy (damage to the nerves) is probably permanent when it results in total anesthesia (loss of feeling) in the feet.
</h3></center></blockquote></blockquote>
<p><center>
<IMG SRC="red-line.gif" Height=2 Width=50% ALT=" ">
</center>
<blockquote><P>
Things to do:
<ul>
<li>Be sure the diagnosis is correct! (There are several treatable conditions that can also cause neuropathy). You should have an EMG/NCV study done, and some blood tests. Ask your diabetes specialist or neurologist if your personal physician isn't sure what to do.
<li>Be careful to protect your feet from injury. Any minor injury may allow infection to set in, which could lead to gangrene and amputation.
<li>Look at your feet (with your eyes, or someone else can look if it's difficult for you to do): <strong>every day!</strong> If new problems are seen, such as a blister or red spot, telephone your doctor's office promptly for advice; stay off your feet until you get other advice.
<li>Break in new shoes slowly, so that they don't accidentally cause blisters.
<li>Keep several pairs of shoes at work, or in the car, so you can rotate among them if your feet feel tired.
<li>Every patient with neuropathy resulting in anesthesia should be under the care of a podiatrist for routine foot care, such as trimming nails and calluses.
(In the U.S., Medicare will pay for this care every 60 days, if you have diabetes and are covered by Medicare health insurance.)
</ul>
Information about painful diabetic foot pain can be found at <em><a href="dm-feet.htm">Diabetes and Foot Pain</a></em>
<p>
More information about diabetic neuropathy can be found on the Internet at:
<blockquote><P>

<P>

<IMG SRC="star.gif" Height=14 Width=14 alt=" ">
<em><a href="http://www.ummed.edu:8000/dept/diabetes/handbook/chap12.htm#nerves">Nerves</a></em>
From the The Healing Handbook for Persons with Diabetes
(Univ. of Mass. Medical Center)
<br>

<IMG SRC="star.gif" Height=14 Width=14 alt=" ">
<em><a href="http://www.diabetes.ca/aboutdia/chronic.htm">
The Chronic Complications of Diabetes</a></em>
(includes Neuropathy and Foot Problems)
From the Canadian Diabetes Association
<br>

<IMG SRC="star.gif" Height=14 Width=14 alt=" ">
<em><a href="http://www.diabetes.org/ada/c70h.html">
Neuropathy And Nerve Damage</a></em>
From the American Diabetes Association
<br>
</blockquote>

<table width=80%><td align=right>
<em><a href="cv-wwq.htm">&#151; WWQ</a></em>
</td></table>

</blockquote>
<IMG SRC="red-line.gif" Height=2 Width=100% ALT=" ">
<P><center><em><a href="#top">Return to the beginning of this document</a></em></center>
