<a name="top"></a><a name="_top"></a>
<table>
<td>
<IMG src="spinstar.gif" height=47 width=47 ALT=" " align=left>
</td><td>
<h2><strong>
<font SIZE="+3"><A HREF="index.htm" TARGET="_top">D</a></FONT><font color="#ff00cc">IABETES</font>
<FONT SIZE="+3"><a href="with.htm" TARGET="_top">M</a></FONT><font color="#ff00cc">ONITOR:</font>
<br>
<FONT face="Rockwell, Comic Sans MS, Arial">Upcoming <nobr>Diabetes Medications</nobr></font>
</td><br>
</table>
<IMG SRC="red-line.gif" width=100% Height=2 ALT=" ">
</h2></strong>
<blockquote>
<P><font color="#ff00cc">
 . . . as of February 1, 1997
</font><P>
<a name="listing"></a>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="red-line.gif" ALT=" " Height=2 Width=50%>
<h3>Here&#0146;s some of what may be coming . . .
<p><em>

    <a href="#alc">acetyl-l-carnitine</a>
<br><a href="#diarg">diarginyl insulin</a>
<br><a href="#betarxp">encapsulated porcine islets</a>
<br><a href="#GLP-I">glucagon-like peptide I</a>
<br><a href="#anergix">IDDM-AnergiX</a>
<br><a href="#igf">insulin-like growth factor</a>
<br><a href="#npi">oral insulin</a>
<br><a href="#pimagedine">pimagedine</a>
<br><a href="#pramlintide">pramlintide</a>
<br><a href="#repagl">repaglinide</a>
<br><a href="#x14">X-14</a>
<br><a href="#zopol">zopolrestat</a>

</em></h3>

<IMG SRC="red-line.gif" ALT=" " Height=2 Width=50%>
</center>
<P>
<table width=95% cellpadding=6><td valign=top width=50%>
<a name="alc"></a>
<h2>acetyl-l-carnitine</h2><ul>
<LI><strong>Brand name in US: </strong>not stated
<LI><strong>Class</strong>: not stated
<LI><strong>For</strong>: diabetic neuropathy
<LI><strong>Route of Administration</strong>: not stated
<LI><strong>Action</strong>: acts as a precursor of a neurotransmitter, acetylcholine
<LI><strong>Manufacturer</strong>: Sigma-Tau, together with Hoffmann-La Roche
<LI><strong>Status</strong>: Phase II testing for diabetic neuropathy in US; currently marketed in Italy (as of April 1994)
<LI><strong>Source of Information</strong>: <u>British J Clinical <nobr>Pharmacology</u>,</nobr> Mar/Apr, 1994, Vol. 48 #2, page 94
</ul>
<center><em><a href="#listing">Return to the beginning of this listing</a></em></center>

<a name="dexff"></a>
<P>
<h2>dexfenfluramine (Redux&#153;)</h2>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>
<a href="redux.htm"><em>Now Available (in the USA): See separate page</em></a>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<a name="diarg"></a>
<h2>diarginyl insulin</h2><ul>
<LI><strong>Brand name in US: </strong>unstated
<LI><strong>Class</strong>: insulin analogue
<LI><strong>For</strong>: insulin-treated diabetes
<LI><strong>Route of Administration</strong>: unstated
<LI><strong>Action</strong>: same as insulin
<LI><strong>manufacturer</strong>: unstated
<LI><strong>Status</strong>: 
several years away from human trials
<LI><strong>Source of Information</strong>: 
<u>Diabetes <nobr>Self-Management</u>,</nobr>
July/August 1996
</ul>
<center><em><a href="#listing">Return to the beginning of this listing</a></em></center>

<a name="betarxp"></a>
<h2>encapsulated porcine islets</h2><ul>
<LI><strong>Brand name in US: </strong>BetaRx-P
<LI><strong>Class</strong>: pig islet cells
<LI><strong>For</strong>: 
Type I diabetic patients with kidney transplants; perhaps for Type I patients
with no immunosuppression.
<LI><strong>Route of Administration</strong>: transplant
<LI><strong>Action</strong>: same as human insulin
<LI><strong>manufacturer</strong>: VivoRx, Inc.
<LI><strong>Status</strong>: 
Has FDA approval for Phase I/II clinical trials
<LI><strong>Source of Information</strong>: 
Press Release, July 22, 1996, VivoRx,Inc (310) 264-7768</ul>
<center><em><a href="#listing">Return to the beginning of this listing</a></em></center>

<a name="amaryl"></a>
<P>
<h2>glimeprimide (Amaryl&#153;)</h2>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>
<a href="amaryl.htm"><em>Now Available (in the USA): See separate page</em></a>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<a name="GLP-I"></a>
<h2>Glucagon-like peptide I (GLP-I)</a></h2>
<ul>
<LI><strong>Brand name in US: </strong>unstated
<LI><strong>Class</strong>: endogenous incretin
<LI><strong>For</strong>: Type II diabetes
<LI><strong>Route of Administration</strong>: buccal tablet
(transmucosal absorption)
<LI><strong>Action</strong>: lowers blood sugar by suppressing glucagon secretion,
prolonging stomach emptying after meals,
and stimulating insulin release; might also decrease insulin resistance.
<LI><strong>Manufacturer</strong>:TheraTech
<LI><strong>Status</strong>: 
Human feasibility trial reported in <u>Diabetes <nobr>Care</u>.</nobr>
<LI><strong>Sources of Information</strong>: <u>Diabetes <nobr>Care</u>,</nobr> Vol 19, #8, August 1996
(address correspondence to Mark Gutniak, MD, PhD at
<em><A HREF="mailto:mark.gutniak@mailbox.swipnet.se">mark.gutniak@mailbox.swipnet.se</A></em>);
<u>Diabetes Wellness <nobr>Letter</u>,</nobr> Vol 2, #9, 1996.
</ul>
<center><em><a href="#listing">Return to the beginning of this listing</a></em></center>

<a name="anergix"></a>
<h2>IDDM-AnergiX&#153</h2>
<ul>
<LI><strong>Brand name in US: </strong>IDDM-AnergiX
<LI><strong>Class</strong>: T cell inactivator
<LI><strong>For</strong>: Type I diabetes
<LI><strong>Route of Administration</strong>: unstated
<LI><strong>Action</strong>:
inactivates the disease-related T cells in the immune system that are responsible for the disease.
<LI><strong>Manufacturer</strong>:
<IMG SRC="star.gif" Height=14 Width=14>
<a href="http://www.irnet.com"><em>Anergen</em></a>
<LI><strong>Status</strong>: preliminary data presented in an animal model of IDDM at the International Immunology and Diabetes Workshop, Rome Italy, November, 1995
<LI><strong>Source of Information</strong>:
<IMG SRC="star.gif" Height=14 Width=14>
<a href="http://keydet.sra.com">
<em> First! For the WEB,</em></a>
April 2, 1996
</ul>
<center><em><a href="#listing">Return to the beginning of this listing</a></em></center>

<a name="igf"></a>
<h2>insulin-like growth factor (IGF)</h2><ul>
<LI><strong>Brand name in US: </strong>unstated
<LI><strong>Class</strong>: peptide hormone
<LI><strong>For</strong>: Type I and II diabetes
<LI><strong>Route of Administration</strong>: subcutaneous
<LI><strong>Action</strong>: acute lowering of blood glucose and long-term improvement in
insulin sensitivity
<LI><strong>Manufacturer</strong>: Genentech
<LI><strong>Status</strong>: Phase II clinical trials underway in US
<LI><strong>Source of Information</strong>:
<u>Drug <nobr>Topics</u>,</nobr>
June 12, 1995
</ul>
<center><em><a href="#listing">Return to the beginning of this listing</a></em></center>

<A name="lispro"></a>
<h2>lispro insulin (Humalog&reg;)</h2>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>
<a href="lispro.htm"><em>Now Available (in the USA): See separate page</em></a>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<a name="npi"></a>
<h2>oral insulin</h2><ul>
<LI><strong>Brand name in US: </strong>unstated
<LI><strong>Class</strong>: synthetic &#0147;mini-protein&#0148; analogue of insulin
<LI><strong>For</strong>: insulin-treated diabetes
<LI><strong>Route of Administration</strong>: oral
<LI><strong>Action</strong>: same as insulin
<LI><strong>manufacturer</strong>: Johnson & Johnson
<LI><strong>Status</strong>: 
speculation based on success of other protein analogues
<LI><strong>Source of Information</strong>: 
Jerry Bishop, Staff Reporter, <u>Wall Street <nobr>Journal</u>,</nobr> July 1996</ul>
<center><em><a href="#listing">Return to the beginning of this listing</a></em></center>

</td><td valign=top width=50%>

<a name="pimagedine"></a>
<h2>pimagedine</h2><ul>
<LI><strong>Brand name in US: </strong>unstated
<LI><strong>Class</strong>: aminoguanidine
<LI><strong>For</strong>: Prevention of complications in Type I and Type II patients
<LI><strong>Route of Administration</strong>: unstated
<LI><strong>Action</strong>: in diabetic rats, and in <strong>in vitro</strong> studies,
pimagedine inhibits the formation of advanced glycosylation end-products (AGE's)
which occur when glucose attaches itself to proteins without the aid of enzymes.
The resulting cross-links between proteins may contribute to the development of
atherosclerosis, nerve damage, kidney failure, and blindness.
<LI><strong>manufacturer</strong>: Alteon, Inc.
<LI><strong>Status</strong>: Phase II clinical trials underway in US
<LI><strong>Sources of Information</strong>:
<u>Clinical <nobr>Diabetes</u>,</nobr>
July/August, 1995;
<u>Drug <nobr>Topics</u>,</nobr>
June 12, 1995; <u>Clinical <nobr>Diabetes</u>,</nobr> March/April, 1996
</ul>
<center><em><a href="#listing">Return to the beginning of this listing</a></em></center>

<a name="pramlintide"></a>
<h2>pramlintide</h2><ul>
<LI><strong>Brand name in US: </strong>unstated
<LI><strong>Class</strong>: unstated
<LI><strong>For</strong>: both Type I and Type II diabetes
<LI><strong>Route of Administration</strong>: injection
<LI><strong>Action</strong>: lowers blood sugar
<LI><strong>manufacturer</strong>: 
<br><IMG SRC="star.gif" height=14 width=14 alt=" ">
<A HREF="http://www.amylin.com/">
<EM>Amylin Pharmaceuticals, Inc.</EM></a>
<LI><strong>Status</strong>: Phase II clinical trials underway in US
<LI><strong>Sources of Information</strong>:
Press release:
<em><a href="http://www.amylin.com/pages/press/08079602.html">
Amylin Pharmaceuticals announces positive Phase II Clinical results in insulin using
Type II Diabetes</a></em>,
and e-mail from a subject in one of their studies, who writes:
&#0147;I have been part of a research project
with a new product call pramlintide. I started the study in June of 1995.
We inject ourselves before each meal with a specified dosage.
We started at 30 units, and now after a year we are administering 10 units (3 times a day,
or if we eat more frequently, then with each meal.)&#0148; [December 13, 1996]
</ul>
<center><em><a href="#listing">Return to the beginning of this listing</a></em></center>


<a name="repagl"></a>
</ul><h2>repaglinide</h2><ul>
<LI><strong>Brand name in US: </strong>NovoNorm
<LI><strong>Class</strong>: nonsulfonylurea oral hypoglycemic agent
<LI><strong>For</strong>: Type II Diabetes
<LI><strong>Route of Administration</strong>: oral
<LI><strong>Action</strong>: enhances insulin secretion; works differently than
sulfonylurea
<LI><strong>Manufacturer</strong>: Novo Nordisk
<LI><strong>Status</strong>: Phase III clinical trials underway in US; in final stages of clinical 
trials in Europe
<LI><strong>Source of Information</strong>:
<u>Drug <nobr>Topics</u>,</nobr>
June 12, 1995;
<u>Diabetes <nobr>Self-Management</u>,</nobr>
July/August 1996
</ul>
<center><em><a href="#listing">Return to the beginning of this listing</a></em></center>

<a name="tolres"></a>
<h2>tolrestat</h2><ul>
<LI><strong>Brand name in US: </strong>Alredase
<LI><strong>Class</strong>: aldose reductase inhibitor
<LI><strong>For</strong>: prevention/controlling diabetic complications
<LI><strong>Route of Administration</strong>: unstated
<LI><strong>Action</strong>: enzyme inhibition
<LI><strong>Manufacturer</strong>: Wyeth-Ayerst Laboratories
<LI><strong>Status</strong>: 
<em><a href="hx-9610.htm#tolwd">Apparently withdrawn
by manufacturer in October, 1996 as being ineffective?</a></em>
<LI><strong>Other drugs in same class</strong>: 
<a href="#zopol">zopolrestat</a>
<LI><strong>Source of Information</strong>:
<u>Drug <nobr>Topics</u>,</nobr>
June 12, 1995; local researcher, October, 1996
</ul>
<center><em><a href="#listing">Return to the beginning of this listing</a></em></center>

<a name="trogl"></a>
<h2>troglitazone (Rezulin)</h2>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>
<a href="rezulin.htm"><em>Now available (in the USA): See separate page</em></a>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<a name="x14"></a>
<h2>X-14</h2><ul>
<LI><strong>Brand name in US: </strong>unstated
<LI><strong>Class</strong>: insulin analog
<LI><strong>For</strong>: insulin-treated diabetes
<LI><strong>Route of Administration</strong>: subcutaneous (perhaps also IV? and/or IM?)
<LI><strong>Action</strong>: unstated
<LI><strong>Manufacturer</strong>: Novo Nordisk
<LI><strong>Status</strong>: Phase II clinical trials underway in US
<LI><strong>Source of Information</strong>:
<u>Drug <nobr>Topics</u>,</nobr>
June 12, 1995
</ul>
<center><em><a href="#listing">Return to the beginning of this listing</a></em></center>

<a name="zopol"></a>
<h2>zopolrestat</h2><ul>
<LI><strong>Brand name in US: </strong>unstated
<LI><strong>Class</strong>: aldose reductase inhibitor
<LI><strong>For</strong>: prevention/controlling diabetic complications
<LI><strong>Route of Administration</strong>: unstated
<LI><strong>Action</strong>: enzyme inhibition
<LI><strong>Manufacturer</strong>: Pfizer
<LI><strong>Status</strong>: Phase II/III clinical trials underway in US
<LI><strong>Other drugs in same class</strong>: 
<a href="#tolres">tolrestat</a>
<LI><strong>Source of Information</strong>:
<u>Drug <nobr>Topics</u>,</nobr>
June 12, 1995
</ul>
</td></table>

</blockquote>
